       ID that is used to specify the start point of the row area.  The  -bump

       does not recommend the use of this parameter because there can be prob-

       deltas are specified in relation to a block in R0 orientation (left  is
       applied  to  the  left edge of block oriented R0). For non-R0, the halo
       deltas are rotated/flipped according to the blocks's  orientation  (for
       block  oriented MY, the left halo delta specifies the width of the halo
       along the right side of the inst in the floorplan).

       <inst_name_list>}  format.  The names list option is used for instances
       only and NOT for group or hierarchical  instances.  Data_type:  string,

addIoFiller(21.15)                                          addIoFiller(21.15)



[1mName addIoFiller [22m- Adds I/O instances in the I/O box
[1mSyntax addIoFiller [22m[-help] -cell {<name_list>} [-fillAnyGap] [-fillerOrient R0
       | R90 | R180 | R270 | MX | MX90 | MY | MY90] [-from  <coord>]  [-prefix
       <prefix>]  [-side  {top  |  bottom | left | right}] [-to <coord>] [-row
       <rowNumber>] [-useSmallIoHeight] [-logic [-deriveConnectivity]]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information  for each addIoFiller parameter. For a detailed description
       of the command and all of its parameters,  use  the  man  command:  man
       addIoFiller  [1m-cell  {<name_list>}  [22mSpecifies  the  name list of the I/O
       filler cells to be added. Data_type: list, required [1m-deriveConnectivity[0m
       Derives  connectivity  for I/O fillers. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-fil-[0m
       [1mlAnyGap [22mForces the I/O filler instance into a gap even though  the  gap
       (clearance)  is  not  large enough. Default: If you do not specify this
       parameter, it does  not  force  a  filler  instance.  Data_type:  bool,
       optional  [1m-fillerOrient  R0 | R90 | R180 | R270 | MX | MX90 | MY | MY90[0m
       Specifies the orientation value of the  filler  cell.  The  orientation
       value  can  be  R0, R90, R180, R270, MX, MX90, MY, or MY90. Default: R0
       Data_type: string, optional [1m-from <coord> [22mSpecifies the starting offset
       from  the edge for adding fillers. The values are in micrometers. Note:
       The -from and -to parameters are intended to be  used  with  the  -side
       parameter to indicate a range. This command is applicable to peripheral
       I/O only; therefore, it is  only  one  dimensional.  Data_type:  float,
       optional  [1m-logic  [22mEnables the creation of I/O filler instances for non-
       physical I/O cells. The added IO fillers are  not  marked  as  physical
       only  cells.  They  are  saved  in  netlist  if  user does saveNetlist.
       Data_type: bool, optional [1m-prefix <prefix> [22mSpecifies  the  prefix  name
       for  the  new  I/O filler instances. Default: FILLER Data_type: string,
       optional [1m-row  <rowNumber>  [22mSpecifies  the  row  number  for  inserting
       fillers  in a multiple I/O row design. Minimum: 0 Maximum: 1 Data_type:
       int, optional [1m-side {top | bottom | left | right} [22mSpecifies the side as
       top  side,  bottom  side,  left  side,  and  right side of the I/O box.
       Default: If you do not specify this parameter, all sides are specified.
       Data_type:  string,  optional  [1m-to  <coord> [22mSpecifies the ending offset
       from the edge for adding fillers. The values are in micrometers.  Note:
       The  -from  and  -to  parameters are intended to be used with the -side
       parameter to indicate a range. This command is applicable to peripheral
       I/O  only;  therefore,  it  is  only one dimensional. Data_type: float,
       optional [1m-useSmallIoHeight [22mSpecifies that the  filler  cell  should  be
       inserted  between  I/O pads only when the smallest I/O pad has the same
       height as the height of the filler cell.  For  example,  consider  that
       there are I/O pads A, B, C, D, and E. Out of these, A, B, and E are the
       same height, and C and D have a height double that  of  A,  B,  and  E.
       Assume that you want to insert an I/O filler cell F, which has the same
       height as A, B, and E. If you  do  not  specify  the  -useSmallIoHeight
       parameter,  the cell F will be inserted between A and B, B and C, C and
       D, and D and E. However, if you specify the  -useSmallIoHeight  parame-
       ter, the cell F will be inserted between A and B, B and C, and D and E.
       The cell will not be inserted between C and D, because  both  C  and  D
       have a height different from F. Data_type: bool, optional
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

addMetalFill(21.15)                                        addMetalFill(21.15)



[1mName  addMetalFill [22m- Inserts inactive metal into a placed and routed design to
       achieve the metal density within the range required by a specific manu-
       facturing process
[1mSyntax  addMetalFill  [22m[-help]  [-area  <x1> <y1> <x2> <y2>] [-extraCriticalNet
       <netNameList>] [-excludeVia  <via_list>]  [-ignoreLEFDensity]  [-itera-
       tionNameList {<list_of_iteration_names>}] [-keepSquareFloating] [-layer
       <layerName>  |  {<list_of_layer_names>}]  [-onCell  [-std]]  [-pg_fill]
       [-removeFloatingFill]  [-slackThreshold <slack>] [-snap] [-squareShape]
       | [-net {<netNameList>} [-genViaOnly] [-mesh  |  -meshOnly]]  [-stagger
       {on | off | diag}] [-timingAware {on | off | sta}] [-useNonDefaultSpac-
       ing]
[1mAdding Metal Fill in Multi-Threading Mode[0m
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information  for  each  addMetalFill parameter. For a detailed
       description of the command and all its parameters, use the man command:
       man  addMetalFill.  [1m-area  <x1 y1 x2 y2> [22mSpecifies a set of coordinates
       within which to add metal fill. This command reduces the fill  area  by
       half  of  the  maximum design rule spacing defined in the LEF file. For
       example, if you specify -area 0 0 100 100, and the maximum spacing rule
       in  the LEF file is 2.5 , addMetalFill adds fill in the following area:
       1.25 1.25 98.75 98.75. Default: If you do not specify  this  parameter,
       adds  metal  fill to the entire design area (taking the maximum spacing
       rule into account).
[1mBehavior of addMetalFill -area with external metal density When metal fill  is[0m
       [1madded  to  a block design the external metal density provides a density[0m
       [1massumption to addMetalFill. The external density is used only for  den-[0m
       [1msity  calculation  purposes and no fill shapes are added outside of the[0m
       [1mdesign area. When the -area parameter is not  specified,  the  external[0m
       [1mdensity  value  is  not  used. In this case, the addMetalFill window is[0m
       [1mpushed back if it extends outside the design area, as shown in the fig-[0m
       [1mure  below.  (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Com-[0m
       [1mmand Reference - Release 21.1 manual.)  (<Image>  To  view  the  image,[0m
       [1mrefer  to the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 manual.) If[0m
       [1mthe -area parameter is specified and is larger  than  the  design  size[0m
       [1mthen  addMetalFill  windows  extend  outside the block area and use the[0m
       [1mexternal density value (see setMetalFill  for  external  density  value[0m
       [1mspecification)  for  that  area.  If  external density is less than the[0m
       [1mspecified preferred density, it is more  likely  that  shapes  will  be[0m
       [1madded  to  the  area. If external density is greater than the preferred[0m
       [1mdensity it is less likely that shapes will be added  (shapes  are  only[0m
       [1madded  within  the  design  boundary). Note: Windows outside the design[0m
       [1mboundary are ignored. -extraCriticalNet <netNameList> [22mSpecifies a  list
       of  extra critical nets for adding metal fill in the timing-aware mode.
       If you are using a third-party tool for sign-off static timing analysis
       (STA),  your  list  of  timing critical nets may be different from that
       generated by report_timing in Innovus/Tempus. In such a case,  you  can
       use -extraCriticalNet in one of the following ways:

[1mName addNet [22m- Adds a net to the design
[1mSyntax  addNet  [22m[-help] <netName> [-bus <startID>:<endID>] [-moduleBased <ver-
       ilogModule>] [-power | -ground ]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information for each addNet parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       addNet [1m-bus <startID>:<endID> [22mSpecifies the bit range for bus nets. The
       <startID> and <endID> indicate the first and last bits on the bus.  You
       must  separate the start and end IDs with a colon (:). If the specified
       bus does not exist, tool will create a bussed Verilog net. If the spec-
       ified  bus already exists, tool will do bus net resizing. The specified
       bus bit range must be adjacent to the first or last bit of the existing
       bus.  Also,  it  must  have  the  same ascending or descending order as
       existing bus. Note: PG bus net is not supported   [1m-ground [22mAdds a ground
       net.  [1m-moduleBased  <verilogModule>  [22mAdds  the new net to the specified
       verilog module. If the module name  contains  special  characters,  you
       need  to  start  the  module name with a backslash '' and end it with a
       space. [1m<netName> [22mSpecifies the net to add. If  the  net  name  contains
       special  characters,  you need to start the part of the net name, which
       contains special characters, with a backslash ''  and  end  it  with  a
       space. Note: You must specify <netName> before you specify other param-
       eters. The software issues an error message if you do not  specify  the
       <netName> first. [1m-power [22mAdds a power net.

[1mName  addPowerSwitch [22m- The addPowerSwitch command supports five type of cells:
       switch cells, filler cells, corner cells (for the ring style only), and
       buffer cells
[1mSyntax  addPowerSwitch  [22m[-help]  [-1801PowerSwitchRuleName  <string>] {-column
       -powerDomain -enablePinIn  {<listOfPins>}  -enableNetIn  {<listOfNets>}
       -enablePinOut  {<listOfPins>}  -enableNetOut  {<netBaseName>}  -global-
       SwitchCellName <cell_syntax> -globalBufferCellName <cell_syntax> -hori-
       zontalPitch  <float>  [-area  {<x1  y1 x2 y2>}] [-switchModuleInstance]

       [-topOffset   <value>]   [-power  {(<VDD:VDD1  VDD2>...)...}]  [-ground
       {(<GND:GND1  GND2>...)...}]  [-incremental]   [-width   <length_in_um>]
       [-height <length_in_um>] [-orientation <orientation_syntax>] [-connect-
       BottomSwitchEnablePins {LtoR | RtoL} [-parallelEnable]  [-globalPattern
       <pattern_syntax>] [-acknowledgeTreeCell <cell_name>] [-acknowledgeTree-
       HierInstance <hier_instance>] [-backToBackChain {LtoR | RtoL}]  [-loop-
       backAtEnd]     [-maxChainDepth     <integer>]    [-maxDistance    <dis-
       tance_in_microns>] [-maxFanout <integer>] [-snapToNearest]  [-skipRows]

addRepeaterByRule(21.15)                              addRepeaterByRule(21.15)



[1mName  addRepeaterByRule [22m- Inserts buffers and/or inverters to nets, as defined
       in a rule file
[1mSyntax addRepeaterByRule  [22m[-help]  [-copyNetAttribute]  [-excNet  <excludeNet-
       File>]  [-netMapping <fileName>] [-outDir <directoryName>] [-preRoute |
       -postRoute | -alongRoute] [-reportIgnoredNets <ignoredNetFile>]  [-rule
       <fileName>] [-selNet <selNetFile>] [-template]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information  for  each  addRepeaterByRule  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description  of  the  command  and  all  of  its  parameters,  use  man
       addRepeaterByRule. [1m-alongRoute  [22mAllows  repeater  insertion  along  the
       route. The database should be global-routed with preRoute RC extraction
       before calling this option. Note: Run refinePlace and ecoRoute  if  you
       specify this parameter. [1m-copyNetAttribute [22mWhen this parameter is speci-
       fied, the net attributes set on the original nets  are  copied  to  the
       nets inserted by this command. [1m-excNet <fileName> [22mSpecifies a file that
       contains the names of hierarchical nets to exclude from rule  violation
       repair.  If  a  net  appears in the files specified by both -excNet and
       -selNet, it is excluded from rule violation repair. [1m-netMapping  <file-[0m
       [1mName> [22mWhen specified, generates a file that maps the original net names
       to the nets inserted by this command. An example of the file format  is
       provided  below.  In  this  example,  netA  is  split  into  two  nets;
       FE_new_net1_netA  and  FE_new_net2_netA.  netA  FE_new_net1_netA   netA
       FE_new_net2_netA  If,  in the next iteration, FE_new_net1_netA is split
       again,  the   file   would   contain   the   following:FE_new_net1_netA
       FE_new_net1_FE_new_net1_netA                           FE_new_net1_netA
       FE_new_net2_FE_new_net1_netA  [1m-outDir  <directoryName>  [22mSpecifies   the
       directory where the software writes detailed failure reason report that
       is generated when this command runs. By  default,  the  failure  reason
       report  is dumped in the timingReports/ARRFailureReason/<design> direc-
       tory.  For  example,   timingReports/ARRFailureReason/<design>.arr.pre-
       Route.rpt.gz  Default:  timingReports [1m-postRoute [22mAllows repeater inser-
       tion along the route.  The  database  should  be  detailed-routed  with
       detailed RC extraction before calling this option. Preserves routing so
       that changes are minimized. Note: Run refinePlace and ecoRoute  if  you
       specify  this  parameter. [1m-preRoute [22mAllows repeater insertion with dif-
       ferent routing topologies. The database should  be  global-routed  with
       preRoute  RC extraction before calling this option. When this parameter
       is specified, the software explores different typologies  to  optimally
       insert  repeaters. [1m-reportIgnoredNets <fileName> [22mReports the nets where
       no buffers were inserted and the reason the nets  were  ignored.  [1m-rule[0m
       [1m<fileName>     [22mSpecifies a file you create that should list the buffers
       and inverters and the length and capacitance rules for  inserting  each
       of  them.  Only  buffers  and  inverters  included in the rule file are
       inserted. [1m-selNet <fileName> [22mSpecifies a file that contains  the  names
       of  hierarchical  nets  considered by this command. If a net appears in
       the files specified by both -excNet and -selNet , it is  excluded  from
       rule  violation  repair.  [1m-template  [22mWrites a template rule file. Note:
       When the -template parameter is specified, the software does not  honor
       any other parameters for this command.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

       blocks.  A  block  name  must be an instance name and not a cell master
       name. The specified blocks should be separated by a space. Note: A halo
       is not allowed on std-cells (cells with CLASS CORE SITE) and is written
       out as ROUTEHALO in DEF. A design halo is written out as a  DEF  design

       ponent LITHOHALO property. Data_type: list, required  [1m-bottom  <bottom-[0m
       [1mLayer>  [22mSpecifies  the  bottom  layer  for the routing halo. Note: Even
       though the -bottom, -space, and -top parameters  are  optional,  it  is
       important  to specify all of them together. Data_type: string, required
       [1m-cell <cellNameList> [22mSpecifies that the routing halo should be added to
       all  insts  of  the  specified  cell  names.  Data_type: list, required
       [1m-designHalo [22mSpecifies that the routing  halo  should  be  added  inside
       design  boundary.  Note:  The -designHalo parameter cannot be specified
       with the -lithoHalo parameter. These parameters are mutually exclusive.
       Data_type:  bool,  required  [1m-help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description that
       includes the type  and  default  information  for  each  addRoutingHalo

       parameters, use the man command: man  addRoutingHalo  [1m-inst  <instance-[0m

       instance. This parameter can be useful for adding halo for  I/O  cells.

       addSdpObject.    [1m-emptyRow   <instance_name>   [22mInserts   empty   row(s)
       above/below the specified instance based on the justifyBy constraint of
       the  group to which the instance belongs. The empty row(s) are inserted
       across all SDP groups. The number of rows to be inserted  is  specified
       by the -numRow parameter. If -numRow is not specified, one empty row is
       inserted by default. Note: The core boundary will be extended to accom-
       modate  the newly added rows if the current core box is not big enough.
       (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference
       -  Release  21.1 manual.) [1m-numRow <value> [22mIndicates the number of empty
       rows to be inserted. [1m-obstruct <group_name_list>  [22mCreates  a  placement
       blockage  over  the specified SDP group(s). (<Image> To view the image,
       refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 manual.)

       SizeBlockage  [1m-isResizeable  [22mSpecifies  that  the  size blockage can be
       resized, however alignment and the minimum space between the objects in
       the blockage area will be maintained during floorplan resize. When this
       options is specified, the resize line can go through size blockage. But
       it  can  not  turn direction inside blockage. The benefit of using this
       option is if objects (for example,  macros)  under  size  blockage  are
       aligned  before  calling  resizeFloorplan, they will stay aligned after
       the command. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-name  <blockageName>  [22mSpecifies

[1mName  addSpareInstance [22m- Specifies a file that lists spare cells to add to the
       netlist
[1mSyntax addSpareInstance [22m[-help] [-async <netName:terminalList>  [<netName:ter-
       minalList>
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information  for  each  addSpareInstance  parameter.  For  a   detailed
       description  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man com-
       mand: man  addSpareInstance.  [1m-async  <netName:terminalList>  [22mSpecifies
       which  net(s)  to tie off the async pin(s). Default: async pins will be

[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default

       Name/instancePin  .  Each  line  in the file contains one instance pin.

       [1mfalse}  [22mAdds tie-off cells to all power domains that have library bind-
       ing containing the specified tie-off cell(s). Default: false  [1m-postMask[0m
       [1m{true  | false} [22mInsert tie cells in post mask flow. Instructs the soft-
       ware to reuse existing tie cells to  tie  off  a  newly  created  spare
       instance  in  the  design  instead  of  adding  or  deleting tie cells.
       Searches for input pins that are tied to logical 1  or  logical  0  and
       attempts  to  tie them off to tie high or tie low cells. Default: false

add_clock_tree_source_group_roots(21.15a)dd_clock_tree_source_group_roots(21.15)



[1mName  add_clock_tree_source_group_roots  [22m- This command updates the design and
       clock tree specification to create a multiple-tree source  group  below
       the specified driving root pin
[1mSyntax  add_clock_tree_source_group_roots  [22m[-help]  -cell <driverCell> [-loca-
       tions  {{x1  y1}  {x2  y2}...}]  -name  <sourceGroupName>  -pin  <root-
       Pin>[-grid  {columns rows} [[-adjust_grid_for_aspect_ratio] [-grid_rect
       {lx  ly  ux  uy}]  [-grid_search_area  {width  height}]   [-grid_exclu-
       sion_rects {{lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1} {lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2}...}]]]
[1mParameters  -help           [22mOutputs a brief description that includes type and
       default information for each add_clock_tree_source_group_roots  parame-
       ter.  For  a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
       ters,  use  the  man  command:  man  add_clock_tree_source_group_roots.
       [1m-adjust_grid_for_aspect_ratio  When  specified, exchanges rows and col-[0m
       [1mumns to match the aspect ratio. -cell <driverCell> [22mSpecifies the buffer
       cell  to  use for new source group # roots (libCell/ptnCell). This is a
       required parameter. [1m-grid {columns rows} [22mSpecifies  a  grid  of  target
       locations.  By default, the command attempts to create a full grid con-
       sisting of columns and rows. However, if a particular grid target point
       falls  within  an exclusion rectangle, specified using the -grid_exclu-
       sion_rects parameter, then that grid point  will  be  skipped.  If  the
       -adjust_grid_for_aspect_ratio  parameter  is specified, the columns and
       rows will be swapped if doing so better matches the aspect ratio of the
       grid  rectangle  area. Note: The -grid and -locations parameters can be
       used together. For example, you can specify a grid, and then use -loca-
       tions  to  add  a few additional taps in specific floor-plan locations.
       [1m-grid_exclusion_rects {{lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1} {lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2}...} [22mProvides
       the  coordinates  of  rectangular  areas that should not contain source
       group roots. Any grids that fall within the exclusion rectangle will be
       ignored.  [1m-grid_rect  {lx  ly  ux  uy} [22mSpecifies the area that the grid
       should cover. This parameter provides the overall rectangle intended to
       be  driven  by  the  taps  requested by the -grid parameter. Note: This
       parameter does not specify the bounding box of the grid taps. Basically
       the  overall  -grid_rect rectangle is cut up into m x n smaller rectan-
       gles, and a tap is targeted at the center of each smaller rectangle. to
       understand  more clearly, consider the below example. If you have -grid
       {2 2} and -grid_rect {0 0 100 100}, the corresponding target  locations
       will  be  {{25  25} {25 75} {75 25} {75 75}}. This is different than if
       the -grid_rect were the bounding box of tap locations, in which case it
       would  be  {{0 0} {0 100} {100 0} {100 100}}). [1m-grid_search_area {width[0m
       [1mheight} [22mSpecifies the size of the search area around each  grid  point.
       [1m-locations {{x1 y1} {x2 y2}...} [22mSpecifies a list of (x,y) locations for
       the new roots that are to be created. The specified roots are  inserted
       at  the  nearest  legal  location. Note: This parameter takes a list of
       points, not rectangles. A specified point will be taken as a tap target
       location,  and the software will search for the nearest legal location.
       If the -grid_search_area {width height}  parameter  is  specified,  the
       search  will be limited to the points specified using the -grid parame-
       ter and not points specified using the -locations parameter. If  it  is
       not  specified,  the  software  will  search as far as needed to find a
       legal location for a tap. If a legal location cannot be  found,  either
       within the specified search area, or anywhere in the floorplan, the tap
       will be added at the target location and not legalized. If all taps can
       be  inserted  at  legal  locations,  they will be set to locked for CTS
       placement status. If one or more taps cannot be legalized, the  command
       will print a warning and all taps will be left in simple placed status.
       Note: The behavior when a tap cannot be legalized, and for whether taps
       are locked applies to all taps created by this command - from the -grid
       and/or -locations parameters. [1m-name <prefix> [22mSpecifies the name of  the
       source  group  to  be created for the roots. The name should be unique.
       The multi-tap roots will be named using this string as  a  prefix.  For
       example, sourceGroupName_0, sourceGroupName_1..sourceGroupName_n. Note:

       cal_edge_endcap {<cell_name>}
[1mParameters  -bottom_edge_endcap  {<cell_name>}  [22mSpecifies the CA-break end cap

       vertical direction.  [1m-power_domain  <power_domain_name>  [22mSpecifies  the
       power  domain for which CA-break filler cells are to be inserted. Note:
       If the -power_domain option is used, the offset value is applied to the
       specified power domain. However, if the -power domain is not specified,
       the offset value is applied to all available power domains. To use dif-
       ferent  offset  value  for  a  specific power domain, you first need to
       delete the CA fillers from the power domain if it is already filled and
       then  reinsert  CA  filler  to  the power domain with the target offset
       value. [1m-prefix <prefix_name> [22mSpecifies the prefix for decomp cells.  If
       this  option  is specified, the user-specified prefix is applied to all
       inserted decomp fillers, else the default prefix name is  used.  [1m-stepx[0m

       [1mcal_edge_endcap  {<cell_name>} [22mSpecifies CA-break end cap cell inserted
       at the left and right edges as end caps.

[1mName add_obj_on_bump [22m- Adds shapes on the TSV bumps
[1mSyntax   add_obj_on_bump   [22m[-help]  {{-cell  <bump_cell_name>  |  -selected  |
       -feedthru } {-relative_pin_layer <pin_layer_name> | -rect {x1 y1 x2 y2}
       |   -polygon   {{x1   y1}  {x2  y2}...}}}  [-check_only  <bump_name>  |
       -write_script  <filename>]  {[-layer  <layer>+]   [-placement_blockage]
       [-routing_blockage <layer>+] [-physical_pin <layer>+]} [-layer <layer>+
       [-check_only  <bump_name>]  [-incremental]]  [-feedthru  [-cdl_map_file
       <cdl_map_file_name>]]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mPrints  a  brief description of the add_obj_on_bump command
       usage. For a detailed description of the command, use the man  command:
       man  add_obj_on_bump  [1m-cdl_map_file  <cdl_map_file_name>  [22mSpecifies the
       output cdl map file for LVS. [1m-cell <bump_cell_name> [22mSpecifies the  name
       of  the  bump  cell  on  which  the  shape  is to be added. [1m-check_only[0m
       [1m<bump_name> [22mChecks if there is a shape on the specified bump  and  out-
       puts  a  report  file.  The  -check_only  option  cannot  be  used with
       -write_script. Note: The -check_only  option  can  be  used  only  when
       -layer  is  specified.  [1m-feedthru [22mAdds shapes on the bump that contains
       the TSV layer and whose net is a  feedthrough  net.  [1m-incremental  [22mAdds
       shapes  in  the incremental mode. It deletes the shapes without a bump,
       and adds new shapes on  the  bumps  without  shapes.  The  -incremental
       parameter  only  checks  the shapes on the same layer. In the following
       sequence of commands, the first command is  add_obj_on_bump  -layer  M1
       and  the  second  command is add_obj_on_bump -layer M2 -incremental. In
       these  commands,  the  layers  specified  are   different.   Therefore,
       add_obj_on_bump  will  not  delete previously added shapes on M1. Also,
       the result of the command add_obj_on_bump -layer M2 -incremental is the
       same   as   add_obj_on_bump   -layer  M2.  >add_obj_on_bump  -layer  M1
       >add_obj_on_bump -layer M2 -incremental Note: The  -incremental  option
       can  be  used  only when -layer is specified. [1m-layer <layer>+ [22mSpecifies
       the layer(s) on which  new  shapes  are  to  be  added.  Polygons  with
       non-45-degree edges are supported. [1m-placement_blockage [22mAdds a placement
       blockage on bumps. Only  orthogonal  polygons  are  supported.  [1m-physi-[0m
       [1mcal_pin  <layer>+ [22mSpecifies the layer(s) on which to add physical pins.
       For a single-pin bump, the name of the physical pin is same as that  of
       the  target bump. For a multiple-pin bump, the name of the physical pin
       is same as that of the bump pin on the  same  layer.  If  no  bump  pin
       exists  on  the  layer  specified for adding the physical pin, the tool
       chooses the name of any of the pins on the target bump as the pin  name
       of  the  physical pin. Polygons with non-45-degree edges are supported.
       [1m-polygon {{x1 y1} {x2 y2}... [22mSpecifies the point list of the polygon to
       add  shapes.  The  center  of the specified polygon bounding box aligns
       with the center of the specified bump cell. [1m-rect {x1 y1 x2 y2}  [22mSpeci-
       fies  the  rectangle  to  add shapes. The center of specified rectangle
       aligns with the center of the specified bump cell.  [1m-relative_pin_layer[0m
       [1m<pin_layer_name> [22mSpecifies the pin layer of the pin shape of the speci-
       fied bump. Adds shapes based on the specified pin shape of the bump. If
       the  -relative_pin_layer  option is specified while adding objects, the
       shape of the added object is same as the shape  of  the  relative  pin.
       (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference
       -  Release  21.1  manual.)  [1m-routing_blockage  <layer>+  [22mSpecifies  the
       layer(s)  on  which  to add routing blockages on bumps. Only orthogonal
       polygons are supported. [1m-selected  [22mAdds shapes on  the  selected  bump.
       [1m-write_script  <filename>  [22mSpecifies the file name to dump a Tcl script
       for adding objects on bumps. If this option is specified, the tool will
       not  add  objects on bumps directly. The -write_script option cannot be
       used with -check_only.

       default,  the  add_tracks command adjust the pitch to what it considers
       best. The -honor_pitch parameter forces add_tracks  to  use  the  layer
       pitch  value  specified  in the LEF or OA technology file. If the layer
       pitch specified in the LEF file is smaller than the minimum line-to-via
       pitch,  the pitch is reset to the minimum line-to-via pitch and a warn-
       ing message is displayed in the log file. Note: The -honor_pitch param-
       eter  cannot  be  used  with  any  of  the options setting pitch values
       directly (-pitches, -pitch_pattern,  -width_pitch_pattern).  Data_type:
       bool,  optional  [1m-keep_default_width [22mKeeps user specified default width
       between routing tracks. Note:  This  enables  the  interoperability  of

       -useUserGrid, -skip_row, and -layer parameters Note: The  alignPtnClone
       command  supports  advanced  node  fully  abutted designs. It moves the
       clone partition for aligning with the master with all  allowed  routing
       tracks  by  default.  It  snaps clones such that the pins are never off
       grid. Consequently, the -snap,  -track,  -useUserGrid,  -skip_row,  and
       -layer  parameters  are  obsolete. Even though the use of snap, -track,
       -useUserGrid, -skip_row, and -layer parameters  is  supported  in  this
       release  using  the -stripeOffset parameter for backward compatibility,
       the -stripeOffset parameter itself is obsolete and will be removed in a
       future  release.  To  avoid  warnings  and to ensure compatibility with
       future releases, remove  the  obsolete  parameters  from  your  script.
       Data_type:  bool, optional [1m-symmetricOrientation [22mChecks the orientation
       between each pair of partitions and fixes the symmet<standard input>:18: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

       optimum  symmetric  orientation  of  clones.  Note: If Innovus suggests

       parameter can find orientations based upon  nested  hierarchy.  If  the
       alignPtnClone  command  finds no clone connectivity, it can reports the

[1mName all_registers[0m
[1mSyntax  all_registers  [22m[help]  [-clock  {<clock_list>}]  [-cells] [-rise_clock
       {<clock_list>}] [-fall_clock {<clock_list>}] [-flops | -edge_triggered]
       [-no_hierarchy] [-latches | -level_sensitive] [-macros] [-master_slave]
       [-data_pins]      [-clock_pins]      [-output_pins]       [-async_pins]
       [-slave_clock_pins]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mPrints out the command usage. [1m-async_pins [22mReturns a collec-
       tion of async preset or clear pins.  [1m-cells  [22mCreates  a  collection  of
       cells.  This is the default option. [1m-clock {<clock_list>} [22mSpecifies the
       name of a clock or a list of clocks. The all_registers command  creates
       a  collection  of  registers  clocked  by  the  specified <clock_list>.
       [1m-clock_pins [22mReturns a collection of register clock pins.  You  can  use
       other  parameters to further filter this collection. [1m-data_pins [22mReturns
       a collection of register data input pins. You can use other  parameters
       to further filter this collection. [1m-fall_clock {<clock_list>} [22mSpecifies
       the name of a clock or a list of clocks. The all_registers command cre-
       ates a collection of registers opened by the falling edge of the clocks
       specified in the <clock_list>. [1m-flops | -edge_triggered [22mReturns a  col-
       lection  of  edge-triggered  sequential  instances. Both the -flops and
       -edge_triggered options return the same collection. The  -flops  option
       is  provided  for  backward  compatibility. [1m-latches | -level_sensitive[0m
       Returns a collection  of  level-sensitive  sequential  instances.  Both
       -latches  and  -level_sensitive options return the same collection. The
       -latches option is provided for backward compatibility. [1m-macros [22mReturns
       sequential  instances  that  are  neither flip-flops nor latches. [1m-mas-[0m
       [1mter_slave  [22mReturns  a  collection  of  master-slave   register   cells.
       [1m-no_hierarchy  [22mSearches the current instance only; does not descend the
       hierarchy. [1m-output_pins [22mReturns a collection of register  output  pins.
       [1m-rise_clock  {<clock_list>}  [22mSpecifies the name of a clock or a list of
       clocks. The all_registers command creates  a  collection  of  registers
       opened  by the rising edge of the clocks specified in the <clock_list>.
       [1m-slave_clock_pins [22mReturns a collection of slave clock pins of the  mas-
       ter-slave   registers.   You  can  specify  the  slave  clock  pins  as
       clocked_on_also in the library.

       effective resistance for all instances of  the  specified  master  cell
       name.  The  -cell  parameter improves the usability of effective resis-
       tance calculation by allowing you to specify only the cell name of  the
       instances  you want to analyze. You can specify multiple cells for per-
       forming effective resistance analysis of multiple cells simultaneously.
       [1m-domain  <domainName> [22mSpecifies the domain name that is to be analyzed.
       [1m-domain_threshold<value> [22mSpecifies the minimum allowed effective resis-
       tance  (effective resistance sum of each net) to instance. For specific
       instance list analysis, the instances below the threshold value will be
       reported as PASS, while the instances above the threshold value will be
       reported as FAIL. For full  chip  analysis,  the  instances  below  the
       threshold  value will not be reported in the domain report. The default
       value is 0. [1m-exclude_list_file <filename> [22mSpecifies the name of a  file
       containing a list of cells or instances that will not be processed dur-
       ing the resistance analysis flow. The specified cells/instances will be
       ignored from report generation.

[1mName assembleDesign [22m- Brings back specified block data to the top-level design
       for chip assembly
[1mSyntax assembleDesign [22m[-help] [-keepPGPinGeometry] [-keep_block_halo]  [-skip-

       -fplan | -noDefMerge ] [-keepPinGeometry]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and

       and assembly of blocks with digital content. The -blockCell option  can
       be  used  to  manually force blocks to be assembled, and -except_blocks
       option can be used to exclude cells from being assembled  as  it  over-
       rides  to  the default list of blocks to be assembled. Data_type: bool,
       optional [1m-block  <blockLib>  <blockCell>  <blockView>    [22mSpecifies  the
       block-level  library,  cell,  and  view names respectively for a design
       that was saved into an OpenAccess database. This parameter is used when
       bringing back block data for the partition from an OpenAccess database.
       Note: If you specify more than  one  block-level  design,  specify  the

       TDSP_CORE ptnView1 -block libForOA TDSP_ARB ptnView1 Data_type: string,
       optional  [1m-blockCell   <b><lockCell>  [22mSpecifies  the  cell name for the

[1mParameters -align [22mIf you specify this option, each top I/O pin will be aligned
       with one of the instance pins with which it is connected. The  instance
       pin  with  which  the I/O pin is aligned is the one whose distance from
       its nearest edge is shortest among all the instance pins  connected  to
       the  top I/O pin. Default: If you do not specify this option, the loca-
       tion of the top pin is based on the average  of  the  distance  of  all
       instance  pins  (that  are  connected  to  the  top I/O pin) from their
       respective nearest edges. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-autoBusGroup [22mSpec-

       trigger the clock net markings prior to  running  attachIOBuffer,  with
       the  timeDesign  command. To query whether a given clock net is marked,
       use dbIsNetClock <netName>. [1m-excNetFile <excNetFileName> [22mSpecifies  the
       file that contains the names of nets to exclude from the buffer attach-
       ment operation. [1m-in <cellNameList> [22mSpecifies the cell name or a list of
       cell  names  of  the  input  (-in)  buffer. If the specified cell is an
       inverter, then the attachIOBuffer command  inserts  an  inverter  pair.
       Note: If the -in and -out parameters are specified together, both input
       and output pins will be attached buffers/inverters.  If  only  -in  (or
       -out)  option  is  specified,  then only input (or output) pins will be
       attached buffer. If a list of cells is specified, it  will  insert  the
       first  CPF  compliant  cell.  It  is  recommended  to  give non-AO buf-
       fers/inverters before AO buffers/inverters in  the  list.  [1m-out  <cell-[0m
       [1mNameList> [22mSpecifies the cell name or a list of cell names of the output
       (-out) buffer. If the specified cell is an  inverter,  then  the  atta-
       chIOBuffer  command inserts an inverter pair. Note: If the -in and -out
       parameters are specified together, both input and output pins  will  be
       attached  buffers/inverters. If only -in (or -out) option is specified,
       then only input (or output) pins will be attached buffer. If a list  of
       cells  is specified, it will insert the first CPF compliant cell. It is
       recommended to give non-AO buffers/inverters before AO  buffers/invert-

       instance created. Example: attachIOBuffer -in  BUFX4  -port  Before"i1/4

[1mName attachTerm [22m- Attaches a terminal to a net
[1mSyntax  attachTerm  [22m[-help] [-moduleBased <verilogModule>] [-noNewPort] <inst-
       Name> <termName> <netName> [-port <portName>] [-pin <refInstName> <ref-
       PinName>]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description  that  includes the type and
       default information for each attachTerm. For a detailed description  of
       the  command  and  all  of  its  parameters,  use  the man command: man
       attachTerm [1m<instName> [22mSpecifies the instance containing  the  terminal.
       If  the  instance  name  does not exist, the software displays an error
       message and the command stops.  [1m-moduleBased  <verilogModule>  [22mAttaches
       the  terminal  to the specified verilog module. [1m<netName> [22mSpecifies the
       name of the net to attach to the terminal. If the  net  name  does  not
       exist,  Innovus  displays  an  error  message and the command stops.The
       reserved names of 1'b1 and 1'b0 can be used to set a constant  directly
       on  the  terminal rather than connect it to a net. [1m-noNewPort [22mProhibits
       Innovus from creating hierarchical ports when it attaches  a  terminal.
       If  the  terminal  cannot  connect  to  the net through existing ports,
       Innovus displays an error message and the command  stops.  Default:  If
       you  do  not specify this parameter, Innovus creates hierarchical ports
       as needed. [1m-pin <refInstName refPinName> [22mSpecifies the pin <refPinName>
       on instance <refInstName> connected to the net that Innovus connects to
       the terminal. You cannot specify the -port parameter if  you  use  this
       parameter.  [1m-port  <portName>  [22mSpecifies  the hierarchical port used to
       connect the terminal with the net. If you specify this  parameter,  the
       hierarchical  port must exist in the module that contains the instance.
       The hierarchical port must connect to the net. This parameter lets  you
       use  a  specific port to maintain the same netlist topology, which sim-
       plifies equivalence checking later in the design flow. You cannot spec-
       ify  the  -pin  parameter if you use this parameter. Default: If you do
       not specify this parameter, Innovus uses existing ports or creates  new
       hierarchical  ports  as  necessary  to connect the terminal to the net.
       [1m<termName> [22mSpecifies the name of the terminal that Innovus connects  to
       the  specified  net.  If the terminal name does not exist, Innovus dis-
       plays an error message and the command stops.

       parameters,  the  results  will  be  based on a default of 5 resolution

[1mParameters -help        [22mOutputs a brief description  that  includes  type  and

       fies a particular buffer or inverter to use as an exclusion driver.  If
       this parameter is not specified or if the property, add_exclusion_driv-
       ers, is used to enable this functionality, then CCOpt will choose small
       area drivers from the CTS cell lists to use as exclusion drivers. CCOpt
       will either add pairs of inverters,  or  single  buffers  as  exclusion
       drivers.  While  choosing  the  cell  to  use, CCOpt will choose either
       inverters or  buffers  depending  on  the  value  specified  using  the
       use_inverters property. This property specifies whether clock tree syn-
       thesis should use inverters or buffers when balancing the clock  trees.
       For  more information about the use_inverters property, use the follow-
       ing command: get_ccopt_property -help use_inverters

       legacy FE-CTS specification file. This mode is a compatibility layer to
       enable the use of CCOpt technology with existing  FE-CTS  specification
       flows.  It enables a translation step that transforms constructs in the
       FE-CTS specification file into a CCOpt  clock  tree  specification  tcl
       script. Note: This parameter is used with the -cts parameter to specify
       that CTS part of CCOpt will be performed using the legacy FE-CTS speci-
       fication  file.  [1m-cts [22mTurns off clock concurrent optimization, and per-
       forms only clock tree synthesis (CTS) using the CCOpt engine.  It  does
       not  perform  any  datapath optimization or useful skew. This parameter
       can be used with or without the -ckSpec parameter. When used  with  the
       -ckSpec parameter, it specifies that the CTS part of CCOpt will be per-
       formed using the legacy FE-CTS specification file. [1m-expandedViews  [22mThis
       parameter is not interpreted in CCOpt but passed directly to optDesign.
       The parameter is same as optDesign-expandedViews  parameter,  which  is
       specified  to generate detailed view-specific timing reports at the end
       of the optDesign command run.  [1m-num_paths  <number_of_paths>  [22mSpecifies

       timing paths are reported. [1m-outDir <dirname> [22mThis  parameter  specifies
       the  directory where the software writes timing reports that are gener-

[1mName  changeIoConstraints  [22m-  Changes the constraints of an I/O row defined in

[1mSyntax changeIoConstraints [22m[-help] [-forceIt] [-ioOrder {clockwise |  counter-
       clockwise | default} | -row <string>] [-spacing <num> | -removeSpacing]
       [-endSpace  <num>  |   -removeEndSpace]   [-firstCellSpacing   <float>|
       -removeFirstCellSpacing] [-removeAll]
[1mParameters  -endSpace <num> [22mSpecifies the space, in meters, between the corner
       pad and the last I/O pad for the specified side of the row. Default:  0
       Data_type: float, optional [1m-firstCellSpacing <float> [22mSpecifies the dis-
       tance, in meters, from the first cell to the beginning of the I/O  row,
       based  on the I/O order. Data_type: float, optional [1m-forceIt [22mForces the
       I/O constraints to run on a non I/O row flow. Data_type: bool, optional
       [1m-help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes type and default infor-
       mation for each changeIoConstraints parameter. For a detailed  descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       changeIoConstraints. [1m-ioOrder {clockwise | counterclockwise |  default}[0m
       Changes  the  I/O placement order on all the rows. Note: This parameter
       is ignored if you specify  a  row  name.  Default:  default  Data_type:
       string, optional [1m-removeAll [22mRemoves all the existing constraints on the
       I/O's. Evenly distributes all the I/O's in the rows.  Data_type:  bool,
       optional  [1m-removeEndSpace  [22mRemoves the end space of the row. Data_type:
       bool, optional [1m-removeFirstCellSpacing [22mRemoves the spacing of the first
       cell.  Data_type: bool, optional [1m-removeSpacing [22mRemove the spacing con-
       straint from I/O cells on a row. [1m-row <string> [22mSpecifies  the  name  of
       the  row  to  modify the I/O constraints. Default: 1 Data_type: string,
       optional [1m-spacing <num> [22mSpecifies the global spacing,  in  meters,  for
       all  the  I/O's  on  a row. Note: changeIoConstraints -ioOrder -spacing
       <num> does not modify the  spacing  of  corner  I/O  pads.  Default:  0
       Data_type: float, optional

       used  with  -bumpPitch,  checkBump  checks  the bump pitch only for the
       bumps in the specific area. If -area is specified  without  -bumpPitch,

       -selected.  [1m-bumpMaxPitch  <max_pitch_value> [22mChecks whether the center-
       to-center    pitch    between    neighboring    bumps    exceeds    the
       <max_pitch_value>,  which  is  specified  in microns. For any bump, the
       search area is defined by a circle with a radius  of  <max_pitch_value>
       and the bump center as its center. (<Image> To view the image, refer to
       the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 manual.)  If  another
       bump  is detected within a bump's search area, the bump is DRC free. If
       no other bump is detected in a bump's search area, the bump  is  marked
       with a maximum spacing violation and a warning message is displayed. In
       the example below, only Bump 5 violates the maximum spacing  constraint
       and  is  flagged  with a maximum spacing violation: checkBump -bumpMax-
       Pitch 200 (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command
       Reference - Release 21.1 manual.) The -bumpMaxPitch parameter works on:

checkPlace(21.15)                                            checkPlace(21.15)



[1mName checkPlace [22m- Checks FIXED and PLACED cells for violations, adds violation
       markers to the design display area, and generates a violation report
[1mSyntax checkPlace [22m[<violationReportFileName>] [-clearMarker]  [-honorPreroute-
       ForFiller]      [-ignoreFillerInUtil]     [-ignoreOutOfCore]     [-inst
       <list_of_instances>] [-ioPinBlockage] [-macroBlockage]  [-noCheckPinAc-
       cess] [-noHardFence] [-noHalo] [-noPreplaced] [-selectedOnly]
[1mParameters  -noCheckPinAccess [22mSpecifies whether to check for pin access viola-
       tions. [1m-clearMarker [22mRemoves  the  violation  markers  from  a  previous
       checkPlace  run,  without rerunning checkPlace. [1m-honorPrerouteForFiller[0m
       Checks for placement blockage violations on physical  instances  placed
       under   preroutes   or  specified  by  setPlaceMode  -place_detail_pre-
       route_as_obs. By default, checkPlace does not treat filler cells placed
       under  preroutes  as violations, even though they are placement/routing
       blockages; however, it does treat standard cells placed under preroutes
       as  violations. [1m-ignoreFillerInUtil [22mIgnores filler cells in calculating
       utilization. [1m-ignoreOutOfCore [22mSkips instances outside the  core  design
       area.  [1m-inst  <list_of_instances>  [22mSpecifies  the  list of instances to
       check. [1m-ioPinBlockage [22mInstructs legalization  routines  to  treat  top-
       level  I/O pins as fixed metal obstructions while placing standard cell
       instances at the block level. There is a minor  run-time  penalty  with
       this  parameter,  so  it  is  not  turned on by default. [1m-macroBlockage[0m
       Checks for overlap between  hard  macro  and  macro-only  blockage  and
       reports  macro  blockage  violation. By default, macro-only blockage is
       ignored for both hard macro and standard cell. With this setting, it is
       treated  as  a  placement  obstruction  for macros. [1m-noHalo [22mSkips block
       halos. Uses the place-and-route  boundary  for  the  placement  overlap
       check.  [1m-noHardFence  [22mIgnores  fence  and region placement constraints.
       [1m-noPreplaced [22mDoes not check fixed instances.  When  this  parameter  is
       specified,  checkPlace  treats  fixed instances as placement blockages.
       [1m-selectedOnly [22mSpecifies to check only the selected instances  legality.
       [1m<violationReportFileName>  [22mSpecifies  the  report  file.  If you do not
       specify this parameter, the command  displays  a  summary  report.  The
       report  file  is more detailed than the summary report, and lists every
       instance with a violation.It contains details on the  violations  along
       with a Tcl procedure to select instances based on the violation type.

[1mName  checkTimingLibrary  [22m-  Checks  the  contents  of  the timing library and
       reports any inconsistencies in a log file
[1mSyntax checkTimingLibrary [22m[-outfile <string>] [-cellName  <string>]  [-library
       <string>] [-checkPower] [-reportMissingPowerOnly]
[1mParameters  -cellName  <string>  [22mChecks if the timing is defined for all cells
       with the specified name, in all timing libraries. Note: In general, the
       -cellName  parameter  is optional. However, if you specify the -library
       parameter, then you must specify -cellName. [1m-checkPower [22mChecks if power
       constructs  are  defined  for  the cells, such as internal_power, leak-
       age_power, or ecsm_power. Note: In general, the  -checkPower  parameter
       is  optional. However, if you specify -reportMissingPowerOnly, then you
       must specify -checkPower. If you use the -library parameter, you do not
       have  to specify the -checkPower parameter, because when a library-spe-
       cific cell is given as input, the  software  automatically  checks  for
       power  constructs.  Default:  Only  checks if timing is defined for the
       cells. [1m-library <string> [22mSpecifies the timing library in which to check
       a  particular  cell.  You  must  specify  the  -cellName parameter with
       -library, to specify the particular library cell to check. Note: If you
       use  the -library parameter, you do not have to specify the -checkPower
       parameter, because when a library-specific cell is given as input,  the
       software  automatically  checks for power constructs. [1m-outfile <string>[0m
       Writes  the  report  to  the  specified  file.  [1m-reportMissingPowerOnly[0m
       Reports  only the cells that do not have internal_power (at pin level),
       or leakage_power defined. You must specify  the  -checkPower  parameter
       with the -reportMissingPowerOnly parameter.
[1mExamples[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022  checkTimingLibrary(21.15)

[1mName compare_model_timing [22m- Compares two reports that contain interface timing
       characteristics generated by the write_model_timing command
[1mSyntax compare_model_timing [22m-help -ref  <string>  -compare  <string>  -outFile
       <string> [-ignore_view] [-percent_tolerance <float>] [-percent_cap_tol-
       erance <float>] [-absolute_cap_tolerance <float>] [-percent_tran_toler-
       ance  <float>]  [-absolute_tran_tolerance <float>] [-absolute_tolerance
       <float>]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each  compare_model_timing  parameter. For a detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man compare_model_timing. [1m-absolute_cap_tolerance <float> [22mSpeci-
       fies the tolerance value for capacitance (as an absolute  value)  while
       comparing  two  report  files. This parameter specifies the permissible
       difference, as an absolute value, between the capacitance values of two
       report files. If the difference in the value of capacitance exceeds the
       absolute tolerance value specified, the comparison  status  is  set  to
       FAIL. Note: When this parameter is not specified, the software uses the
       absolute value specified with the -absolute_tolerance parameter. If the
       -absolute_tolerance  parameter  is not specified, the value defaults to
       0. (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Refer-
       ence - Release 21.1 manual.) When the -percent_cap_tolerance and -abso-
       lute_cap_tolerance parameters are used together, the comparison  status
       is  set  to  FAILonly  when  the difference in the value of capacitance
       exceeds the specified absolute as well as percentage tolerance  values.
       [1m-absolute_tolerance <float> [22mSpecifies the absolute tolerance value. The
       tolerance value is used when there is a difference between  the  timing
       characteristics of the reference file (-ref) and the file that is being
       compared (-compare) to determine the PASS or FAIL status of the compar-
       ison. If the difference in the value of a timing characteristic exceeds
       the absolute tolerance value, the comparison status  is  set  to  FAIL.
       Note:  When  used with the -percent_tolerance option, the difference in
       the value of a timing characteristic should exceed  both  absolute  and
       percentage  tolerance values for the comparison result status of an arc
       to be FAIL. Default: 0 [1m-absolute_tran_tolerance <float>  [22mSpecifies  the
       name of the report file that contains the interface timing characteris-
       tics extracted from the model created using the  do_extract_model  com-
       mand.  The  timing  characteristics  of this file are compared with the
       timing characteristics of the reference file that you specify with  the
       -ref  option.  [1m-compare  <string> [22mSpecifies the name of the report file
       that contains the interface timing characteristics extracted  from  the
       model created using the do_extract_model command. The timing character-
       istics of this file are compared with the timing characteristics of the
       reference  file  that  you  specify  with the -ref option. [1m-ignore_view[0m
       Compares non-MMMC design write_model_timing output report with the MMMC
       design  output report (of write_model_timing command). When you specify
       this parameter, the software ignores the view information while compar-
       ing the reports. So you do not require to create dummy views for timing
       model validation flow. [1m-outFile <string> [22mSpecifies the name of the out-
       put  file  in which the comparison results will be generated. This file
       contains the PASS or FAIL status for the timing data comparison.  [1m-per-[0m
       [1mcent_cap_tolerance  <float>  [22mSpecif<standard input>:11: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:14: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

       tance (as a percentage) while comparing two report files. This  parame-
       ter  specifies  the  permissible difference, in percentage, between the
       capacitance values of two report files. If the percentage difference in
       the  value of capacitance exceeds the percentage tolerance value speci-
       fied, the comparison status is set to FAIL. Note: When  this  parameter
       is not specified, the software uses the percentage value specified with
       the -percent_tolerance parameter. If the  -percent_tolerance  parameter

       files.  The  percentage tolerance value is used when there is a differ-

       command  on  the  original design. The file specified with the -compare
       option is compared with this file.

connectMacroFeedthrough(21.15)                  connectMacroFeedthrough(21.15)



[1mName  connectMacroFeedthrough [22m- Connects predefined feedthrough pins in custom
       macros to overlapping nets that have wires  crossing  over  the  custom
       macros,  based on the routing information. The feedthrough connectivity
       details are defined in a mapping file, which is specified  through  the
       -portmap <filename> parameter
[1mSyntax  connectMacroFeedthrough  [22m[-help]  [-selectNet  <string>  | -excludeNet
       <string>  |  -selectMarkedNet]  [-selectInst  <string>  |  -excludeInst
       <string>]  [-ecoFile  <string> | -checkOnly] [-portMap <string>] [-ver-
       bose]   [-maxSearchDistance   <float]>   [-searchAllSides]   [-abutment
       <float>] [-abutmentFile <string>] [-floatingPortList <string>]
[1mParameters  -abutment  <float>  [22mSpecifies  the  distance that pins on the same
       track and layer must have from one another so as to  be  considered  as
       abutted. If two or more pins are considered as abutted, any feedthrough
       path that passes through one of the pins will pass  through  the  other
       pin(s)  as  well.  Default:  If  this  parameter  is not specified, the
       default value is 1 micron.  Data_type:  float,  optional  [1m-abutmentFile[0m
       [1m<string> [22mReports, in the file specified, the list of pins that are con-
       sidered as abutted. In the file, each feedthrough path is  traced  from
       the first input pin to the last input pin. Each path is preceded by the
       word Begin on a new line and followed by the word End on  a  new  line.
       Here  is  the extract from an example file: Begin Inst [Inst1], Term In
       [A1] Term Out [X1] Inst [Inst2], Term In [A2] Term Out [X2] End In  the
       previous example, the out term X1 of instance Inst1 is abutted with the
       in term A2 of instance Inst2. Data_type:  string,  optional  [1m-checkOnly[0m
       Specifies that only a report of the messages should be displayed but no
       changes should be  made  to  the  netlist.  Data_type:  bool,  optional
       [1m-ecoFile  <string> [22mSpecifies the name of the ECO file that will contain
       a report of the changes. You can use this  file  while  performing  ECO
       changes. Here is a sample report generated through this parameter: FOR-
       MATVERSION  2  ATTACHTERM  eco_instance1  inputbuf2[2]  testnet  ADDNET
       FE_FTM_1_testnet  ATTACHTERM eco_instance1 outputbuf2[2] FE_FTM_1_test-
       net ATTACHTERM i1  A  FE_FTM_1_testnet  ATTACHTERM  eco_instance1  rstb
       FE_FTM_1_testnet Data_type: string, optional [1m-excludeInst <string> [22mPre-
       vents feedthrough buffers from being added for the specified  instance.
       The names of the instances are specified in a file, specified by <file-
       Name>. In the file, you can specify  wildcards  (*)  for  the  instance
       names to exclude. Default: All instances of the cell types specified in
       the portmap file are considered. Data_type:  string,  optional  [1m-exclu-[0m
       [1mdeNet  <string>  [22mPrevents  feedthrough  buffers from being added to the
       specified net. The names of the nets are specified in a file, specified
       by  <fileName>.  In the file, you can specify wildcards (*) for the net
       names to exclude. Default:  All  nets  or  bus  names  are  considered.
       Data_type:  string,  optional [1m-floatingPortList <string> [22mSpecifies that
       the list of unused ports should be saved in  the  specified  file.  The
       file  lists  the  instance  name and the pin name for each unused port.
       After running the connectMacroFeedthrough  command,  the  unused  ports
       should be manually tied. You can use this parameter to save the list of
       the unused ports to a file. Data_type: string, optional [1m-help [22mOutputs a
       brief  description  that  includes the type and default information for
       each connectMacroFeedthrough parameter. For a detailed  description  of
       the<standard input>:13: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:14: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
  command  and  all of its parameters, use the man command: man con-
       nectMacroFeedthrough [1m-maxSearchDistance <float> [22mSpecifies the  distance
       in  microns from the wire crossing till which the command should search
       to find a connected feedthrough. Note: Specifying  a  large  value  for
       this  parameter  might have an adverse impact on the Quality of Results
       (QoR). Data_type: float, optional [1m-portMap <string> [22mSpecifies the  name
       of  the  file  that  contains the feedthrough connectivity definitions.
       Default: If you do not specify a  file  name,  a  file  with  the  name
       portmap  in the current directory is used.by default. Note: A file with
       the feethrough connectivity definitions must be available.  The  syntax
       of  the  file  is as follows: MACRO <MacroName>Macro definition section
       END MACRO The definition of the macro is provided in the  <Macro><defi-
       nition>  section,  which  can contain one or more feedthrough sections.
       The name of the feedthrough section is  optional.  The  syntax  of  the
       Feedthrough  section  is  as follows: Feedthrough [FeedthroughName] Pin
       Section END FEEDTHROUGH Each Feedthrough section contains  one  section
       for  the  INPUT  PIN  and  one section for the output pin. Note: Multi-
       fanout feedthrough sections are not supported. The syntax  of  the  pin
       section  is as follows: PIN PinName DIRECTION {in | out }; SIDE {left |
       right | top | bottom}; END PIN If the pin direction is  not  specified,
       it is read from the LEF file. If you specify a value for pin direction,
       ensure that it is consistent with the  description  in  the  LEF  file.
       Note:  The  pin  direction inout is not supported. Note: All the prede-
       fined macro feedthrough pins should be floating pins. Here is an  exam-
       ple  of  a  mapping  file:  MACRO  RAMXXX  FEEDTHROUGH feedthrough1 PIN
       feedthrough1_in END PIN PIN feedthrough1_out END  PIN  END  FEEDTHROUGH
       FEEDTHROUGH    feedthrough2    PIN    feedthrough2_in   END   PIN   PIN
       feedthrough2_out END PIN END FEEDTHROUGH END MACRO  Data_type:  string,
       optional  [1m-searchAllSides  [22mSpecifies  that  if  the  closest  available
       feedthrough pin on the same  side  cannot  be  connected,  the  command
       should search for the feedthrough pins on other sides as well. When you
       specify this parameter, it is recommended to limit the distance of  the
       search  using  the  -maxSearchDistance option to get good QoR. Default:
       The command searches for a feedthrough whose in and out pins lie on the
       same  sides  of  the macro on which the wires enter and exit the macro.
       Data_type: bool, optional [1m-selectInst  <string>    [22mSpecifies  that  the
       feedthrough  buffers  should be added only for the specified instances.
       Data_type: string, optional [1m-selectMarkedNet [22mSpecifies that feedthrough
       buffers  should  be added only to the nets that are currently selected.
       Default: All nets.are considered. Data_type: bool, optional  [1m-selectNet[0m

       the specified nets. Data_type: string, optional [1m-verbose [22mProvides addi-
       tional  messages,  for  example net-specific messages. Data_type: bool,
       optional

createBusGuide(21.15)                                    createBusGuide(21.15)



[1mName  createBusGuide [22m- Creates bus guides associated with net groups, to guide
       routing for all the nets of the specified net group
[1mSyntax createBusGuide [22m[-help] [-type {hard  |  soft}]  -netGroup  <netGrpName>
       -layer  {id  |  id1:id2} {[{-centerLine {<x1 y1 x2 y2>} -width <value>}
       [-beginExt <value>] [-endExt <value>]] | -rect {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}}
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that  includes  type  and  default
       information  for each createBusGuide parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       createBusGuide.  [1m-beginExt  <value> [22mSpecifies the value, in microns, by
       which the bus guide segment is to be extended in the  beginning.  [1m-cen-[0m
       [1mterLine  <x1><y1><x2><y2>  [22mSpecifies the coordinates of the center line
       of the bus guide segment. The direction of the guide segment is derived
       from  the x1 y1 x2 y2 coordinate values. Note: Non-orthogonal bus guide
       segments are not supported. [1m-endExt <value>  [22mSpecifies  the  value,  in
       microns,  by  which the bus guide segment is to be extended in the end.
       [1m-layer {<id> | <id1>:<id2>} [22mSpecifies the routing layer constraint hon-
       ored  by the router. Note: Routing done on non-preferred routing layers
       or on layers which are not part of the specified layer  constraint  can

       the  selected  nets.  You  can  select  instances  or  nets  using  the

       optional [1m-excludePin  {allLayer  |  sameLayer  |  allLayerInGuidedArea}[0m

createPinBlkg(21.15)                                      createPinBlkg(21.15)



[1mName createPinBlkg [22m- Creates a pin blockage for a module
[1mSyntax  createPinBlkg [22m[-help] [-cell <cell_name>] [-layer {<layer_id_list>}] {
       -area <{x1 y1 x2 y2>}  |  [-edge  <edge_number>  [[-offset_start  <dis-
       tance>]   [-offset_end   <distance>]]]  |  [-abutted_master_clone_chan-
       nel_access_only  [-feedthru_blockage_file  <file_name>]]  }   [   -name
       <blockage_name>   [   -includePinPatterns  {<pin_name_pattern_list>}  |
       -excludePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>} ]]
[1mParameters -abutted_master_clone_channel_access_only [22mCreates pin blockages  on
       abutted edges of master-clones that abut to its parent or other master-
       clones. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-area <x1 y1  x2  y2>  [22mSpecifies  the
       lower left x coordinate, lower left y coordinate, upper right x coordi-
       nate, and upper right y coordinate respectively of the  blockage  area.
       Note:  The  values  of x1, y1, x2, and y2 are relative to the top-level
       coordinates. Data_type: box, optional [1m-cell  <cellName>  [22mSpecifies  the
       module  for  which  the pin blockage will be created. This parameter is
       required if the module is not the top-level module. Data_type:  string,
       optional [1m-edge <edgeNumber> [22mSpecifies the integer value where edge num-
       bering starts from lower-left corner of a partition clock-wise. Edge  0
       is  the  edge  that  has the smallest y value. Data_type: int, optional
       [1m-excludePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>} [22mSpecifies the pin-list on
       which  the  pin-blockage is not applicable. Pins which are specified in
       this list can be placed in this area legally. Note: The -excludePinPat-
       terns and -includePinPatterns options are mutually exclusive and cannot
       be used in a single command. Both these options require the use of  the
       -name  option  to  specify  the  name  of  the  partition pin blockage.
       Data_type: string, optional [1m-feedthru_blockage_file <file_name> [22mOutputs
       a file with coordinates of blocked edges for pin assignment transformed
       into feedthru blockage_file format. Data_type: string,  optional  [1m-help[0m
       Outputs a brief description that includes the type and default informa-
       tion for each createPinBlkg parameter. For a  detailed  description  of
       the  command  and  all of its parameters, use the man command: man cre-
       atePinBlkg [1m-includePinPatterns {<pin_name_pattern_list>} [22mSpecifies  the
       pin-list on which the pin-blockage is applicable. All other pins can be
       placed  in  this  area  legally.  Note:  The  -excludePinPatterns   and
       -includePinPatterns  options  are mutually exclusive and cannot be used
       in a single command. Both these options require the use  of  the  -name
       option  to  specify  the name of the partition pin blockage. Data_type:
       string, optional [1m-layer {<layer_id_list>} [22mSpecifies the metal  layer(s)
       for  which  pins  are  not to be created. Note: Layers can be specified
       using the LEF layer names or layer ID numbers.  Default:  If  no  layer
       number  is  specified, all metal layers are blocked. Data_type: string,
       optional [1m-name <blockageName> [22mSpecifies the name of the  partition  pin
       blockage. Default: By default, the name is defPtnPinBlkName. Data_type:
       string, optional [1m-offset_end  <distance>  [22mSpecifies  the  distance,  in
       microns,  from  the ending corner of the edge. Minimum Value: 0 Maximum
       Value: 65535 Data_type: float, optional [1m-offset_start <distance> [22mSpeci-
       fies  the  distance,  in microns, from the starting corner of the edge.
       Minimum Value: 0 Maximum Value: 65535 Data_type: float, optional

       guide  honoring  the  minimum  spacing  constraint  and overlooking any

       Text  Command  Reference  -  Release  21.1  manual.)  Data_type:  bool,
       optional [1m-excludePin {allLayer |  sameLayer  |  allLayerInGuidedArea  }[0m

       same layer, or on all layers in the guided area.

[1mSyntax createPipelineNetGroup [22m[-help] netGroupName  [-endReserve  <reserveDis-

       from the end points on block boundary to the internal connection inside

       All the nets attached to the D and Q pins are  put  into  the  PFF  net
       group.  [1m-net  <listOfNetNamesOrRegularEx><p>  [22mCreates  net group of all
       given nets. [1m-startReserve <reserveDistanceInMicrons> [22mSpecifies  a  dis-
       tance  budget from internal connections inside block to the start point
       of the PFF net. This value is added to the first  stage  distance  when
       calculating  equidistant spacing for each stage. The unit is in micron.
       [1m-startTerm <termList> [22mCreates net group of all data  nets  between  the
       given end points. The PFF-chain is traced from the startTerm, through D
       and Q terminals of PFF(s) until an endTerm is matched.

       instance names. Use this parameter if you want to create the SDP  group

       if you want the tool to honor the order in which SDP instance are spec-
       ified  in the list. Note: Wildcards can be used to specify the instance

       that  will be used to align the SDP group you are creating. Default: SW

       you  specify  as  input  with the -inst parameter. [1m-name <sdpGroupName>[0m
       Specifies the name of the SDP group you are creating.  [1m-numCol  <value>[0m
       Indicates  the  number  of columns to be created. [1m-numRow <value> [22mIndi-
       cates the number of rows to be created. Note: If you specify both -num-
       Row  and  -numCol, use the -type parameter to specify the parent struc-
       ture type (row or col). If you do not specify type, the default  parent
       structure  will  be column. [1m-selected [22mIndicates that you want to create
       the SDP group from the  current  set  of  selected  instances.  If  the
       selected  cells  are already placed and you specify neither the -numRow
       or -numCol options nor the -type option, the command will automatically
       generate  one column with rows where the SDP structure will be based on
       the physical location of the selected cells. The tool  will  print  the
       following  message  to  indicate that the SDP structure created will be
       derived from the physical location of the selected  cells:  Command  is
       running  with  physical  mode  extraction  where  SDP structure will be
       derived from the existing physical  cell  placement.  If  the  selected
       cells  are  not  yet placed or if some of the selected cells are placed
       while others are not, the tool prints a  message  indicating  that  SDP
       physical  mode  extraction cannot be activated and SDP structure cannot
       be derived from the existing physical placement  because  the  selected
       instance  is  not  placed. [1m-side {W|E|MID} [22mIndicates the pin edge to be
       used for alignment. Default: W [1m-skip_space <value>  [22mSpecifies  a  space
       value to be skipped. By default, if -skip_space is defined in a column,
       its value represents the number of  skipped  rows.  If  -skip_space  is
       defined  in  a row, its value is for column skipping and represents the
       number of M2 tracks (pitch of first vertical layer). Skip  space  value
       can  also  be  specified as number of widths of a specified row site by
       using the -skip_space_by_site_width <value> <siteName> parameter.  How-
       ever,  row  site width should be speci<standard input>:14: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

<standard input>:22: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
fied only for an SDP row, and not
       for   an   SDP   column.   Alternatively,   you   can    specify    the

[1mName  createSignalPin  [22m-  Promotes signal pins in the IO pad/block to the top-

       moted  to  the  top  level.  The specified pins should be hierarchical.
       Note: This option cannot be used with -inst.

createTBOptFile(21.15)                                  createTBOptFile(21.15)



[1mName  createTBOptFile  [22m-  This  command  creates  a  target-based optimization
       (TBOpt) file for use with postRoute targeted optimization
[1mSyntax  createTBOptFile  [22m[-help]  -bottleneckInstanceNumber  <integer>[-early]
       [-gtdFile   <filename>]  [-max_paths  <integer>]  [-max_slack  <float>]
       [-min_slack <float>] -outFile <filename> [-path_group <groupname_list>]

[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information for each createTBOptFile parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       createTBOptFile [1m-bottleneckInstanceNumber <integer> [22mSpecifies the  num-
       ber  of  critical  bottleneck  instances  to  be  generated.  This is a
       required parameter. [1m-early [22mSpecifies that the TBOpt file will  be  cre-
       ated based on hold timing's critical nodes. This parameter can be spec-
       ified along with the following commands to generate and use a hold tar-
       get  file  for hold TBOpt. For example: createTBOptFile -early -bottle-
       neckInstanceNumber 5  -outFile  TBOpt_bottleneck_5_hold.txt  setOptMode
       -targetBasedOptHoldFile      TBOpt_bottleneck_5_hold.txt      optDesign
       -postRoute -targeted -hold [1m-gtdFile <filename> [22mSpecifies  the  name  of
       the machine-readable timing report on which you want to base the criti-
       cal instance analysis. If this parameter is not specified, the  command
       generates  its own file with the -max_slack value of 0.0 and -max_paths
       value of 100,000. [1m-max_paths <integer> [22mSpecifies the  number  of  worst
       paths  to  be  considered,  regardless of the endpoint. By default, the
       value is 100,000. [1m-max_slack <float> [22mSpecifies that  only  those  paths
       should be considered that have a slack equal to or less than the speci-
       fied float value in ns. By default, the value is  0.0  to  ensure  that
       only  paths  with  negative  slacks  are considered. [1m-min_slack <float>[0m
       Specifies that only those paths should be considered that have a  slack
       greater than the specified float value in ns. [1m-outFile <filename> [22mSpec-
       ifies the name of the TBOpt file that will  be  generated.  This  is  a
       required  parameter.  [1m-path_group  <groupname_list> [22mSpecifies that only
       those paths should be considered  that  are  from  the  specified  path
       groups on which you want to base the critical instance analysis.
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
