[1mName  createWhatIfInternalGeneratedClock [22m- Creates an internal pin on a black-
       box or a blackblob, and creates a generated clock on this internal pin
[1mSyntax createWhatIfInternalGeneratedClock [22m<blackBoxCellName>  [-help]  -clock-
       Name  <genClkName>  -clockPin <internalPinName> -masterPin <clockInput-
       Port> [-edge_shift <edge_shift_list>] [-noCreateInternalPin]  [-invert]
       {-multiplyBy <integer> | -divideBy <integer> | -edges <edge_list>}
[1mParameters  <blackBoxCellName> [22mSpecifies the name of the blackbox or blackblob
       cell. [1m-clockName <genClkName> [22mSpecifies the name of the clock.generated
       on  the internal pin. [1m-clockPin <internalPinName> [22mSpecifies the name of
       the pin generated inside the blackbox or blackblob. [1m-divideBy <integer>[0m
       Specifies  the frequency division factor. The generated clock period is
       equal to the master clock period  multiplied  by  this  parameter.  For
       example,  if  the  value  of  this  parameter is 2, the generated clock
       period is two times the master clock period. This  parameter  takes  an
       integer  value.  [1m-edge_shift  <edge_shift_list> [22mSpecifies the amount of
       shift for each edge in the  specified  edge  list.  [1m-edges  <edge_list>[0m
       Specifies  the  list  of  edges from source clock to the derived clock.
       [1m-invert [22mInverts the source clock. [1m-masterPin <clockInputPort> [22mSpecifies
       the  source from which the derived clock is generated. Note: The source
       must be an existing clock port. and a clock should be available on this
       port.  [1m-multiplyBy   [22mSpecifies the frequency multiplication factor. The
       generated clock period is equal to the master clock period  divided  by
       this  parameter.  For example, if the value of this parameter is 2, the
       generated clock period is half the master clock period. This  parameter
       takes an integer value. [1m-noCreateInternalPin [22mSpecifies that a generated
       clock should be created on an existing internal pin. In this case,  the
       -clockPin  <internalPinName>  parameter  should  specify  the  existing
       internal pin.
[1mRelated Information[0m
[1mExamples[0m

       PNG files. Color coding of  images  is  provided  below:  White:  Unob-
       structed  edges of the synthesis grid Red: Grid points that are blocked
       for trunk cell placement in all modules Orange: Grid  points  that  are
       blocked for final cell placement in all modules Red orange: Grid points
       that are blocked for trunk and final cell placement in all modules Yel-
       low  circle: The grid point of the source Yellow crosses: Targeted grid
       points of H-tree sinks Yellow rectangle: The sink area containing  tar-
       get  grid  point  candidates of H-sinks, adjusted to the synthesis grid
       Brown: If specified, the sink grid box snapped to  the  synthesis  grid
       Green/blue:   The  edges  of  the  synthesized  H-tree  Purple:  H-tree
       repeaters [1m-final_cell <base_cell> [22mSpecifies the library cell (buffer or
       inverter)  to  use  for the ends of the clock tree. [1m-hv_balance {true |[0m
       [1mfalse} [22mWhen set to true, specifies that  the  horizontal  and  vertical
       metal wires can only be balanced against other wires of the same orien-

       against  any other wire. Default: true [1m-inverting [22mSpecifies whether the
       tree will invert its input or not. By default, this  parameter  is  not

       and uses the given value as the maximum length of the  nets  connecting
       the  H-tree  drivers.  [1m-max_root_distance  <value>  [22mWhen specified, the
       software ignores DRVs and uses the given value as the maximum length of
       the  net  connecting  the root and the first driver of the H-tree. This
       value can only be specified if the  -max_driver_distance  parameter  is
       also  specified.  [1m-mode {drv | distance} [22mSpecifies the driver insertion
       mode. When set to drv, drivers are inserted to avoid DRVs. When set  to
       distance,  the  parameters, -max_driver_distance and -max_root_distance
       determine the maximum net lengths allowed. Transitions and  delays  are
       not  computed  in  this case. Default: drv Note: When this parameter is
       set to distance, the -max_driver_distance and -max_root_distance param-
       eters  must be specified. [1m-name  <flexibleHtreeName> [22mSpecifies the name
       of the flexible H-tree to  be  created.  This  parameter  is  required.
       [1m-omit_symmetry  <string>  [2<standard input>:17: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

<standard input>:21: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:24: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:37: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:42: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:48: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:50: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:51: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:52: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
2mSpecifies  that  no  symmetry  drivers and/or
       branches should be added to balance the pin load of nets in the  flexi-
       ble  H-tree. Symmetry drivers are drivers that are added to balance pin
       capacitances at  branch  points.  For  example,  if  buffer  pairs  are
       inserted  at  branch  points,  one  of  these buffers may not drive any
       fanout and is inserted to match other buffer pairs at the same level of
       the  flexible H-tree. Omitting symmetry drivers can reduce the power of
       the H-tree but increase its skew. Drivers that are added  to  terminate
       symmetry  branches do not count as symmetry drivers and are never omit-
       ted. Similarly, symmetry branches are branches that are needed to  bal-
       ance  the  wire  load  at  branch points. They are added to match other
       branchpoints at  the  same  level  of  the  flexible  H-tree.  Symmetry
       branches  are  always terminated with drivers, which are not counted as
       symmetry drivers. Possible values for this parameter  are:  false:  Add
       symmetry  branches  and  drivers  true:  Omit both symmetry drivers and
       branches  drivers:  Omit  symmetry  drivers  branches:  Omit   symmetry
       branches  {drivers  branches}:  Omit both symmetry drivers and branches
       {}: Add symmetry branches and drivers By default, symmetry branches and
       buffers  are added. [1m-partition_boundary_inverting {true | false} [22mSpeci-
       fies whether the clock phase is inverting with regard to the  root  pin
       when  entering  partitions.  Default: false [1m-partition_groups {{<parti-[0m

create_ccopt_generated_clock_tree(21.15c)reate_ccopt_generated_clock_tree(21.15)



[1mName create_ccopt_generated_clock_tree [22m- Defines a generated clock tree within
       the design. Use this command if you want to balance the  sinks  in  the
       generated tree against those in the parent trees
[1mSyntax  create_ccopt_generated_clock_tree  [22m[-help] [-generated_by pins] [-name
       <clockname>] [-parents  <parents>]  [-search_method  <method>]  -source
       <pin> [-stop_at_sdc_clock_roots]
[1mParameters  -help        [22mOutputs  a  brief  description that includes type and
       default information for each create_ccopt_generated_clock_tree  parame-
       ter.  For  a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
       ters, use the man command: man create_ccopt_generated_clock_tree. [1m-gen-[0m
       [1merated_by  <pins>     [22mSpecifies the sink pins in the parent clock trees
       for which the delay between the parent and generated clock trees should
       be  considered. If this parameter is not specified, all possible timing
       paths between sinks in the parent tree and the source of the  generated
       clock  tree  will  be  considered. This parameter is mutually exclusive
       with the -search_method  parameter.  [1m-name  <clockname>  [22mSpecifies  the
       user-defined  identifier for the generated clock tree. This name should
       be unique. If this parameter is not specified, the  software  uses  the
       name    of    the   source   pin   by   default.   [1m-parents   <parents>[0m
       Specifies the parent clock trees for the generated  clock  trees.  This
       parameter   should   be   specified   if  the  parents  are  ambiguous.
       [1m-search_method {same_instance multi_stage} [22mSpecifies the  search  meth-
       dology  to  be  used  when  tracing  the  path to the generator inputs.
       multi_stage This is the default method, and  will  select  the  current
       behavior  of  the software. When this method is specified, the software
       searches backwards through all the delay paths leading into  the  clock
       root  pin,  looking for pre-existing clock sinks. Every such clock sink
       found is a candidate generator input for the generated clock tree. This
       includes  clock sinks that lie on different instances to the root pin -
       where multiple stages lie between the clock  sink  and  the  root  pin.
       Additional  filtering  on  the candidate generator inputs is applied by
       the -parents parameter to avoid producing  cycles  in  the  clock  tree
       structure.  Once  the  set  of generator inputs is finalized, the delay
       path between each finalized generator input and the clock root  pin  is
       imported  into  the  CCOpt  clock tree data stuctures. If the generator
       input lies on a different instance of the clock root pin,  ClockGenera-
       torPathNode  objects  are created. same_instance This method is similar
       to the multi_stage method,  except  that  the  software  restricts  its
       search  to  consider  only clock sinks that lie on the same instance as
       the generated clock tree's root pin. This means that the software  does
       not  traverse  net arcs looking for generator input clock sinks. Conse-
       quently, ClockGeneratorPathNode objects will not be needed to model any
       generator path. Note:
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 0c2r:e0a2t:e1_5cc2o0p2t2_generated_clock_tree(21.15)

create_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe(21.c1r5e)ate_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe(21.15)



[1mName  create_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe [22m- This command creates an object that
       corresponds to a single preferred_cell_stripe. The object represents  a
       constraint  where CCOpt tries to place instances of the specified cells
       within the specified bounding box of the stripe. When several of  these
       objects  are  created, CTS tries to place instances within the bounding
       boxes of the stripes, choosing the stripe that yields the best  quality
       of result
[1mSyntax  create_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe [22m[-help] -bbox {xmin xmax ymin ymax}
       -cells <list_of_cells> -name <name>
[1mParameters -help        [22mOutputs a brief description  that  includes  type  and
       default information for each create_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe parame-
       ter. For a detailed description of the command and all of  its  parame-
       ters,  use  the  man  command:  man create_ccopt_preferred_cell_stripe.
       [1m-bbox <bbox> [22mSpecifies the area of the  bounding  box.  Cell  instances
       within  this box will be preferentially placed on the stripes, if their
       library cell appears in the  cell  list  associated  with  the  stripes
       instance.  [1m-cells  <list_of_cells>  [22mSpecifies the list of library cells
       that should be placed on preferred cell stripes. [1m-name <name> [22mSpecifies
       the user-defined identifier for these preferred cell stripes.

create_ccopt_skew_group(21.15)                  create_ccopt_skew_group(21.15)



[1mName create_ccopt_skew_group [22m- Creates a new skew group within the design
[1mSyntax  create_ccopt_skew_group  [22m[-help]  [-constrains  cts  | ccopt_initial |
       ccopt | subset_of_values | all  |  none]  [-from_clocks  <clock_names>]
       [-from_constraint_modes  <constraint_mode_names>]  [-from_delay_corners
       <delay_corner_names>] -name <skew_group_name>  [-rank  <rank>]  [-sinks
       <pins>  |  -shared_sinks  pins  | -exclusive_sinks pins | -auto_sinks |
       -filtered_auto_sinks  <pins>  |   -balance_skew_groups   <skew_groups>]
       [-sources  <pins> | -balance_skew_groups <skew_groups>] [-target_inser-
       tion_delay <value>] [-target_skew <value>]
[1mParameters -help       [22mOutputs a brief  description  that  includes  type  and
       default  information  for each create_ccopt_skew_group parameter. For a
       detailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use  the
       man  command:  man create_ccopt_skew_group. [1m-auto_sinks [22mWhen specified,
       determines the target sinks for the skew group based on the input  pins
       reachable from the source. [1m-balance_skew_groups <skew_groups> [22mSpecifies
       that the new skew groups should be created  by  merging  the  specified
       skew  groups  in order to balance them together as a single skew group.
       Note: The sources of skew  groups  are  specified  using  the  -sources
       parameter.  However, if the -sources parameter is not specified and you
       are using the -balance_skew_groups parameter, then the sources are  the
       sources  of  the  skew  groups that are specified using this parameter.
       [1m-constrains cts | ccopt_initial | ccopt | subset_of_values | all | none[0m
       Specifies  whether  the skew group should constrain cts, ccopt_initial,
       ccopt, a subset of these values, all, or none. If  the  value  includes
       cts,  the  created skew group will constrain cts, if the value includes
       ccopt_initial, the created skew group will be used to constrain CCOpt's
       initial  solution.If  the  value includes ccopt, the created skew group
       will constrain CCOpt's final solution. [1m-exclusive_sinks  <pins>  [22mSpeci-
       fies the input pins in the design that CCOpt should consider as members
       of the new skew group. This will give  the  new  skew_group  an  exclu-
       sive_sinks_rank  1 greater than any other currently defined skew group,
       effectively removing the pins from all skew_groups that they  currently
       belong  to. If both shared_sinks and exclusive_sinks are not specified,
       CCOpt will use the set of  sinks  reachable  from  the  source  if  the
       auto_sinks   switch   is   provided,   or  no  sinks  otherwise.  [1m-fil-[0m
       [1mtered_auto_sinks <pins> [22mSpecifies  that  the  target  sinks  should  be
       determined automatically from the subset provided. The target sinks for
       the skew group are determined based on the input  pins  reachable  from
       the  source.  However,  of these pins, only those are selected that are
       also present in the list of pins provided  as  a  filter.  [1m-from_clocks[0m
       [1m<clock_names> [22mSpecifies the name of the clock for which this skew group
       was extracted. [1m-from_constraint_modes <constraint_mode_names>    [22mSpeci-
       fies  the  constraint  mode  for  which  this skew group was extracted.
       [1m-from_delay_corners <delay_corner_names>    [22mSpecifies the delay corners
       associated  with  the  constraint  modes  for which this skew group was
       extracted. [1m-name <skew_group_name> [22mSpecifies the user-defined name  for
       the new skew group. The name must be unique. [1m-rank <rank> [22mSpecifies the
       exclusive_sinks_rank for this skew group. [1m-shared_sinks  <pins>  [22mSpeci-
       fies the input pins in the design that CCOpt should consider as members
       of the new skew group but are also shared with other skew groups. These
       pins  are  members  of  both  the  original skew group and the new skew
       group. This implies a exclusive_sinks_rank of 0. [1m-sinks  <pins>  [22mSpeci-
       fies the input pins in the design that CCOpt should consider as members
       of the new skew group. [1m-sources <pins>   [22mSpecifies the source  pins  of
       the skew group. Note: The skew group insertion delay is calculated from
       its source pin. Only input ports or output pins can be the sources of a
       skew group. [1m-target_insertion_delay <value> [22mSpecifies the target inser-
       tion delay to be used for the skew group. CCOpt attempts  to  keep  the
       latency of all sinks within half the target skew on either side of this
       delay.  For  example,  create_ccopt_skew_group  -name  b1  -sources  b1
       -exclusive_sinks  {A/CK  B/CK G/CK} -target_insertion_delay 0.3ns -tar-
       get_skew 0.1ns [1m-target_skew <value> [22mSpecifies the skew that  the  clock
       tree synthesis should aim for. It sets the target_skew property for the
       created skew group (set_ccopt_property target_skew  <value>).  If  this
       parameter  is  not set, the software will use the default value that it
       gets from get_ccopt_property target_skew. For example:  get_ccopt_prop-
       erty target_skew The software returns the following value: 2
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 20c2r2eate_ccopt_skew_group(21.15)

create_clock(21.15)                                        create_clock(21.15)



[1mName  create_clock  [22m-  Creates  a clock object and defines its waveform in the
       current design
[1mSyntax create_clock [22m-period  <period_value>  [-name  <clock_name>]  [-waveform
       <edge_list>] [-add] [-comment <string>] [<sources>]
[1mParameters  -add [22mSpecifies multiple clocks on the same source for simultaneous
       analysis with different clock waveforms. You  must  specify  the  -name
       parameter  with  this parameter. [1m-comment <string> [22mAllows you to insert
       comments. The comments are read but are ignored with a one-time warning
       message.  They  are  not  used during timing analysis reporting nor are
       they written out during saving of constraints. [1m-name <clock_name> [22mSpec-
       ifies  the  string name of the ideal clock being created. If you do not
       specify this option, the clock gets the same name as  the  first  clock
       source  that you specify using the -sources option. If you do not spec-
       ify any sources, you must specify the -name <clock_name> option,  which
       creates  a  virtual  clock  not  associated with a port or pin. [1m-period[0m
       [1m<period_value> [22mSpecifies the value of the ideal clock in  library  time
       units. [1m<sources> [22mSpecifies the list of pins or ports associated with an
       ideal clock waveform of the clock. If you do not specify  this  option,
       you must specify the -name <clock_name> option, which creates a virtual
       clock not associated with a port or pin. If you specify a  clock  on  a
       pin  that  already  has  a  clock,  the new clock replaces the old one.
       [1m-waveform <edge_list> [22mSpecifies the rise and fall  edge  times  of  the
       clock  waveforms in library time units over an entire clock period. The
       first value in the edge list is the time at which the first  transition
       on  the  clock  occurs, which is the first rising transition after time
       zero, and edges are monotonically increasing. The numbers should repre-
       sent  one  full  clock  period.  If  you  do  not specify the -waveform
       <edge_list> option, a default waveform is assumed, and the leading edge
       is  placed  at 0 and the trailing edge is placed at the midpoint of the
       period, such that a symmetric clock is generated.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022        create_clock(21.15)

[1mName  create_current_region  [22m-  Specifies static or dynamic current regions on
       global power-grids over the placed macro to accurately capture high and
       low current consuming regions during rail analysis
[1mSyntax create_current_region [22m[-help] -reset | {-region <x1 y1 x2 y2> [-current
       <value>|  -current_pwl_file<filename>]  [-die_instance_name   <dieinst-
       name>] [-file <filename>] [-layer <layername>] [-intrinsic_cap <value>]
       [-loading_cap  <value>]  [-series_resistance<value>]   [-net<net_name>]
       [-polygon {<x1> <y1> <x2> <y2> <x3> <y3>
[1mParameters -current <value> [22mIn the static mode (set_rail_analysis_mode -method
       static), the parameter specifies a single current value in mAmp. In the
       dynamic  mode  (set_rail_analysis_mode  -method  dynamic) the parameter
       specifies a PWL current waveform in time (in ns) and  current  (in  mA)
       format.  For  example,  0ns  0mA 0.5ns 1mA 1ns 2mA 3ns 1mA 4ns 0. [1m-cur-[0m
       [1mrent_pwl_file<filename> [22mSpecifies a PWL current file. The file has  two
       columns,  time (in ns) and current value (in mA), as shown below: time1
       value1 time2 value2 The -current_pwl_file and -current  parameters  are
       mutually exclusive. [1m-die_instance_name <dieinstname> [22mSpecifies the name
       of the die to which you need to apply a current region. This  parameter
       is  only  applicable  to  the  multi-die analysis flow (set_rail_analy-
       sis_mode -die_mode multi-die). The parameter allows you  to  accurately
       assign  current  to power and ground nets in specific geometric regions
       for individual dies during rail analysis in 3D-IC designs. [1m-file <file-[0m
       [1mname>  [22mSpecifies  the  name  of  a  file containing the list of current
       regions  for  each   die.   -file   can   be   used   only   with   the
       -die_instance_name  parameter.  The other parameters of the create_cur-
       rent_region command can be included within the specified file. Example:
       create_current_region       -file      <create_current_region_die0.tcl>
       -die_instance_name  Die0   create_current_region   -file   <create_cur-
       rent_region_die1.tcl>  -die_instance_name Die1 ###File content in <cre-
       ate_current_region_die0.tcl> -net VDD -current 50mA -layer  M2  -region
       10  10 100 100 -net VDD -current 50mA -layer M2 -region 100 100 200 200
       -net VSS -current 100mA -layer M1 -region 10 10 200 200 ###File content
       in  <create_current_region_die1.tcl>  -net VDD -current 150mA -layer M2
       -region 10 10 50 50 -net VDD -current 50mA -layer M2  -region  100  100
       200  200  -net VSS -current 200mA -layer M1 -region 10 10 200 200 [1m-help[0m
       Outputs a brief description that includes the type and default informa-
       tion  for each create_current_region parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command  man
       create_current_region. [1m-gndnet<net_name> [22mSpecifies a ground net name on
       which the specified current is to be  applied.  [1m-intrinsic_cap  <value>[0m
       Specifies  the  cell intrinsic capacitance in pico farads (pf). This is
       required parameter when set in the dynamic mode (set_rail_analysis_mode
       -method  dynamic).  This  parameter  is disabled in static mode. [1m-layer[0m
       [1m<layername> [22mSpecifies a layer name on which the scaling  will  be  per-
       formed. Multiple commands can be issued to scale resistance on multiple
       layers. This is a required parameter. [1m-loading_cap value [22mSpecifies  the
       cell  loading capacitance in pico farads (pf). This is required parame-
       ter when  set  in  the  dynamic  mode  (set_rail_analysis_mode  -method
       dynamic).  This  parameter  is  disabled in static mode. [1m-net<net_name>[0m
       Specifies a net name on which the specified current is to  be  applied.
       [1m-polygon {<x1> <y1> <x2> <y2> <x3> <y3>[0m

create_die_model(21.15)                                create_die_model(21.15)



[1mName  create_die_model  [22m-  Specifies to generate a reduced n-port die model in
       the form of equivalent die parasitic and  current  profile  after  rail
       analysis  to  perform  system-level analysis with extracted package and
       board models
[1mSyntax create_die_model [22m[-accuracy {xd  |  hd  }]  [-output_directory  <direc-
       tory_name>]  -state_directory  <directory_name>  [-rail_analysis_domain
       <domain_name> | -net <net_name>] [-repeat  <time>]  [-probing_node_file
       <file_name>]   [-use_sigrity_repeat]   [-max_ports_per_net   <integer>]
       [-enable_package_pin_map {true false}] [-enable_reference_node]  [-dis-
       able_global_node_zero  {  true|false  }]  [-multi_die  {true  | false}]
       [-port_grouping_by_ploc_files {true false}]  [-port_grouping_file<file-
       name>]   [-temp_directory_name   <directory>]  [-effective_rc]  [-prob-
       ing_region_file<filename>]      [-effective_rc_deck]      [-port_group-
       ing_tiles_file     <filename>]     [-enable_xp    {true    |    false}]
       [-ignore_port_grouping_conflict]   [-generate_sipi_port_definition_file
       {true | false}]
[1mParameters -accuracy {xd | hd } [22mSpecifies the accuracy mode for die-model gen-
       eration. Default : hd
[1mExample probe_1 18 16 METAL_1 VDD  #  pkg  node  voltage  probe_pkg_1  pkg  ir[0m
       [1mGND.in0   probe_pkg_6   pkg   ir   VDD.in2   #   pkg  resistor  current[0m
       [1mprobe_pkg_cur_1 pkg rc R_1_1 probe_pkg_cur_2 pkg  rc  R_5_2  Note:  The[0m
       [1munits  of  x  and y should be in microns. -probing_region_file   <file-[0m
       [1mname> [22mSpecifies a probe node region file to define a probe  region  and
       use  all  points  in the region as probe contact points on the die. The
       file  format  for  specifying  a  probing   region   is   as   follows:
       <region_label  x1  y1  x2 y2 layer_name net_name> [1m-rail_analysis_domain[0m
       [1m<domain_name> | -net <net_name> [22mSpecifies the domain name or  net  name
       for  which  the  die-model  is to be generated. When the domain name is
       specified, coupled die-model is generated and it includes all power and
       ground  nets  associated  with  the  specified domain. When net name is
       specified, decoupled die-model is  generated  for  the  specified  net.
       Before  specifying  this  command parameter, the power net name must be
       specified using the set_pg_nets command. This is a required option  and
       one of them must be specified. [1m-repeat <time> [22mSpecifies the repeat time
       in ns. When this parameter is specified without the -use_sigrity_repeat
       parameter,  the  generated die model has the dynamic current profile of
       the die repeated to the specified time. By default, the die model  con-
       sists  of  the default simulation period saved in dynamic current files
       during IR drop anlaysis. When this parameter is  specified  along  with
       the  -use_sigrity_repeat  parameter,  the  software forces to write out
       repeating  waveforms  in  the   Sigrity   specific   format.   If   the
       -use_sigrity_repeat parameter is specified, the value specified through
       the -repeat parameter indicates the starting  point  of  the  repeating
       waveform.  [1m-state_directory  <directory_name>  [22mSpecifies  the top-level
       state directory that is generated by the  static  or  dynamic  IR  drop
       analysis. This state directory contains analysis of all nets associated
       with the power domain;  For  example,  core_25C_dynamic_1.  This  is  a
       required parameter. [1m-temp_directory_name <directory> [22mSpecifies a direc-
       tory   to   save   temporary   files    for    die-model    generation.
       [1m-use_sigrity_repeat  [22mWhen  this  parameter  is specified along with the
       -repeat parameter of the create_die_model command, the software  forces
       to write out repeating waveforms in the Sigrity specific format. If the
       -use_sigrity_repeat parameter is specified, the value specified through
       the  -repeat  parameter  indicates  the starting point of the repeating
       waveform.  If  -use_sigrity_repeat  is  specified  without   specifying
       -repeat,  time  0  is used for the starting point. The default unit for
       the value is ns . Note: When the -use_sigrity_repeat parameter is spec-
       ified,  the  software  will  write the stimulus current in the specific
       Sigrity format, which cannot be used by other Spice like simulators.

create_generated_clock(21.15)                    create_generated_clock(21.15)



[1mName  create_generated_clock [22m- Creates a new clock signal from the clock wave-
       form of a given pin in the design, and binds it with the pins or  hier-
       archical pins in the <target_pin_list> argument
[1mSyntax   create_generated_clock  [22m[-help]  <target_pin_list>  [-add]  [-comment
       <string>]  [-duty_cycle  <percent>]   [-edge_shift   <edge_shift_list>]
       [-invert]   [-master_clock  <source_clock_name>]  [-name  <clock_nam>>]
       -source <source_pin>  {[-multiply_by  <factor>]  [-divide_by  <factor>]
       [-edges <edge_list>] [-combinational]}
[1mParameters  -help [22mPrints out the command usage. [1m-add [22mModels multiple generated
       clocks on the same source when multiple clocks must fan into the source
       pin. Ideally, one generated clock must be specified for each clock that
       fans into the master pin. Specify this option with the -name and  -mas-
       ter_clock options. By default, the software creates one generated clock
       at the pin by using the fastest clock present on the source pin as  the
       master clock. However, use the -add option to specify a different clock
       name for each generated clock when used with the -master_clock  option.
       Subsequently,  you  can  use  this  clock  name  for setting other con-
       straints, such as the set_false_path command  and  the  set_input_delay
       command.  [1m-combinational  [22mRestricts the path search for latency to only
       paths which do not cross sequential devices,  or  the  source  pins  of
       other  generated  clocks. When you specify -combinational, if there are
       both sequential and combinational latency paths, the software only con-
       siders the combinational paths for the generated clock. If there are no
       combinational latency paths for  the  generated  clock,  the  generated
       clock  does  not  inherit  latency  from its parent clock hierarchy. By
       default, when calculating the latency of a generated clock,  the  soft-
       ware  searches  for  the  longest  (and shortest) paths from the parent
       waveform to the  generated  clock  point.  All  paths  are  considered,
       including  those which traverse sequential elements such as flip-flops,
       registers, and latches. The default  behavior  is  intended  for  cases
       where  there  is  a cascade of generated clocks, and some of the clocks
       are not explicitly defined. The -combinational option can  be  used  in
       conjunction with the -multiply_by, -divide_by, or -edges options. [1m-com-[0m
       [1mment <string>   [22mAllows you to insert comments. The  comments  are  read
       but are ignored with a one-time warning message. They are not used dur-
       ing timing analysis reporting nor are they written out during saving of
       constraints.  [1m-divide_by  <integer> [22mDetermines the frequency of the new
       clock by dividing the frequency of the source clock by  <dfactor>.  For
       example,  if  <dfactor=5>,  the new frequency is 1/5 of the source fre-
       quency, and the new clock period is 5 times the  source  clock  period.
       [1m-duty_cycle  <percent>  [22mSets  the duty cycle (high pulse width or clock
       period). The number (<percent>) is between 0 and 100. For  example,  if
       <percent=50>,  the  high  pulse  width of the new clock waveform is the
       same as its low pulse width. Note: The -duty_cycle option can  only  be
       used  with the -multiply_by option, otherwise it will be ignored with a
       warning. [1m-edges <edge_list> [22mSelects a list of  edges  from  the  source
       clock that form the edges of the derived clock. See the frequency divi-
       sion example below. [1m-edge_shift <edge_shift_list> [22mSpecifies the  amount
       of  shift  for  each edge in the <edge_list>option. The amount of shift
       will be in library time units. [1m-invert [22mInverts the  source  clock.  Use
       with  t<standard input>:34: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:38: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:44: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
he  -source  option  and the -multiply_by or -divide_by options.
       [1m-master_clock  <source_clock_name> [22mGenerates a target  clock  from  the
       specified  clock name. If you specify the -master_clock option and mul-
       tiple signals arrive at the source pin, the  clock  specified  by  this
       option  is  used  to  generate the target clock. Use the -add parameter
       along with-master_clock parameter to add a clock to the existing  clock
       when  you want to specify multiple clocks on the same source for simul-
       taneous analysis. [1m-multiply_by  <integer> [22mDetermines the  frequency  of
       the  new  clock  by  multiplying  the  frequency of the source clock by
       <mfactor>. For example, if <mfactor=4>, the new frequency  is  4  times
       the  source  frequency,  and  the new clock period is 1/4 of the source
       clock period. [1m-name <clock_signame> [22mSpecifies the name for  the  gener-
       ated  clock. Default: The system creates a name for you. Always specify
       a name for the generated clock. Some commands issue an error if you use
       the  system-generated  name. [1m-source <source_pin> [22mSpecifies the name of
       the source pin from which the new clock is to be  derived.  This  is  a
       mandatory  option.  [1m<target_pin_list>  [22mSpecifies the list of pins where
       the generated clock assertion is applied. The clock signal  propagating
       downstream  from  each of these pins becomes associated with the gener-
       ated clock.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 202c2reate_generated_clock(21.15)

       -gds_port_file     <gds_port_file>]    [-libgen_command_file    <file>]

       erence_libs>]     [-powergrid_view_libraries      <primitive_cells.cl>]

[1mParameters -block_lef <lef_file> [22mSpecifies the name of the block LEF file. The
       <lef_file> must have all power pin  port  geometries  defined  for  the
       hierarchical  block. [1m-block_gds <gds_file> [22mIn absence of block LEF, you
       can specify block GDS and port  label  file  to  generate  hierarchical
       power-grid  view.  [1m-cell_name  <name>  [22mSpecifies the block cell name as
       specified in the block DEF file.  [1m-cluster_via1_ports  {true  |  false}[0m
       Designs with follow-pin routing on M1 and M2 layers have standard cells
       library LEF with M1, M2, and VIA1 ports. This  parameter  specifies  to
       cluster  VIA1  ports for such cells in order to improve overall extrac-
       tion and rail analysis performance. Default: true This parameter is set
       to true by default to improve VIA1 port handling in designs with M1 and
       M2 follow-pin routing. This parameter gives significantly  better  per-
       formance by clustering equidistant VIA1 ports defined in cell LEF with-
       out significant loss of accuracy. However, if you specify a  clustering
       rule, the user specification takes precedence over automated VIA1 clus-
       tering.   [1m-cluster_via_rule   {    {<via_layer1>    <number_of_equidis-[0m
       [1mtant_vias>}...}  [22mControls  the  number  of  vias  to cluster on a layer
       basis. The VIA clustering rule  specified  using  this  parameter  will
       override  the  default  clustering  rule for a given accuracy mode. The
       following command will cluster 100 equidistant VIA1 cuts, 200  equidis-
       tant  VIA2 cuts, and 300 equidistant VIA7 cuts: create_hier_view -clus-
       ter_via_rule { {VIA1 100}} {VIA2 200} {VIA7 300}} The rest of the  VIAs
       will  be clustered using the default clustering rule depending upon the
       rail analysis accuracy mode. [1m-cluster_via_size  <value>  [22mSpecifies  the
       size  of  the  via  array  to cluster all via layers except VIA1 (layer
       between Metal1 and Metal2). The default value is 625 (25x25 via array),
       except  when  running  static  analysis  using HD mode. The default for
       static HD mode is 16 (4x4), primarily to preserve more accuracy for  EM
       analysis.  Default:  625  [1m-compress_powergrid_database  {true  | false}[0m
       Specifies to compress the output files generated by extraction and rail
       analysis  to  save  disk space usage. This parameter reduces disk space
       requirement from the extraction and rail analysis  stages  at  approxi-
       mately    5-10%    performance    penalty.    Default:    false    [1m-def[0m
       [1m<list_of_DEF_files> [22mSpecifies a list of block DEF files for  hierarchi-
       cal analysis. [1m-extraction_mode {fast | accurate} [22mDetermines what power-

[1mName  create_library_set  [22m-  Associates  a  TCL  list  of  timing  and cdB/UDN

       associate the library list with a specific  delay  calculation  corner.
       [1m-si  <string>  [22mSpecifies  cdB libraries and/or user-defined noise (UDN)
       models to include in the library set. The cdB and/or UDN libraries  are
       required for performing signal integrity analysis. Note: You cannot use
       this parameter for CCS-N or ECSM-N models,  that  is,  for  cdBs  only.
       [1m-socv  <string>  [22mSpecifies the SOCV libraries to include in the library
       set. [1m-timing <string> [22mSpecifies the timing libraries to include in  the
       library  set.  Note: Libraries intended for use in an ECSM-based multi-
       library interpolation must be grouped within an additional level of Tcl
       list structure to identify the intended usage to the library subsystem.
       Specify three timing libraries  that  are  characterized  at  different
       voltages  (typically  the  lower  and upper voltage bounds, and a third
       intermediate point). All voltages required  by  the  software  will  be
       interpolated  from  this set of libraries. The libraries in the set can
       differ only in the characterization voltage; they must be identical  to
       each other in all other aspects. However, if you want to perform multi-
       temperature based library interpolation, you can use two library  files
       that  are  characterized  at  different  temperatures  for each voltage
       value. See the examples for creating an  ECSM-based  multi-library  set
       and  multi-temperature based library interpolation in the Examples sec-
       tion. Note: The ECSM and CCS libraries can be very  large  and  loading
       them may take significant time. You can convert the ASCII NLDM (Liberty

create_parasitic_coordinate_transfocrrme(a2t1e._1p5a)rasitic_coordinate_transform(21.15)



[1mName  create_parasitic_coordinate_transform  [22m-  Determines  accurate  location
       information of nodes during SPEF reading.
[1mSyntax  create_parasitic_coordinate_transform   [22m[-help]   {-inst   <inst_name>
       [-x_block_origin <value>] [-x_offset< value>] [-y_block_origin <value>]
       [-y_offset <value>] [-orient {R0 R90 R180 R270 MY MX90 MX MY90}] [-rel-

       voltage sources. [1m-cell {<cell_list>} [22mSpecifies  the  cells  from  which

       [1m-delete     [22mDeletes the location of a voltage source from memory. [1m-dis-[0m
       [1mplay [22mLoads and displays the pad location data from the specified  file.
       [1m-format   {padcell  |  xy  |  tsv} [22mThe format of the saved pad location
       file. The choices are Pad File  (VoltageStorm),  XY  File  (xy  coordi-
       nates),  and  TSV. You can create and save the voltage sources location
       file with a unique name for the voltage sources  (both  VDD  and  VSS).
       Default:  xy  [1m-help  [22mOutputs  the command usage and a brief description
       about the command parameters.  [1m-honor_pin_connection  [22mHonors  pin  wire
       connection when fetching voltage source location from a power pad. When
       you specify this parameter, only pins with wire connection  are  output
       as  voltage  sources.  You have the choice to specify whether real wire
       connection is to be honored or  not.  Typically,  during  the  sign-off
       stage,  power  pads  are  already fully routed so the unconnected power
       pads should not be counted in as voltage sources. You can specify  this
       using  the -honor_pin_connection parameter. Alternatively, in the early
       stage, power pads may not have been fully routed so you do not need  to
       set  this  parameter.  Note: For a port with shapes at multiple layers,
       all layer connected shapes are fetched as  voltage  sources.  [1m-instance[0m

       [1m<pinnamen}+>} [22mSpecifies the instances and their pins from which voltage
       sources are determined. [1m-layer layerName [22mSpecifies the process layer in
       LEF  on  which the voltage sources are to be generated. When the -layer
       parameter is specified in conjunction with the -region {x1  y1  x2  y2}
       and -region_pitch {xpitch ypitch} parameters, the layer set here is the
       layer for which voltage sources are to be fetched. If the -layer param-
       eter  is  not  used  together  with  the  -region  {x1  y1  x2  y2} and
       -region_pitch {xpitch ypitch} parameters, the layer set here is for the
       lowest  layer  to  snap (the default value is M5). [1m-list [22mLoads and dis-
       plays all voltage s<standard input>:15: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

ources from memory. [1m-loc {x y} [22mSpecifies  the  loca-

       automatically  lists  DC  sources  for  all  nets.  [1m-package_resistance[0m

       snapping distance constraint from IO/pad pins. If this parameter is not
       specified  with a value, no snapping will be done. Default: 0 Specifies
       whether to snap DC sources from I/O pad pins to some  location  on  the
       power structure. When set to true, the software performs autofetch with
       snapping. For I/O pad pins that are connected to core ring,  the  soft-
       ware  selects  the highest layer and center of the pin as the DC source
       location. When I/O pad pins are not connected to core ring,  the  soft-
       ware  snaps  the location of the I/O pad to somewhere on the core ring.
       The DC source location should be within the distance of  snapping  dis-
       tance  constraint  from I/O pad pins, and the layer should not be lower
       than the lowest layer snap constraint. [1m-vsrc_file <vsrc_filename> [22mSpec-
       ifies  the name of the voltage source file that is required to save the
       auto fetched result.

       capacitance  table  or the Quantus technology file. [1m-via_variation_file[0m

       variation  file lists up all the VIA layer names with the corresponding
       multiplier. Each RC corner can have its own  VIA  variation  file.  For
       example: create_rc_corner -rc_corner rcCornerName1  -via_variation_file
       viaVariationFileName1   create_rc_corner    -rc_corner    rcCornerName2
       -via_variation_file viaVariationFileName2

[1mName  create_relative_floorplan  [22m-  The create_relative_floorplan command cap-
       tures and defines the placement relationship of floorplan objects inde-
       pendently  from the actual coordinates in a floorplan, and resizes mod-
       ules or blackboxes based on other floorplan objects, even  outside  the
       core boundary. You can use this command after importing the design
[1mSyntax  create_relative_floorplan [22m[-help] {{{-place <obj_name_list> | -reshape
       <obj_name_list>} [-ref ref_<obj_name_list>]}}  [-place  <obj_name_list>

       {{<edge1 edge2>}...}] [-density<>{<value>}] [-offset {<value>}]]]
[1mParameters  -bbox  {none  target  reference  both}  [22mSpecifies whether to use a

       object.  Default:  none Data_type: enum_list, optional [1m-density< value>[0m
       Specifies the target utilization (TU). By default, reshaping the object
       will  keep  the  current  TU.  Data_type:  string,  optional [1m-dimension[0m
       [1m{<width height>} [22mSpecifies the width or height of the referenced object
       as  the  reference  dimension.  Default:  width  Data_type:  enum_list,

       will be stretched while fixing two perpendicular edges. Default: {-1 0}

       [1mzontal  y_offset  obj_edge_horizontal>}  [22mSpecifies the vertical spacing

       tive_floorplan parameter. For a detailed description of the command and
       all of its parameters, use the man command: man  create_relative_floor-

       object in the specified dimension. Data_type: string, optional  [1m-orient[0m

       [1m<obj_name_list>  [22mSpecifies the target object to place. It can be hInst,

       blockages, port, or pin. It cannot be used with -ref_type core_boundary
       or  -ref_type  die_boundary.  Data_type:  string,  optional   [1m-ref_type[0m
       [1m{object  core_boundary  die_boundary}  [22mSpecifies the type of reference.

create_route_type(21.15)                              create_route_type(21.15)



[1mName create_route_type [22m- Creates a new route type and sets the routing proper-
       ties for the nets
[1mSyntax  create_route_type   [22m[-help]   [-em_ndr_dist   <float>]   [-em_ndr_rule
       <rule_name>] [-min_stack_layer <layer>] -name <string> [-one_side_spac-
       ing_range     <bottomLayerNum:topLayerNum>]     [-prefer_multi_cut_via]
       [-shield_side   {one_side  |  both_side}]  [-shield_tap_instance_inser-
       tion_effort  {none  |  standard  |  high}]  [-stack_distance   <float>]
       [[-non_default_rule  <ndr_name>]  [-shield_net  <net_name>]  [-top_pre-
       ferred_layer   <layer>]   [-bottom_preferred_layer   <layer>]    [-pre-
       ferred_routing_layer_effort  {low  | medium | high}]] [-mask <mask_num-
       ber> [-layer_mask_range <bottomLayerNum:topLayerNum>]]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each  create_route_type  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  create_route_type [1m-bottom_preferred_layer <layer> [22mSpecifies
       the preferred lowest routing layer. This attribute  is  a  soft  limit,
       which  means,  NanoRoute might use a layer below the specified layer if
       necessary to complete routing. A layer name can be any real layer name,
       for  example,  from  LEF or OpenAccess. Routing layer names can also be
       abbreviated as 1 or metal1 for the first routing layer, 2 or metal2 for
       the  second routing layer, and so on. Note, the software will check for
       real layer names first. So, if metal1 matches  a  real  layer  name  it
       might not be the first routing layer. If not specified, the router will
       freely route the net starting on the first routing layer, with no pref-
       erence  for  higher layers. [1m-em_ndr_dist <float> [22mSpecifies the distance
       related to the output pin, when em_ndr_rule is applied to the net. When
       routing  outside  this  distance  range, the router either uses regular
       wire or regular non-default routing (NDR), if the regular  NDR  setting
       is enabled in this net. Note: When the -em_ndr_rule option is used with
       the command, the -em_ndr_rule option  becomes  mandatory.  [1m-em_ndr_rule[0m
       [1m<rule_name>  [22mSpecifies  the  EM  NDR  rule to associate with this route
       type. When routing within the distance specified in -em_dist from  out-
       put  pin,  router  will  use this ndr rule to route. Default: No EM NDR
       rule [1m-layer_mask_range <bottomLayerNum:topLayerNum> [22mSpecifies the layer
       range  that  the  mask constrain should be applied on. For example, 3:4
       means that the constrain should be applied on metal3 and metal4.  [1m-mask[0m
       [1mmask_number  [22mSpecifies the mask number in allowed range (min=0, max=3).
       [1m-min_stack_layer <layer> [22mSpecifies that the output pins of the net  use
       stacked vias from the pin to the given <layer> and the rest of the con-
       nections start from the mentioned <layer>. [1m-name <string> [22mSpecifies the
       name  of  the  route  type  object. This is required. [1m-non_default_rule[0m
       [1m<ndr_name> [22mSpecifies the non-default routing (NDR)  rule  to  associate
       with  this  route_type. Default is no NDR rule. [1m-one_side_spacing_range[0m
       [1m<bottomLayerNum:topLayerNum> [22mSpecifies the layer range  that  one  side
       spacing  constrain  should  be  applied  on. By default, NDR spacing is
       applied to both sides of an NDR net or wire. Use this option to specify
       the layer range for wires that have only one neighboring wire with min-
       imum spacing, which means only one side  needs  to  follow  larger  NDR
       spacing.  [1m-prefer_multi_cut_via  [22mSpecifies  whether  or  not to use the
       multi-cut vias for connections at the net driver pins. [1m-preferred_rout-[0m
       [1ming_layer_effort  {low | medium | high} [22mSpecifies whether the preferred
       routing layer effort will be low, medium or high. This parameter deter-
       mines  how  flexible  the NanoRoute router is when setting layer limits
       for routing specified nets.  Use  this  parameter  with  the  -top_pre-
       ferred_routing_layer  and  -bottom_preferred_routing_layer  parameters.
       Specify medium or high routing layer effort  level  to  make  NanoRoute
       less  flexible  in  setting  layer  limits  for routing specified nets.
       NanoRoute will obey the preferred routing layer  range  more  strictly.
       Specify low to make NanoRoute more flexible in setting layer limits for
       routing specified nets. Default: low [1m-shield_net <net_name> [22mSpecifies a
       special  net to use as a shield for a critical or high-speed net. Typi-
       cally, a shielded net is routed before routing other net. You can spec-
       ify only one shield net. However, you cannot control which side is used
       by the special net that is routed on the same layer as the signal rout-
       ing.  The  shield terminates near the pin. If not specified, the net is
       not shielded. [1m-shield_side {one_side | both_side} [22mSpecifies whether  to
       perform  one sided or two sided shielding for the route type specified.
       [1m-shield_tap_instance_insertion_effort {none | standard |  high}  [22mSpeci-
       fies  the clock route type for clock shielding of the high and low fre-
       quencies through the high and standard values  respectively.  The  main
       difference  between  these values is related to the ground that the tie
       cell instance/via uses to achieve shield  segments  of  the  electrical
       connection.  [1m-stack_distance <float> [22mSpecifies that the cut distance of
       cuts  on  adjacent  layers  in  the  stacked  vias   are   defined   in
       -min_stack_layer.  [1m-top_preferred_layer  <layer> [22mSpecifies the top-pre-
       ferred layer for the route type.
[1mExample[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022   create_route_type(21.15)

[1mName ctd_trace [22m- Highlights the clock tree path from the clock root to the pin
       or from one pin to the other if the two pins are on the same path using
       the specified color or color index
[1mSyntax ctd_trace [22m[-help] [-color <colorname>] [-file <fileName>] [-from <root-
       clock>] [-index <colorindex>] [-to sink | -through <instancename>]
[1mParameters -help       [22mOutputs a brief  description  that  includes  type  and
       default  information  for  each  ctd_trace  parameter.  For  a detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man ctd_trace. [1m-color <colorname> [22mSpecifies the color to be used
       for highlighting the clock tree path that is being traced. Default: red
       [1m-file  <fileName>  [22mSpecifies the name of the file in which the physical
       information for each instance and net in the clock  path  being  traced
       will  be  dumped.  The  following  information  is  saved  in the file:
       (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference
       -  Release 21.1 manual.) Name is the instance name or the net name Cell
       is the instance cell type. This information is only for instances  Sta-
       tus is the place status for an instance and constrain status for a net.
       For dont_touch nets, the status is 'dont_touch', otherwise this  column
       is  left blank Location is the physical location of the instance or the
       coordinate of that instance Wire Length is only for nets [1m-from  <clock-[0m
       [1mroot>  [22mSpecifies  the  instance name as the starting point of the high-
       light. If this parameter is not specified, the starting  point  of  the
       highlight  is  the clock root of the specified sink. [1m-index<colorindex>[0m
       Specifies the range of colors that can be used to highlight  the  clock
       tree path. Minimum is 1 and maximum is 32. The range corresponds to the
       colors in the color picker provided in the Highlight Clock Path  option
       in the context menu of the Clock Tree Viewer. The number 1 means red, 2
       means blue, and so on. An example is shown in the image below. Default:
       1 or red. [1m-through <instancename> [22mSpecifies the instance or pin through
       which the path should be traced. [1m-to <sink> [22mSpecifies the end point  of
       the highlighted path.

ctd_win(21.15)                                                  ctd_win(21.15)



[1mName  ctd_win [22m- Opens a Clock Tree Debugger (CTD) window with the user-defined
       window ID and title
[1mSyntax    ctd_win    [22m[-help]    [-id     <windowIDName>]     [-include_report-
       ing_only_skew_groups] [-title <CTDWindowID>] [-unit_delay]
[1mParameters  -help         [22mOutputs  a  brief description that includes type and
       default information for each ctd_win parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       ctd_win. [1m-id <windowIDName>   [22mOpens a Clock Tree Debugger window with a
       user-specified window ID. By default, the window IDs will be ctdMain_0,
       or ctdMain_1, and so on. [1m-include_reporting_only_skew_groups [22mWhen  this
       parameter  is  specified,  the  GUI  displays  the  reporting-only skew
       groups. A reporting-only skew group is a skew  group  whose  constrains
       property  is  set to none. Such a skew group imposes no clock balancing
       constraint and is not considered by CTS. By default,  this  setting  if
       off,  which  means  the reporting-only skew groups are omitted from the
       CTD. Note: Once the CTD is  started,  you  cannot  add  or  remove  the
       reporting-only  skew  groups from those that are displayed. Start a new
       CTD window to specify the skew group  filtering.  [1m-title  <CTDWindowID>[0m
       Specifies  the user-defined title for the CTD window. Open a Clock Tree
       Debugger window with a user specified title. For example, if you  spec-
       ify my_title as the window title, when session title is my_test.tcl and
       the primary analysis corner is primary_corner, then the  total  set  of
       the  window  title  line  will  be: my_test.tcl : Clock Tree Debugger :
       my_title Note: The window's ID if not specified using the  -id  parame-
       ter,  will be system default ID. To view the default window ID, use the
       get_ctd_win_id command. [1m-unit_delay [22mOpens the CTD  in  the  unit  delay
       mode. The unit delay lets you view the depth of clock tree objects eas-
       ily. This is useful when you have large designs  with  deep  gate-level
       trees.  When  debugging clock trees, you can use this view to check how
       the clock trees are balanced by looking  at  the  depth  of  the  clock
       trees. Although, the unit delay mode can also be enabled using the Unit
       delay submenu in the Visibility menu of the CTD but this is only  valid
       after running clock tree synthesis, and you still need to invoke timing
       calculation and extraction, which are time consuming. You can use  this
       parameter  to open the CTD in unit delay mode even if the design is not
       placed or without performing CTS. When the CTD is opened in this  mode,
       the following options in CTD menus are disabled: Visibility menu:
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022             ctd_win(21.15)

[1mName  cutRow  [22m-  Cuts  site  rows  within  an  area or that intersect with the

[1mSyntax cutRow [22m[-help] [-area <box>|  -object  <string>|  -selected  |  -fromIo
       {<left bottom right top>}] [-halo <float>| {-leftGap <float>| -rightGap
       <float>| -topGap <float>| -bottomGap <float>}] [-site  <name>]  [-keep-
       Cell]
[1mParameters -area <box> [22mRows will be cut within the specified box. box is a tcl
       list containing 4 items. The items are, in order: LLX, LLY,  URX,  URY.
       Note: The -halo parameter cannot be applied -area used. Data_type: box,
       optional [1m-bottomGap <float>   [22mSpecifies the additional gap to  be  pro-

       Data_type: box, optional [1m-halo <float> [22mSpecifies additional space to be
       provided on the top, bottom, left, and right sides of the objects caus-

       value is used for all sides. Data_type: float, optional [1m-help [22mOutputs a

       to  be  provided  on the left side of the specified or selected object.

       intersecting  object. Rows that intersect this object are cut. Only one
       name may be specified. Data_type: string,  optional  [1m-rightGap  <float>[0m
       Specifies  the  additional  gap to be provided on the right side of the
       specified or selected  object.  Data_type:  float,  optional  [1m-selected[0m
       Specifies that the rows that intersect with the selected object(s) will
       be cut. Note: Only supports inst, hinst,  power  domain,  group,  place
       blockage,  route_blockage,  and  bump as selected object(s). Data_type:
       bool, optional [1m-site <name> [22mRows containing  site  name  will  be  cut.
       Default:  All rows in the core box are cut. Data_type: string, optional
       [1m-topGap <float> [22mSpecifies the additional gap to be provided on the  top
       side of the specified or selected object. Data_type: float, optional

       fies  the  values  in database units, specified in integers. This is an

       Valid orientation values are: R0, R180, R90, R270, MY, MX, MX90,  MY90.

debug_irdrop(21.15)                                        debug_irdrop(21.15)



[1mName  debug_irdrop [22m- Specifies to automatically identify the region with worst
       IRdrops and EM violations, and provide necessary information to  deter-
       mine  and  fix  the  root  cause. The reports are consolidated for each
       region to find root-cause
[1mSyntax debug_irdrop  [22m[-help]  [-nworst_instances  <value>]  [-output_directory
       <dir>]  -state_directory  <dir> [-net <netname> | -domain <domainname>]
       [-region {x1 y1 x2 y2 }| -nregion <value>] [-eco_report]  [-net_thresh-
       old  <value>  |  -domain_threshold  <value>]  [-tile_row_col {<X> <Y>}]
       [-tile_size {<X> <Y>}] [-non_violating_instslimit <value>]  [-enable_xp
       {true | false}]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description  that  includes the type and
       default information for each debug_irdrop  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man com-
       mand man debug_irdrop. [1m-domain <domainname> [22mSpecifies the name  of  the
       power  domain.  [1m-domain_threshold <value> [22mSpecifies the minimum allowed
       voltage for the domain being analyzed. The value will be in percentage.
       This   parameter  behavior  is  same  as  the  set_rail_analysis_domain
       -threshold parameter. [1m-eco_report [22mSpecifies to generate a file with  IR
       drop  information that can be used by Tempus ECO to fix IR voltage drop
       for all instances in a design. The report (eco.ird) is generated in the
       specified   output   directory   (   debug_irdrop   -output_directory).
       [1m-enable_xp {true | false} [22mSpecifies to identify the worst IR  drop  and
       EM  violations  regions  in  the Extensively Parallel (XP) mode wherein
       processing is distributed over a large number of  machines.  Default  :
       false [1m-net <netname> [22mSpecifies the name of the power or ground net that
       you want to  analyze.  [1m-net_threshold  <value>  [22mSpecifies  the  minimum
       allowed  voltage for the power net being analyzed. The value must be an
       absolute number. This parameter behavior is  same  as  the  set_pg_nets
       -threshold  parameter.  [1m-non_violating_instslimit  <value> [22mReports non-
       violating instances within hotspots (violating tiles) that are close to
       the  threshold value. This parameter allows you to define a limit (sub-
       threshold) that can be used to report the non-violating instances  that
       are close to the threshold.

defIn(21.15)                                                      defIn(21.15)



[1mName defIn [22m- Loads the specified DEF file. defIn can be used at any step after
       importing a design
[1mSyntax defIn [22m[-help] <fileName>  [-add_blockage]  [-allWarning]  [-components]
       [-deleteBump]  [-deleteSpecialRoute] [-ignore_drcfill] [-ignore_pg_con-
       nectivity]  [-nets]  [-preserveShape]   [-removeHalfWireExtensionOnPin]
       [-specialnets]    [-specialRouteUserClass   <user_class_name>]   [-ver-
       ilog_from_def_netlist_flow] [-incremental_routing]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information for each defIn parameter. For a detailed description of the
       command and all of its parameters,  use  the  man  command:  man  defIn
       [1m-add_blockage  [22mConverts  undefined  instances (except COVER cells) into
       blockages. [1m-allWarning [22mLists all warning messages issued when you  load
       the  DEF  file.  Default:  Limits the number of warning messages to the
       first 1,000. [1m-components [22mReads the COMPONENTS section of the  DEF  file
       and  ignores  other  sections,  except  when  the -nets or -specialnets
       parameters are specified. [1m-deleteBump [22mDeletes all bumps in the database
       before  reading  the  DEF file. [1m-deleteSpecialRoute [22mDeletes all special
       routes in the database before reading the DEF file. This  includes  the
       RDL  routing  as  well  as  the  power and ground special routes in the
       design. [1m-ignore_drcfill [22mIgnores the special routing with DRCFILL  shape
       attribute.  [1m-ignore_pg_connectivity  [22mIgnores the pg connectivity in the
       SPECIALNETS and NETS sections. [1m<fileName> [22mSpecifies the name of the DEF
       file to load. [1m-incremental_routing [22mPrevents deletion of the whole rout-
       ing of the signal net, and just adds the  new  wires  and  vias.  [1m-nets[0m
       Reads  the  NETS  section  of  the DEF file and ignores other sections,
       except when the -components or -specialnets parameters  are  specified.
       [1m-preserveShape  [22mPrevents  creation  of  symbolic  center-line connected
       routing data and preserves the routing  data  as-is.  The  option  will
       override   the   global  environment  variable  defInShapeBasedDefFile.
       [1m-removeHalfWireExtensionOnPin [22mTruncates the half-width  extension  back
       to  zero  extension for all wire end points that overlap a pin. This is
       useful for DEF  files  created  by  defOut  -addHalfWireExtensionOnPin,
       which  forces  all  NETS  section routing to use the default half-width
       wire extension. Note: Using this parameter can  cause  DRC  violations.
       [1m-specialRouteUserClass  <user_class_name>    [22mSets  the  specified user-
       class name on all the special routes read in from the DEF  file.  [1m-spe-[0m
       [1mcialnets  [22mReads  the  SPECIALNETS and VIAS sections of the DEF file and
       ignores other sections, except when the -components or -nets parameters
       are  specified.  [1m-verilog_from_def_netlist_flow [22mReconciles the names in
       the DEF and Verilog files generated by the  loadDefFile  command.  This
       procedure  is  required  if  you  want to retrieve any information that
       matches the original DEF file.
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022               defIn(21.15)

[1mName defOut [22m- Writes the specified information to a DEF file
[1mSyntax  defOut  [22m[-help]  <fileName>  [-addHalfWireExtensionOnPin] [-allLayers]
       [-bumpAsPin]   [-cutRow]   [-earlyGlobalRoute]    [-flatten_via_pillar]

       tion  uses the default half-width wire extensions everywhere except for
       zero extensions on pins. This parameter forces  the  zero-extension  on
       pins  to the default half-width extension, and makes the DEF compatible
       for older tools that do not support DEF  zero  wire  extensions.  Note:

       only wires and vias on routing layers are  written  to  the  DEF.  This
       option  will write out wires, vias, and shapes on non-routing layers to

       IMPLANT layers, and ROUTING or CUT layers with sub-types MIMCAP or PAS-
       SIVATION. These  shapes  might  have  been  added  with  add_shape,  or
       imported  from DEF or OA directly. [1m-bumpAsPin [22mWrites bump cells as top-
       level pins in the PINS section. If a PORT in a block has a  PASSIVATION
       layer,  the  tool treats it as an embedded bump. defOut -bumpAsPin out-
       puts all the layer information for embedded bumps in the PIN section as
       for  normal  bumps. Use the -bumpAsPin parameter to generate a DEF file
       for use with Quantus gate-level extraction.A DEF  file  generated  with
       this  parameter  cannot be read back into the Innovus software. [1m-cutRow[0m
       Cuts rows against placement obstructions, block halos, or power  domain
       fence minimum gaps. Default: Placement blockages are written to the DEF
       file. [1m-earlyGlobalRoute [22mWrites information about the wires generated by
       Early  Global  Router  to the NETS section of the DEF file. This option
       implies the -routing parameter; therefore, if you specify this  parame-
       ter,  you do not need to specify -routing. [1m<fileName> [22mSpecifies the DEF
       output file. If you add

       <swire_type_list>]   [-tracks]   [-unit   unit_per_micron]  [-unplaced]
       [-usedVia] [-verilog_from_def_netlist_flow] [-vias]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information for each defOutBySection parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       defOutBySection [1m-addHalfWireExtensionOnPin [22mForces the zero-extension on
       pins to the default half-width extension. [1m-bumpAsPin [22mWrites bump  cells
       as top-level pins in the PINS section. Use this parameter to generate a
       DEF file for use with Quantus gate-level extraction. Important:  A  DEF
       file generated with this parameter cannot be read back into the Innovus
       software. [1m-compPlacement [22mWrites  component  placement  and  orientation
       information  to  the  COMPONENTS section of the DEF file. The output is
       limited to instances with PLACED/FIXED/COVER status,  unless  -unplaced
       is  also specified. [1m-earlyGlobalRoute [22mWrites wire information generated
       by the Early Global Router to the NETS section of the DEF file.  [1m<file-[0m
       [1mname>  [22mSpecifies  the  name of the DEF output file. [1m-fills [22mWrites metal
       fill information to the FILLS section of the DEF file.  [1m-groups  [22mWrites
       group  information  to the GROUPS section of the DEF file. When you use
       this parameter, Innovus also writes information about  regions.  [1m-ioRow[0m
       Generates  I/O  rows  based on I/O pad placement and writes the I/O row
       information to the DEF file. [1m-netRouting [22mWrites  routing  data  to  the
       NETS  section  of the DEF file. [1m-noComps [22mExcludes component information
       from the DEF file.  [1m-noDieArea  [22mExcludes  the  DIEAREA  and  associated
       FE_CORE_BOX*     properties     (FE_CORE_BOX_LL_X,    FE_CORE_BOX_UR_X,
       FE_CORE_BOX_LL_Y, FE_CORE_BOX_UR_Y). You can use this option if you  do
       not  need  some  sections, such as SCANCHAINS or NONDEFAULTRULES, to be
       consistent with the  DIEAREA  or  core-box  settings.  [1m-nonDefaultRules[0m
       Writes  non  default rules (NDRs) to the NONDEFAULTRULES section of the
       DEF file. Note: The -nonDefaultRules parameter works only with -noNets.
       As  the NETS section is always dumped by default, so the NONDEFAULTRULE
       section is also dumped by default. However, if  -noNets  is  specified,
       the  NONDEFAULTRULE  section will be dumped only if -nonDefaultRules is
       also specified. [1m-noNets [22mExcludes net information  from  the  DEF  file.
       Note:  If  -noNets  is specified, the -netRouting and -earlyGlobalRoute
       parameters are ignored. [1m-noPrintGroupRegex [22mSuppresses the use of  regu-
       lar  expressions to represent instance names. You must also specify the
       -groups parameter. [1m-noPrintWildCard [22mSuppresses the use of the  wildcard
       format  to represent special net connectivity. If specified, the -comp-
       Placement parameter is ignored. Note:  The  -noPrintWildCard  parameter
       must  be used along with the -specialNets parameter to be effective. If
       you specify -noPrintWildCard without -specialNets, the software ignores
       it.  Default: If you do not specify this parameter, Innovus writes con-
       nectivity information in the SPECIALNETS section in wildcard format, if
       possible.  [1m-no_virtual_trim [22mExcludes the trim metal shapes on a virtual
       trim metal layer. [1m-outputMaskLayers <layerNames> [22mOutputs MASK  data  on
       specified layers only. [1m-pins [22mWrites pin information to the PINS section

       file. [1m-selected [22mWrites out information for selected as follows:

       or through the highlight command. The Edit -  Highlight  Selected  menu
       provides  eight  highlight  patterns to choose from. The value of index
       should, therefore, be a number be from 1 to 8. As an  example,  if  you
       specify  a  value  of  3 for index, all objects that are highlighted as
       Highlighted Set 3 will be  dehighlighted.  [1m<objectList>  [22mSpecifies  the
       object  pointer  list  for dehighlighting. [1m-original [22mSpecifies that the
       objects  highlighted  with  original  color  should  be  dehighlighted.

[1mName  deleteBNet  [22m-  Given a bussed net or a single bit of a bussed net, logi-
       cally removes the entire bussed net from a design
[1mSyntax deleteBNet [22m[-help] [-moduleBased <moduleName>] {-bus  busName  |  -bus-
       FromBit <busBitName>}
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description  that  includes the type and
       default information for each deleteBNet. For a detailed description  of
       the  command  and  all  of  its  parameters,  use  the man command: man
       deleteBNet [1m-moduleBased <moduleName> [22mSpecifies  the  module  name  that
       contains  the  bus  net  which  needs  to be deleted. This parameter is
       optional. [1m-bus <busName> [22mSpecifies the base name of the  top-level  bus
       net,  or  the  base  name of a bus net in verilog module when used with
       -moduleBased option [1m-busFromBit <busBitName> [22mSpecifies the bus bit name
       of  a  top level or a non-top level bus net, or a bus bit name of a bus
       net in verilog module when used together with the -moduleBased  option.
       Note: The deleteBNet command does not support wildcards. It is not pos-
       sible to delete a single bit of a bussed net. To change the  bus  width
       of  an  existing  net,  the net needs to be deleted and re-created with
       addNet.

[1mTop level bus net[0m

[1mName  deleteBufferTree  [22m- Removes all buffers and inverter pairs, of all foot-
       print types, on all nets in the design
[1mSyntax deleteBufferTree [22m[-help] [-excNetFile <excFileName>] [-footprint <foot-
       PrintName>]     [-preserveRoute]     [-selNetFile    <selF>    <ileName
       |>-net<list_of_nets>] [-verbose]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information   for  each  deleteBufferTree  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  deleteBufferTree  [1m-excNetFile  <excFileName>  [22mSpecifies the
       input file that contains the names  of  nets  to  exclude  from  buffer
       removal.  If  a  net appears in the files specified by both -excNetFile
       and -selNetFile, it is excluded. [1m-footprint  <footprintName>  [22mSpecifies
       the  footprint of buffers to remove. If you do not specify this parame-
       ter, the Innovus software removes buffer instances with one  input  and
       one  output  terminal,  and  whose  timing  arc  is  not  SPECIAL. [1m-net[0m
       [1m<list_of_nets> [22mSpecifies the hierarchical nets to include during buffer
       removal.  Note: The -net and -selNetFile parameters are mutually exclu-
       sive. [1m-preserveRoute [22mSpecifies that  nets  not  impacted  by  the  buf-
       fer/inverter  deletion  process  must  have their routing unchanged. By
       default, the tool removes all the routes after  running  this  command.
       [1m-selNetFile <selF> <ileName> [22mSpecifies the file that contains the names
       of hierarchical nets to include during  buffer  removal.  The  software
       excludes  all  other  nets.  If a net appears in the files specified by
       both -excNetFile and -selNetFile, it is excluded. Note:  The  -net  and
       -selNetFile parameters are mutually exclusive. [1m-verbose [22mWhen specified,
       displays additional debug messages in log file. For example, the  fail-
       ure reason for deletion of buffer and inverter pairs.

       ing]

       of  the  command  and  all  of its parameters, use the man command: man
       deleteBumps [1m-all [22mDeletes all bumps. [1m-floating [22mDeletes bumps  which  are
       not  assigned  to  any nets. [1m-overlap_areaio [22mDeletes bumps that overlap
       with the area I/O cells. You must first select the area  I/O  cells  in
       the  design  display  area,  then use this command to delete the bumps.
       [1m-overlap_blockages [22mDeletes all bumps that overlap routing blockages  on
       the  same  layer. For example, if a bump on layer M7 overlaps a routing
       blockage on layer M7, the bump is deleted when you use this  parameter.
       [1m-overlap_keepout [22mDeletes specified bumps that overlap the bump keep out
       zone. [1m-overlap_macro  [22mDeletes  all  bumps  that  overlap  the  selected
       macros.  You  must  first select the macros in the design display area,
       then use this command to delete the bumps. [1m-selected  [22mDeletes  selected
       bumps. You must first select the bumps in the design display area, then
       use this command to delete the bumps.

       information  and  not a subset of it. For example, for a bus guide seg-
       ment with layer constraint 2:5 if you specify -layer 5, the segment  is

       2:5 completely. [1m-netGroup {<netGroup>|  {<list_of_net_groups>}}  [22mSpeci-

       guide segments are deleted. You can also use  wildcard  (*  or  ?)  for

[1mName  deleteFiller  [22m-  Removes  physical cell instances, such as filler cells,
       end-cap cells, and well-tap cells, from standard cell rows
[1mSyntax deleteFiller [22m[-cell <fillerCellList>] [-area {llx lly urx ury}]  [-inst
       <instanceName>] [-prefix <prefix>] [-keepFixed]
[1mParameters -area {llx lly urx ury} [22mSpecifies the bounding box within which the
       filler cells are deleted. The argument type is a box, in microns. Note:
       Only  those  filler cells that are completely contained within the area
       will be deleted. the command does not delete filler  cells  that  cross
       the area boundary. [1m-cell <fillerCellList> [22mSpecifies a cell name or list
       of cells to delete. Separate cell names with spaces. Note: Cells speci-
       fied by this parameter override the list of cells provided by the -core
       parameter of setFillerMode. [1m-keepFixed [22mControls the command to keep the
       End-cap  and  Well-tap  cells  that are marked FIXED. By default, those
       cells will be deleted if this option is not specified. Deletes  End-cap
       and  Well-tap  cells  by  default,  though  they  are  marked as FIXED.
       Default: true  [1m-prefix  <prefix>  [22mSpecifies  the  prefix  of  the  cell
       instances  to  delete. For example, to delete all filler cell instances
       with the prefix FILL, type the following command: deleteFiller  -prefix
       FILL  The software will remove all physical instances whose name starts
       with FILL, including instances named FILL_1,  FILLTEMP_1,  and  so  on.
       Default: FILLER [1m-inst <instanceName> [22mSpecifies the instance of the cell
       to delete. You can use wildcards (*?) with this  parameter.  Note:  You
       can specify this parameter with this command or with addFiller, and not
       with setFillerMode.

       according to the worst timing slack threshold value. For information on
