do_extract_model(21.15)                                do_extract_model(21.15)



[1mName do_extract_model [22m- Builds a Liberty (.lib) format model for the top cell,
       which is the timing model equivalent of the original design
[1mSyntax  do_extract_model  [22m[-help]  <model_filename>   [-abs_tol_val   <float>]
       [-abs_tol_val_optimistic  <float>]  [-abs_tol_val_pessimistic  <float>]
       [-assertions   <constraint    filename>]    [-cell_name    <cell_name>]
       [-clock_slews  {<clk_slew1  clk_slew2>...}]  [-format  <string>] [-gain
       <integer>]    [-include_aocv_weights]    [-input_slews    {<input_slew1
       input_slew2>...}]   [-lib_name   <lib_name>]  [-max_num_loads  <value>]
       [-max_num_slews    <value>]    [-output_loads    {<output_load1    out-
       put_load2>...}]    [-per_tol_val    <float>]   [-per_tol_val_optimistic
       <float>] [-per_tol_val_pessimistic <float>]  [-pg]  [-precision  <inte-
       ger>]  [-resolution  <float>] [-tolerance <float>] [-validate <string>]
       [-verilog_shell_file   <filename>]   [-verilog_shell_module   <top_mod-
       ule_name>] [-view <string>] [-check]
[1mParameters  -help [22mPrints out the command usage. [1m-abs_tol_val <float> [22mSpecifies
       the absolute tolerance value to be used during the  validation  of  the
       extracted   timing   model.   For  more  details,  refer  to  the  com-
       pare_model_timing -absolute_tolerance command  option.  This  parameter
       can  be  used  only when the -validate option is specified. The integer
       value specified with this option is read as ns/ps  depending  upon  the
       time unit. Default: 3ps [1m-abs_tol_val_optimistic <float>   [22mSpecifies the
       absolute tolerance limit for flagging an optimistic failure.  An  opti-
       mistic  path  violating  the  absolute  as well as percentage tolerance
       limit will be flagged as FAIL in the compare_model_timing command  out-
       put  report.  You can use the this parameter when the -validate is used
       with model extraction. Default: 15ps [1m--abs_tol_val_pessimistic  <float>[0m
       Specifies the absolute tolerance limit for flagging a pessimistic fail-
       ure. A pessimistic path violating the absolute as  well  as  percentage
       tolerance  limit will be flagged as FAIL in the check_timing_model com-
       mand output report. You can use the this parameter when  the  -validate
       is  used  with  model extraction. Default: 15ps [1m-assertions <constraint[0m
       [1mfilename> [22mDumps the constraints for a model, which is used in the vali-
       dation  flow.  Default: model.asrt [1m-cell_name <cell_name> [22mSpecifies the
       cell name used in the timing model. Default: The name of the  top  cell
       to  be extracted. [1m-check [22mChecks the extracted timing model for any pos-
       sible liberty related  issue.  When  specified,  the  command  displays
       detailed  error  and  warning messages, and their summary. [1m-clock_slews[0m
       [1m{<clk_slew1 clk_slew2>...} [22mSpecifies a range of slew values used at all
       clock  pins.  The  list  of values must be enclosed by curly braces. If
       this parameter is not specified, the  software  automatically  computes
       the  appropriate  values. [1m-format <string> [22mSpecifies the format for the
       extracted model in tlf, dotlib, or syntech. [1m-gain <integer>  [22mRepresents
       an  increase  in  the  number  of  delay arcs if a pin is removed. This
       option reduces the extracted model size in scenarios where  removing  a
       pin can result in increased model size. The gain at an internal pin can
       be defined as: (number of incoming delay  arcs  *  number  of  outgoing
       delay arcs) - (number of incoming delay arcs + number of outgoing delay
       arcs If an internal pin has a gain greater than the  specified  number,
       then  that  pin  needs to be preserved in order to reduce the extracted
       model size. Default: 0 [1m-include_aocv_weights [22mWrites the stage weight on
       individual  arcs.  Before  using  this option, it is mandatory that the
       AOCV libraries are read in and AOCV analysis is enabled (by using  set-
       AnalysisMode  -aocv  true). The weights written in ETM are not meant to
       derate the model. Model itself will be containing the  derated  delays.
       The  stage weight extracted on arcs will be used to calculate the stage
       count of chip level paths going across the ETM. The  stage  weights  in
       the  extracted  model  are dumped as user defined attributes. This will
       require defining two attributes at arc level.
[1mExamples[0m

ecoChangeCell(21.15)                                      ecoChangeCell(21.15)



[1mName  ecoChangeCell [22m- Upsizes or downsizes the specified instance based on the
       available footprint
[1mSyntax ecoChangeCell [22m[-help] -cell <list_of_cells>|-upsize |  -downsize  -inst
       <instNames>  [-loc  {xLoc yLoc} [-orient {R0 | R90 | R180 | R270 | MX |
       MX90 | MY | MY90}]] [-pinMap <oldpin1 newpin1 oldpin2 newpin2>
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information for each ecoChangeCell. For a detailed description
       of the command and all of its parameters,  use  the  man  command:  man
       ecoChangeCell  [1m-orient {R0 | R90 | R180 | R270 | MX | MX90 | MY | MY90}[0m
       Specifies the legalized orientation for the instance. You  can  specify
       this  parameter  with the -loc parameter only. [1m-inst <instNames> [22mSpeci-
       fies the names of the instances to be changed. [1m-loc {xLoc yLoc}  [22mSpeci-
       fies  the legalized location where the instance will be placed. [1m-upsize[0m
       Upsizes the specified instance with the next available cell in the same
       footprint  unless  the specified cell is already of the highest driving
       strength. Upsizing an instance that drives a large load can improve the
       driver  delay and the transition time at the receivers. [1m-downsize [22mDown-
       sizes the specified instance with the next available cell in  the  same
       footprint  unless  the  specified cell is already of the lowest driving
       strength. Downsizing an instance on the noncritical path can reduce the
       loading of its driver on the critical path. [1m-cell <list_of_cells> [22mSpec-
       ifies the name of a specific cell(s) to be substituted in  the  design.
       The  function of the original cell has to match the function of the new
       cell for all the outputs used by the old cell. The original master cell
       and  the new master cell must have exactly same number of pins. [1m-pinMap[0m
       [1m<oldpin1 newpin1 oldpin2 newpin2> [22mSpecifies the pin mapping for the new
       cell  based  on the old cell. This option is required if the new master
       cell has different pin names than the original cell. The net  connected
       to  <oldpin1>  of the original cell should be connected to <newpin1> of
       the new cell, and so forth.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022       ecoChangeCell(21.15)

ecoClone(21.15)                                                ecoClone(21.15)



[1mName  ecoClone  [22m-  Clones  combinational logic if logic does not have any user
       constraints like don't size/touch and so on. This command is used  when
       you want to clone combinational logic as manual ECO
[1mSyntax   ecoClone   [22m[-help]   [-allow_sequential]   [-auto]  [-balance  <num>]
       [-delete_buffer_trees] [-dont_legalize] [-dont_resize] [-force]  [-from
       <pin  names>] [-instances <instance names>] [-locs <list_of_locations>]
       [-loop <number>]  [-max_levels  <integer>]  [-max_num_loads  <integer>]
       [-min_num_loads <integer>] [-nets <list_of_nets>] [-numClones <number>]
       [-preview]     [-radius     <number>]     [-same_hier_only]     [-terms
       <list_of_term_lists>] [-to <pin names>] [-verbose]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information for each ecoClone parameter. For a detailed description  of
       the  command  and  all of its parameters, use the man command: man eco-
       Clone [1m-allow_sequential [22mUsed with -auto to try cloning at  the  sequen-
       tial  gates too. [1m-auto [22mApplies cloning and buffering automatically. The
       software identifies and clones combinational logic  based  on  critical
       endpoints  distance-based clustering. [1m-balance <number> [22mWhen specified,
       forces the number of loads on each clone to  be  within  the  specified
       number  percentage  (<num %>). The default balance is 10%. [1m-delete_buf-[0m
       [1mfer_trees [22mWhen specified, the software attempts to delete buffer  trees
       driven  by  instances to clone. Note: The deletion of buffer trees with
       user constraints is skipped. [1m-dont_legalize [22mWhen specified,  the  soft-
       ware may leave cloned instances overlapped with the original ones. This
       means the software will not try to legalize instances. This means  that
       if  space  is available, it will place legally, otherwise it will leave
       cloned instances overlapped with the original ones. [1m-dont_resize [22mSpeci-
       fies that neither the original nor the new (cloned) instances should be
       resized. [1m-force [22mWhen specified, forces instance  cloning,  even  if  it
       worsens  QoR  or  causes illegal placement. [1m-from <pin names> [22mSpecifies
       'from' pins. You can specify a single pin or a list of pins. [1m-instances[0m
       [1m<instance  names>   [22mSpecifies the instances to be cloned. You can spec-
       ify a single instance or a tcl list of instances to  be  cloned.  [1m-locs[0m
       [1m<list_of_locations>  [22mSpecifies the location of each clone. This parame-
       ter is used along with the -numClones parameter. When this parameter is
       specified, a location should be specified for each clone, so the length
       should be numClones. The length can be numClones+1, in which case,  the
       first  location  is  used for the original gate. When the locations are
       specified, the sink partitions are assigned to the closest clone. [1m-loop[0m
       [1m<number> [22mRepeat cloning at most <number> times, as far as new instances
       are being created. The original and new instances  within  the  min/max
       number  of  loads range are valid targets at each iteration. Default: 0
       (means  no  limit)  [1m-max_levels  <integer>    [22mSpecifies  the  level  of
       instances  that  the software needs to traverse for cloning. Zero value
       means the software will clone everything  till  the  origin  of  logic.
       Default:  0  (meaning infinite) [1m-max_num_loads <integer> [22mSpecifies that
       cloning should be skipped for instances driving more than the specified
       number of loads. Default: 50000 [1m-min_num_loads <integer> [22mSpecifies that
       cloning should be skipped for instances with less than or equal to  the
       specified  number  of loads. [1m-nets <list_of_nets> [22mSpecifies the nets to
       be cloned. You can specify a single net or a tcl list  of  nets  to  be
       cloned.  Note:  The -nets and -instances parameters are mutually exclu-
       sive. Wildcards are allowed for  this  parameter.  [1m-numClones  <number>[0m
       Specifies the number of clones to create. The default value is 0 and in
       that case, it is computed from the -min_num_loads parameter. Note:  The
       -min_num_loads   and  -numClones  parameters  are  mutually  exclusive.
       Default: 0 [1m-preview [22mWhen specified, provides a preview of what would be
       done, while leaving the netlist untouched. This means that the software
       will report instances that will be cloned and the changes that will  be
       applied  to  the netlist without actually changing the netlist. [1m-radius[0m
       [1m<number> [22mSpecifies that the clones should be placed within a radius  of
       the specified number of rows from their preferred location based on the
       original instance location and the center of mass of  the  new  set  of
       loads. Default: 10 [1m-same_hier_only [22mSpecifies that only those loads will
       be considered that are in the same  hierarchy  as  the  driver.  [1m-terms[0m
       [1m<list_of_term_lists>  [22mSpecifies the partitions, so it is a list of term
       lists. This parameter is used along with the -numClones parameter. When
       this  parameter  is  specified,  there should be one partition for each
       clone, so the length should be numClones. The terms that are not in any
       partition  are  assigned  to the partition driven by the original gate.
       The length can be numClones+1, in which case the first partition is for
       the  original  gate.  In that case, all the sinks should be in a parti-
       tion. [1m-to <pin names> [22mSpecifies 'to' pins. You can specify a single pin
       or  a  list of pins. [1m-verbose [22mWhen specified, verbose messages are dis-
       played during the cloning of instances.
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022            ecoClone(21.15)

<standard input>:17: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

ecoDefIn(21.15)                                                ecoDefIn(21.15)



[1mName  ecoDefIn [22m- Restores physical information from an old design and compares
       this information with the design in memory
[1mSyntax  ecoDefIn  [22m[-help]  [-postMask  [-suffix  <suffixName>]]   [-useGACells
       <GACoreSite>]  [-reportFile  <fileName>]  [-cleanFEData] [-keepInstLoc]
       [-mergeFloatingRouteToPGNet <netName>]  [-ecoDef  {<new_DEF_fileName>}]
       <filename>
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description  that  includes the type and
       default information for each ecoDefIn. For a  detailed  description  of
       the  command  and  all  of  its  parameters,  use  the man command: man
       ecoDefIn [1m-cleanFEData [22mSpecifies that the routed data is DRC clean.  ECO
       routing will skip routing analysis. [1m-ecoDef {<new_def_fileName>} [22mSpeci-
       fies the name of a partial DEF file. The  tool  compares  the  original
       routed  DEF  file  or  Innovus  database  with  this file and marks the
       changed instances, changed location  of  the  existing  instances,  and
       changed  segments  or  wires.  [1m<fileName>  [22mSpecifies  the  name  of the
       routed/original DEF file to load. [1m-keepInstLoc  [22mApplies  the  placement
       status  and location of the instance in the DEF file to the instance in
       db. This option is only applicable in the following special  situation:
       When  an  instance in DEF file and an instance in db have the same name
       but the master cell of the instance in the DEF and in  the  db  do  not
       match,  then  the  instance  in  DEF is considered as deleted while the
       instance in db is added. In this case, if the option is not  specified,
       the  general rule for addition or deletion of an instance is applied as
       described earlier. For the added instance, the placement status is  set
       to unplaced. If the option is specified, the placement status and loca-
       tion of the instance in the DEF file is applied to the instance in  db.
       [1m-mergeFloatingRouteToPGNet  <netName>  [22mMerges  the  routing data to the
       specified PG net. In this case, the physical-only net will not be  cre-
       ated.  When this parameter is not specified, if a net is deleted in the
       new netlist but exists in the DEF file, then the ecoDefIn command  dis-
       cards  the net in pre-mask ECO and creates a physical-only net in post-
       mask ECO to preserve the routing data on the net. [1m-postMask  [22mRuns  this
       command  in  post-route mode. [1m-reportFile <fileName> [22mSpecifies the name
       for the report generated by the ecoDefIn command. Default: ecoDefIn.rpt
       [1m-suffix  <suffixName> [22mAppends the specified suffix to cells that appear
       in the DEF file but have been deleted  in  the  new  netlist.  Default:
       _SPARE [1m-useGACells <GACoreSite> [22mSpecifies the GA Core Site.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022            ecoDefIn(21.15)

[1mName ecoDesign [22m- Takes an Innovus database and a modified netlist as input and

       [-noAddFiller] [-skipCcopt] [-fillerPrefix  <prefix>|  -noDeleteFiller]

       -useGAFillerCells <list_of_filler_cells>]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information  for each ecoDesign. For a detailed description of
       the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man  ecoDe-
       sign  [1m-1801File  <new1801File> [22mSpecifies the name of the new 1801 file.
       [1m-allow_to_load_binary_timing_file [22mAllows the tool to  load  the  binary
       timing  graph  or  the timing constraint file. If you execute ecoDesign
       based on binary timing graph or timing constraints, the tool will  give
       an  error  and  stop loading the new design. This is because the timing
       graph or the timing constraints file from the loaded design is a binary
       file,  and if you keep on loading it, it may cause fatal error. In such
       a case, you need to restore the original design and  then  save  a  new
       design with the no-binary timing file. Then, execute ecoDesign based on
       the new design. If you still want to load the current design, you  need
       to  run  ecoDesign  -allow_to_load_binary_timing_file  1 to turn on the
       control. [1m-addHierPortForTieOff [22mAllows the added tie cells to connect to
       the  tie pins across hierarchical boundaries if other constraints, such
       as maximum fanout and maximum distance, allow it. This parameter can be
       used  only  with  -postMask and -tieCell options. [1m-cpfFile <newCPFFile>[0m
       Specifies the name of the CPF file. [1m-def <fileName> [22mSpecifies  the  DEF
       file  you  want the software to load automatically when performing ECO.
       This parameter automatically assigns the location of the new ECO cells.
       As  a result, you do not need to run ecoPlace after performing the ECO.
       [1m<design> [22mSpecifies the top cell name of the design. [1m-ecoMMMC  <newMMMC-[0m

       mand removes all filler cells before placing the ECOs. If  you  do  not
       specify  a  prefix,  deleteFiller removes filler instances based on the
       setFillerMode command settings. If you have not set setFillerMode, then
       no  filler  cells are removed. [1m-keepInstLoc [22mKeeps the instance location
       of changed cells. [1m-lef_files <LEFFilesName>  [22mSpecifies  the  LEF  files
       name  for  loading. Use this option if you want to replace the existing
       LEF files in the original design with new LEF files. Refer to  restore-
       Design  -lef_files  for  more  details  and  limitations.  For example,
       tech.lef, A.lef are the existing LEFs used in original design. You  can
       change  A.lef to A_v2.lef using the following command: ecoDesign origi-
       nal.enc.dat  myDesign  myDesign.new.v  -lef_files  {tech.lef  A_v2.lef}

       ing  the  ECO process. [1m-noTiming [22mIgnores timing libraries and MMMC con-

       [1msionDirectory> [22mSpecifies the

ecoPlace(21.15)                                                ecoPlace(21.15)



[1mName ecoPlace [22m- Incrementally places the unplaced standard cells
[1mSyntax       ecoPlace       [22m[-help]       [-fixPlacedInsts       {true|false}]
       [-place_detail_use_GA_filler_groups    {true|false}]    [-timing_driven
       {true|false}]  [-useGACells <GACoreSite>] [-useGAFillerCells <GAFiller-
       Cells>] [-useSpareCells {true|false}]
[1mParameters -fixPlacedInsts {true | false} [22mSpecifies that  instances  with  the
       PLACED  status  are  not  moved. [1m-help [22mOutputs a brief description that
       includes type and default information for each ecoPlace parameter.  For
       a  detailed  description  of the command and all of its parameters, use
       the man command: man ecoPlace. [1m-timing_driven {true|false} [22mTurns on the
       slack-driven   placement   for  ecoPlace.  Default:  false  [1m-useGACells[0m
       [1m<GACoreSite> [22mSelects and places the unplaced  instances  with  techSite
       matching  the  provided  GACoreSite.  It is expected that there is free
       space to place the instances. If  not,  GA  fillers  could  be  deleted
       before  ecoPlace -useGACells and re-inserted after the command. You can
       use this parameter only for post-mask ECO. Note: You cannot specify the
       -useGAFillerCells  parameter  if  you use this parameter. [1m-useGAFiller-[0m
       [1mCells <GAFillerCells> [22mSpecifies a list of Gate Array (GA)-style  filler
       cells that the tool can replace with GA cells during post-mask ECO. You
       can only use this parameter in a post-mask  ECO  flow.  The  new  logic
       instances adding during a post-mask flow must already be present in the
       netlist. Note: You cannot specify the -useGACells parameter if you  use
       this  parameter. [1m-place_detail_use_GA_filler_groups {true|false} [22mSpeci-
       fies that  filler  cell  instances  will  only  be  replaced  by  logic
       instances  that  belong  to the same GA groups. This option can only be
       used when there is  a  filler  group  created  by  createGAFillerGroup.
       ecoPlace  -place_detail_use_GA_filler_groups  first  finds  the optimal
       location for each instance based on its connectivity, then searches for
       the  nearest  GA filler cell that is included in the same filler group,
       places a GA cell at the GA filler location, and deletes the original GA
       filler.  If  the GA cell is smaller than the GA filler, the placer cre-
       ates a new GA filler instance using the list of GA filler cells in  the
       same  filler  group  and places the filler in the gap. If there is only
       one filler group created, it equals  to  ecoPlace  -  useGAFillerCells.
       Default:  false  [1m-useSpareCells  {true  | false} [22mMaps unplaced cells to
       spare cells during placement. First, checks whether all unplaced  cells
       match  spare  cells. Next, chooses a spare cell and changes the connec-
       tions from the unplaced cell  to  the  selected  spare  cell.  Finally,
       deletes  the  unplaced  cell. You can use this parameter only for post-
       mask ECO. This option observes the  power  domain  when  selecting  the
       spare  cell  and  maps  an unplaced cell to the spare cell in the power
       domain, based on the instance name of the cell. For example, if  module
       A/B  is  defined for power domain PD2, this option will map an unplaced
       cell A/B/inst1 to a spare cell in module A/B. Default: false
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022            ecoPlace(21.15)

[1mName  ecoRemoveTiedInputs [22m- Remaps or restructures gates that have inputs con-

[1mSyntax     ecoRemoveTiedInputs     [22m[-help]      [-base_cells      <cell_list>]
       [-ignore_base_cells  <cell_list>]  [-ignore_insts  <inst_list>] [-insts
       <inst_list>]  [-relaxed_placement]   [-term   <term_list>]   [-verbose]
       [-report]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a  brief  description  that  includes the type and
       default information  for  each  ecoRemoveTiedInputs  parameter.  For  a
       detailed  description of the command and all of its parameters, use the
       man command: man ecoRemoveTiedInputs [1m-base_cells <cell_list>  [22mSpecifies
       the  buffer cells to be used for fixing. [1m-ignore_base_cells <cell_list>[0m
       Specifies to ignore instances of these cells from fixing. [1m-ignore_insts[0m
       [1m<inst_list>  [22mSpecifies  to  ignore  these instances from fixing. [1m-insts[0m
       [1m<inst_list> [22mSpecifies to fix only these instances. Default: All  design
       minus ignored instances/cells. [1m-relaxed_placement [22mAccepts moves even if
       instances cannot be placed. You do not  need  to  set  this  option  if
       ecoRemoveTiedInputs can successfully fix all violations. In some cases,
       for example if an instance with tied inputs  is  in  a  very  congested
       area,  the  tool  may  not  be able to place the new instances. In such
       cases, you can use the -relaxed_placement option to fix such instances.
       However,  the  final  placement may not be legal, and the new instances
       will likely overlap. For this, you can perform incremental placement to
       legalize  the  placement.  [1m-term  <term_list> [22mSpecifies the terms to be
       buffered. [1m-verbose [22mSpecifies to increase the detail of reports and fix-
       ing.  [1m-report [22mReports existing tied inputs, but does not provide fixing
       details by any method.

[1mName  ecoRoute  [22m-  This command is part of an ECO flow process and is based on
       the NanoRoute router
[1mSyntax ecoRoute [22m[-help] [-ignore_route <string>] [-handlePartition ] [-fix_drc
       [-cut_color_flip     {0     1}]    [-trim_layer_patch    ]    [<area>]]
       [-fix_filler_drc_with_patch_only | -fix_drc ]  [-target  |  -fix_drc  |
       -prototype ] [-modifyOnlyLayers <bottomLayer>:<topLayer> | -fix_drc ]
[1mParameters  <area>  [22mFixes  DRC violations is the specified route area. You can
       specify the area using the x1 y1 x2 y2  coordinate  values.  Note:  The
       parameter  must  be  used with the -fix_drc parameter. Data_type: rect,
       optional [1m-cut_color_flip {0 1} [22mFixes cut color DRC violations by  flip-
       ping.  When enabled ( 1 ), the ecoRoute command fixes the cut same-mask
       spacing violations by flipping the color of the cut. Note: The  parame-
       ter must be used with the -fix_drc parameter. [1m-fix_drc [22mFixes violations
       on existing  DRC  markers  in  the  design.  When  enabled,  it  allows
       NanoRoute  to fix only the DRC's on existing DRC markers in the design.
       If violations increase then the ecoRoute command reverts to the  origi-
       nal  snap  shot  of  the  design.  Note:  If open nets are found in the
       design, NanoRoute will error out. Note: This parameter does not support
       the    -modifyOnlyLayers    arguments.    Data_type:   bool,   optional
       [1m-fix_filler_drc_with_patch_only   [22mFixes filler related drc  with  metal
       patch only. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-help [22mOutputs a brief description
       that includes the type and default information for each ecoRoute param-
       eter.  For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
       ters, use the man command: man ecoRoute [1m-handlePartition [22mTurns on  han-
       dling  partition  flag.  For the nets in hierarchical partition design,
       the ECO routing performed is partition aware with this option.
[1mExamples[0m

[1mName  ecoSplitComplexFlop [22m- Splits a complex flip-flop into a simple flip-flop

[1mSyntax ecoSplitComplexFlop [22m[-help] [-force] {-inst  {<inst1>,  <inst2>,...}  |

       mand: man ecoSplitComplexFlop [1m-all [22mSpecifies that all flop instances in
       the design should be processed. Note: The -inst,  -listFile,  and  -all
       parameters  are  mutually  exclusive.  One  of these parameters must be
       specified. [1m-force [22mWhen specified,  forces  the  complex  flip-flops  to
       split regardless of the timing gains. [1m-inst {<inst1, inst2,...>}  [22mSpec-
       ifies the names of the flop instances to be split. You  can  specify  a
       single  instance  or  a  tcl  list  of instances to be split. Note: The
       -inst, -listFile, and -all parameters are mutually  exclusive.  One  of
       these parameters must be specified. [1m-listFile <instNamesFile> [22mSpecifies
       the file containing the names of the flop instances to be split.  Spec-
       ify  one instance on one line. Comment with #. Instance name should not
       contain spaces or backslashes. Note: The  -inst,  -listFile,  and  -all
       parameters  are  mutually  exclusive.  One  of these parameters must be
       specified. [1m-legal [22mWhen specified, places the split flip-flops and  com-
       binational  cells  at a legal location. [1m-preCTS [22mSpecify this parameter,
       if the design stage is preCTS. [1m-postCTS [22mSpecify this parameter, if  the
       design  stage  is  postCTS.  [1m-postRoute  [22mSpecify this parameter, if the
       design stage is postRoute. [1m-power [22mWhen  specified,  complex  flops  are
       split  to  reclaim  power.  By default, the flops are split for timing.
       [1m-skipRoute [22mSkip globalDetailRoute after split in postRoute stage.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022 ecoSplitComplexFlop(21.15)

ecoSplitFlop(21.15)                                        ecoSplitFlop(21.15)



[1mName  ecoSplitFlop [22m- Splits a multi-bit flip-flop (MBFF) into single-bit flip-
       flops for the specified instance. By default, a specific  flip-flop  is
       split  only  if  equivalent  single-bit  flip-flops  can  be  found  in
       libraries and there is timing gain after the split
[1mSyntax ecoSplitFlop [22m[-help] [-batch] [-force] [-fullSplit]  {-inst  <flopInst-
       Name>  |  {{Mbff1  flopCell1} {Mbff2 flopCell2}...} | -listFile <<file-
       Name>> | -all} [-legal] [-power]  {-preCTS  |  -postCTS  |  -postRoute}
       [-skipRoute]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information for each ecoSplitFlop parameter. For a detailed description
       of  the  command  and  all  of its parameters, use the man command: man
       ecoSplitFlop [1m-all [22mWhen specified, splits  all  MBFFs  into  smaller-bit
       flip-flops  including single-bit flip-flops (SBFFs). Only timing criti-
       cal bits are split into single-bit flops, and the remaining, non-criti-
       cal  bits, are split into smaller bit width MBFFs, to preserve power as
       much as possible. For example, a 4-bit MBFF may be split into two  sin-
       gle-bit  flops  and one 2-bit flop. Note: The -all, -inst and -listFile
       parameters are mutually exclusive. If the -all parameter is not  speci-
       fied,  one  of these two parameters, -inst or -listFile, must be speci-
       fied. Default:  false  [1m-batch  [22mWhen  specified,  splits  the  MBFFs  in
       batches.  For  example,  ecoSplitFlop  -listFile <list> -postCTS -batch
       -force Default: false [1m-force [22mForces the flip-flop  splits  irrespective
       of  timing  gains.  Default: false Note: If there is no timing gain and
       this parameter is not  specified,  the  flip-flops  for  the  specified
       instance  will  not  be  split.  [1m-fullSplit [22mForces the MBFFs to be com-
       pletely split into all single-bit flip-flops.  [1m-inst  <flopInstName>  |[0m
       [1m{{Mbff1 flopCell1} {Mbff2 flopCell2}...} [22mSpecifies pairs of MBFFs to be
       split and the corresponding single-bit flops to be used. You  can  also
       specify  the names of the flop instances to be split. You can specify a
       single instance or a tcl list of instances to be split. Note: The -all,
       -inst  and  -listFile  parameters  are  mutually exclusive. If the -all
       parameter is not specified, one  of  these  two  parameters,  -inst  or
       -listFile,  must  be specified. [1m-listFile <fileName> [22mSpecifies the file
       containing pairs of MBFFs to be split and the corresponding  single-bit
       flops to be used. You can also just specify the names of MBFF instances
       to be split. You can specify up to 50,000 instances to  split.  Specify
       each  instance  on  a line and comment with #. Instance name should not
       contain spaces or backslashes. Note:  The  -all,  -inst  and  -listFile
       parameters  are mutually exclusive. If the -all parameter is not speci-
       fied, one of these two parameters, -inst or -listFile, must  be  speci-
       fied.  [1m-legal  [22mPlaces the split flip-flops at legal locations. Default:
       false [1m-power [22mSplits the flip-flop for  power  purpose.  Default:  false
       [1m-preCTS   [22mSpecify  this  parameter,  if  the  design  stage  is preCTS.
       Default: -postRoute [1m-postCTS [22mSpecify  this  parameter,  if  the  design
       stage  is  postCTS. Default: -postRoute [1m-postRoute [22mSpecify this parame-
       ter, if the design stage is postRoute. This  is  the  default  setting.
       Note:  One  of the three options, -preCTS, -postCTS, or -postRoute must
       be specified. [1m-skipRoute [22mSpecify if the stage is  postRoute  and  glob-
       alDetailRoute  is  not  required to be performed after the split. Since
       postRoute is also the default stage, globalDetailRoute is also  skipped
       when the stage is default and -skipRoute is specified. However, for the
       default case, when the stage is postRoute but  this  parameter  is  not
       specified,  after  splitting  the  instances, globalDetailRoute will be
       called. Default: false
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022        ecoSplitFlop(21.15)

editDelete(21.15)                                            editDelete(21.15)



[1mName editDelete [22m- Deletes physical wires, any vias connected to the wires, and
       violation markers associated with the wires
[1mSyntax editDelete [22m[-help] [-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}] [-direction {H | V  |  45  |
       135}]  [-floating_via] [-layer {<list_of_layers>}] [-net <net>+] [-par-
       allel_routing]      [-physical_pin_only]       [-regular_wire_with_drc]
       [-selected]  [-shape  {RING  STRIPE FOLLOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE
       PADRING  BLOCKRING  FILLWIRE  FILLWIREOPC  DRCFILL   None}]   [-shield]
       [-shield_only]  [-status  {FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN} [-sub-
       class <sublass_name>] [-trim_metal] [-type {Regular| Special |  Patch}]
       [-use    {CLOCK    POWER    SIGNAL}]    [-via_cell    <cell_name_list>]
       [-with_edit_flag {0 | 1}] [-object_type {Wire Via} ]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that  includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each editDelete parameter. For a detailed description
       of the command and all of its parameters,  use  the  man  command:  man
       editDelete [1m-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>} [22mSpecifies the coordinates for the area
       from which to delete the wires. Default: Deletes all wires.  [1m-direction[0m
       [1m{H  |  V  | 45 | 135} [22mSpecifies the orientation of the wires to delete.
       Default: If you do not  specify  this  parameter,  deletes  wires  with
       either  orientations. H: Specifies that only horizontal wires are to be
       deleted. V: Specifies that only vertical wires are to be  deleted.  45:
       Specifies  that  45-degree wires are to be deleted. 135: Specifies that
       135-degree wires are to be deleted. [1m-floating_via [22mSpecifies  that  only
       floating  vias  should  be deleted. [1m-layer {<list_of_layers>} [22mSpecifies
       the layers from which to delete wires. You must use LEF layer names  or
       a  routing  layer index value (1 for the first routing layer, 2 for the
       second routing layer, and so on). This  option  supports  backside  and
       Through  Silicon Via (TSV) layers as well. If you are specifying multi-
       ple layers, enclose them in braces. Default: If you do not specify this
       parameter, deletes wires from all layers. [1m-net <net>+ [22mSpecifies the net
       or list of nets from which to delete wires. You can use wildcard values
       in  this field. For example, if you specify V*, deletes wires from nets
       VDD and VSS. If you are  specifying  multiple  nets,  enclose  them  in
       braces.  Note: By default, the wires and vias shielding the nets speci-
       fied with editDelete -net are not deleted. If you want  to  delete  the
       shielding  as  well,  specify -shield along with -net. (<Image> To view
       the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference -  Release  21.1
       manual.) [1m-object_type {Wire Via} [22mSpecifies whether wires or vias should
       be deleted. You can specify both as well. If -object_type is not speci-
       fied,  editDelete  deletes  both  wires  and  vias  by default. [1m-paral-[0m
       [1mlel_routing [22mSpecifies that the  wires  created  by  NanoRoute  parallel
       routing are to be deleted. [1m-physical_pin_only [22mSpecifies that the physi-
       cal pins in the design are to be deleted. You can use  filter  options,
       such   as  -net,  -layer,  -area,  and  -selected  along  with  -physi-
       cal_pin_only to delete specific physical  pins.  [1m-regular_wire_with_drc[0m
       Deletes  the regular wires with violation markers. This parameter works
       only when -net or -status are specified as  filters.  Note:  editDelete
       -selected parameter deletes only physically selected objects. To delete
       wires with violations from a specific net, specify the  net  name  with
       the   editDelete  -net  parameter:  editDelete  -net  <netName>  -regu-
       lar_wire_with_drc [1m-selected [22mDeletes selected wires,<standard input>:12: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:15: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:17: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:19: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:21: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:23: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:25: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:28: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:29: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
 vias, and  physical
       pins.  Note: Only physically selected objects are deleted. If selectNet
       is used to select a net, editDelete -selected cannot be used to  delete
       that  net's wires. This is because selectNet selects the net only logi-
       cally. If you want to  delete  the  entire  net,  use  editSelect  -net
       instead  of  selectNet  to  ensure  the wires of the net are physically
       selected. [1m-shape {{RING  STRIPE  FOLLOWPIN  IOWIRE  COREWIRE  BLOCKWIRE[0m
       [1mPADRING  BLOCKRING  FILLWIRE  FILLWIREOPC  DRCFILL None}} [22mSpecifies the
       shapes of the wires to delete. The status must  be  in  all  upper-case
       letters.  If you specify multiple shapes, enclose the shapes in braces.
       For shape definitions, see Shapes, in the DEF  Syntax  chapter  of  the
       LEF/DEF Language Reference. Default: If you do not specify this parame-
       ter, deletes wires of all shapes. [1m-shield [22mDeletes the wires and vias of
       the  nets  specified  with the -net parameter, along with the wires and
       vias shielding the specified nets. (<Image> To view the image, refer to
       the  Innovus  Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 manual.) Note: This
       parameter cannot be used with -shield_only. [1m-shield_only  [22mDeletes  only
       the  wires  and vias shielding the nets specified with the -net parame-
       ter. The signal nets being shielded are retained. (<Image> To view  the
       image,  refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 man-
       ual.) Note: This parameter cannot be used with -shield. [1m-status  {FIXED[0m
       [1mNOSHIELD  ROUTED  SHIELD  UNKNOWN}  [22mSpecifies  the  status  of wires to
       delete. The status must be in uppercase letters. If  you  specify  more
       than one status, enclose the status list in braces. Note: If you select
       -type Special -status NOSHIELD or  -type  Regular  -status  SHIELD  the
       software generates an error message. [1m-subclass <sublass_name> [22mSpecifies
       the subclass name of the wires to be deleted. Use this parameter if you
       want  to  delete rings, stripes, or other wires belonging to a specific
       subclass. Note: You can use wildcards in <subclass_name>. Only  special
       wire  is  supported  by this option. [1m-trim_metal [22mDeletes the trim metal
       attached to all patch wires,  without  deleting  the  patch  wires.  If
       -selected  is  also  specified, deletes only the trim metal attached to
       the selected patch wire without deleting the patch wire.  [1m-type  {Regu-[0m
       [1mlar|  Special  | Patch} [22mSpecifies whether to delete regular wires, spe-
       cial wires, or patch wires. Note: If  you  specify  Regular,  omit  the
       -shape  parameter  or  specify  -shape  None. [1m-use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}[0m
       Indicates that wires will be deleted on the basis of the specified use:
       CLOCK: Specifies that only wires for clock nets will be deleted. POWER:
       Specifies that only wires for power nets will be deleted. SIGNAL: Spec-
       ifies  that  only  wires  for  general  signal  nets  will  be deleted.
       [1m-via_cell <cell_name_list>   [22mSpecifies the via cells of the vias to  be
       deleted.  You can use wildcards while specifying the via cell names. If
       you are  specifying  multiple  cell  names,  enclose  them  in  braces.
       [1m-with_edit_flag  {0 | 1} [22mDeletes all modified wires, that is wires with
       value 1 for the isEdit property on the net. Notes
[1mExamples[0m

editPin(21.15)                                                  editPin(21.15)



[1mName  editPin  [22m- Modifies properties of pins, such as pin spreading, pin loca-
       tion, pin width and depth, spacing, snap-to location, and status
[1mSyntax editPin [22m[-help] [-cell <cellName> |  {-hinst  <hinstName>[-refMaster]}]
       [-end   {<x  y>}]  [-fixedPin]  [-global_location]  [-include_rectilin-
       ear_edge]  [-masterCloneAware]   [-offsetEnd   <value>]   [-offsetStart
       <value>]  -pin  {<pinName> | <pinNameList>} [-pinDepth <pinDepthValue>]
       [-pinWidth <pinWidthValue>] [-skipWrappingPins] [-snap {TRACK  |  USER-
       GRID | MGRID}] [-spreadDirection {clockwise | counterclockwise | both}]
       [-start {<x y>}] [-use { SIGNAL | CLOCK | ANALOG }] [{-layer {<layerId>
       |  <layerIdListName>}  |  {[-layerH  <layerId>]  [-layerV  <layerId>]}}
       [-layer_priority] [-assign {<x y>} | -spreadType {START | CENTER | SIDE
       |  EDGE | RANGE} | -pattern {fill_track | fill_layer | fill_optimised |
       fill_diagonal | fill_sinusoidal |  fill_checkerboard}]]  [-side  <side-
       Name>   |  -edge  <edgeNumber>]  [-fixOverlap  {0|1}  [-honorConstraint
       {0|1}]]  [-pattern  {fill_track  |  fill_layer   |   fill_optimised   |
       fill_diagonal  |  fill_sinusoidal | fill_checkerboard} [-reverse_alter-
       nate]] [-spacing <spacingValue> [-unit {MICRON | TRACK}]]
[1mParameters -assign {<x y>} [22mPreassigns a pin at the specified location. You can
       use  this  parameter  with other parameters such as -snap, -fixOverlap,
       -side, and so on. Data_type: point, optional [1m-cell <cellName> [22mSpecifies
       the  name of the module. If you do not specify a cell name, the command
       runs on the top-level cell. Data_type: string, optional [1m-edge <edgeNum-[0m
       [1mber>  [22mFor  rectilinear  partitions,  specifies the edge along which the
       pins will be placed. The edge number is an integer. The edge  numbering
       starts  from the lower-left corner of a partition clock-wise. Edge 0 is
       the edge that has the smallest y value. (<Image>  To  view  the  image,
       refer  to the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release 21.1 manual.) To
       spread pins on multiple rectilinear edges that are on  the  same  side,
       use  the -side parameter. For rectangular partitions, you can specify a
       side with the -side parameter. Data_type: int, optional  [1m-end  {<x  y>}[0m
       For  pin  spreading along a range, specifies the coordinates where pins
       should end. This parameter is used with the -spreadType  RANGE  parame-
       ter.  Data_type:  point,  optional  [1m-fixedPin [22mA value of 1 sets the pin
       status to Fixed. Default: The pin status is  placed.  Data_type:  bool,
       optional  [1m-fixOverlap  {0 | 1} [22mWith this parameter on, the editPin com-
       mand tries to resolve pin-overlap with other/nearby objects.  The  pins
       are  moved  to  the  closest  acceptable position such that pins do not
       overlap. Default: 1. Resolve pin-overlap is on.  Note:  This  parameter
       applies  only  when  pins  are snapped to layer track. Data_type: bool,
       optional [1m-global_location [22mSpecifies that the global location should  be
       considered  by  the  command.  Note:  By default all locations that the
       editPin command considers are coordinates with  respect  to  lower-left
       corner  of  partition.  If you specify the -global_location option, the
       -start, -end, and -assign parameters accept coordinates with respect to
       the lower-left corner of the design. For example, in the following com-
       mand, the pin will be placed 3u from the lower-left corner of the  par-
       tition.  editPin  -cell c -pin cIn -assign 0 3 -layer 2 -side left When
       you use the -global_location parameter, the pin will be placed 3u  from
       the lower-left corner of the design. editPin -cell c -pin cIn -assign 0
       3 -layer 2 -side left -global_location Data_type: bool, optional  [1m-help[0m
       Outputs  a brief description that includes type and default information
       for each editPin parameter. For a detailed description of  the  command
       and  all  of  its  parameters,  use the man command: man editPin [1m-hinst[0m
       [1m<hinstName>   [22mSpecifies the hinst name, including black box or  commit-
       ted  partition  and  top.  Data_type: string, optional [1m-honorConstraint[0m
       [1m{0|1} [22mSpecifies whether user-defined pin constraints should be honored.
       The following constraints are honored when this parameter is set to on:

[1mExample[0m

editSelect(21.15)                                            editSelect(21.15)



[1mName editSelect [22m- Selects wires and vias using the specified parameters
[1mSyntax  editSelect  [22m[-help] [-area {<x1> <y1> <x2> <y2>}] [-direction {H | V |
       45 | 135}]  [-floating_via]  [-layer  <list_of_layers>]  [-net  <net>*]
       [-physical_pin_only] [-regular_wire_with_drc] [-shape {RING STRIPE FOL-
       LOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE PADRING BLOCKRING FILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC
       DRCFILL  None}] [-shield] [-shield_only] [-status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD
       ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN}] [-subclass <sublass_name>] [-type {Regular Spe-
       cial  Patch}]  [-use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}] [-via_cell <cell_name_list>]
       [-with_edit_flag  {0  |  1}]  [-object_type  {Wire   Via}]   [-from_pin
       <pin_name> -to_pin <pin_name>]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mPrints the usage of the command. For a detailed description
       of the command, use the man command: man editSelect [1m-area  {<x1  y1  x2[0m
       [1my2>}  [22mSpecifies the coordinates for the area from which to select wires
       and vias. Default: Entire area <x1>: Specifies the lower left x coordi-
       nate.  <y1>: Specifies the lower left y coordinate. <x2>: Specifies the
       upper right x coordinate. y2: Specifies the upper right  y  coordinate.
       [1m-direction {H | V | 45 | 135} [22mSpecifies the orientation of the wires to
       be selected. Default: If you do not  specify  this  parameter,  selects
       wires  with  any orientation. H: Specifies that horizontal wires are to
       be selected. V: Specifies that vertical wires are to be  selected.  45:
       Specifies  that 45-degree wires are to be selected. 135: Specifies that
       135-degree wires are to be selected. [1m-floating_via [22mSpecifies that  only
       floating  vias are to be selected. A via, or a stack of vias, is float-
       ing, if it is not connected to another object, wire, pin,  or  via,  on
       either its top or bottom metal layer or on both these layers. [1m-from_pin[0m
       [1m<pin_name> [22mSpecifies the name of the starting pin of  the  wire  to  be
       selected.  The starting pin you specify should be connected to the same
       net as the ending pin specified with -to_pin. If they connect  to  dif-
       ferent  nets,  the  tool reports an error. In addition, the from and to
       pins you specify should be connected to the same wire. Note:  Selection
       of  wires between specified pins is supported only for signal and clock
       nets. [1m-layer <list_of_layers> [22mSpecifies the layers from which to select
       wires  and  vias. This option supports backside and Through Silicon Via
       (TSV) layers as well. If you are specifying  multiple  layers,  enclose
       them  in braces. Default: If you do not specify this parameter, selects
       wires and vias on all layers. [1m-net <net>* [22mSpecifies the net names  from
       which  to  select  wires  and vias. You can use wildcard values in this
       field. For example, if you specify V*, selects wires/vias from nets VDD
       and  VSS.  [1m-object_type  {Wire  Via} [22mSpecifies whether wires or vias or
       both should be selected. If the parameter is not specified, only  wires
       are  selected. Default: Wire [1m-physical_pin_only [22mSpecifies that physical
       pins are to be selected. By default, editSelect does not select  physi-
       cal  pins.  You  can  use  the  -physical_pin_only parameter along with
       -area, -layer, or -net to select the physical  pins  in  the  specified
       area, layer, or net, respectively. [1m-regular_wire_with_drc [22mSelects regu-
       lar wires with violation markers. Clock nets are also selected.  [1m-shape[0m
       [1m{RING  STRIPE  FOLLOWPIN  IOWIRE  COREWIRE  BLOCKWIRE PADRING BLOCKRING[0m
       [1mFILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC DRCFILL None} [22mSpecifies the shapes  of  the  wires
       and  vias to be selected. Use all upper-case letters for the shapes. If
       you specify multiple shapes, enclos<standard input>:9: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:12: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

<standard input>:20: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:23: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:24: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

       shape definitions, see Shapes, in the DEF Syntax chapter of the LEF/DEF
       Language Reference. Default: If you  do  not  specify  this  parameter,
       selects  wires  and  vias  of all shapes. [1m-shield [22mSelects the wires and
       vias of the nets specified with the  -net  parameter,  along  with  the
       wires  and vias shielding the specified nets. Note: This parameter can-
       not be used with -shield_only. [1m-shield_only  [22mSelects  only  the  shield
       wires  associated with the nets specified using the -net parameter. The
       signal nets being shielded are not selected. Note: This parameter  can-
       not  be  used with -shield. [1m-status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD[0m
       [1mUNKNOWN} [22mSpecifies the status of wires and vias to be selected. Use all
       upper-case letters for the status. If you specify more than one status,
       enclose the status list in braces. Note: If you  select  -type  Special
       -status  NOSHIELD or -type Signal -status SHIELD the software generates
       an error message. [1m-subclass <sublass_name> [22mSpecifies the subclass  name
       of the wires and vias to be selected. Use this parameter if you want to
       select wires or vias belonging to  a  specific  subclass.  Here,  <sub-
       class_name>  is  a  user-defined  attribute  that  has  been previously
       defined using the -uda  parameter  of  the  addSplitPowerVia,  addRing,
       addStripe, or sroute command. For wires, use this parameter if you want
       to select or delete rings, stripes, or other wires belonging to a  spe-
       cific  subclass.  Only  special wire is supported by this option. Note:
       You can use wildcards in <subclass_name>. [1m-to_pin <pin_name>  [22mSpecifies
       the  name  of the ending pin of the wire to be selected. The ending pin
       you specify should be connected to the same net  as  the  starting  pin
       specified  with  -from_pin. If they connect to different nets, the tool
       reports an error. In addition, the from and to pins you specify  should
       be connected to the same wire. If there there are more than one wire or
       via between the specified starting and ending pins, the command is  not
       able  to  select  the wire path and returns an error. The -from_pin and
       -to_pin parameters are compatible with  only  the  -direction,  -layer,
       -object_type, and -status options of the editSelect command. If you use
       -from_pin and -to_pin with any other editSelect  parameters,  the  tool
       returns  an  error.  Note: Selection of wires between specified pins is
       supported only for signal and clock nets. [1m-type {Regular Special Patch}[0m
       Specifies  whether  to select regular wires and vias, special wires and
       vias, or patch wires. Note: If you specify Regular, you must  omit  the
       -shapes  parameter  or  specify -shapes None. [1m-use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}[0m
       Specifies whether to select only CLOCK wires/vias, POWER wires, or SIG-
       NAL  wires.  [1m-via_cell  <cell_name_list> [22mSpecifies the via cells of the
       vias to be selected. You can use wildcards while  specifying  via  cell
       names.  If  you  are  specifying  multiple  cell names, enclose them in
       braces. [1m-with_edit_flag {0 | 1} [22mSelects all modified  wires  and  vias,
       that is wires and vias with value 1 for the isEdit property on the net.
       Notes
[1mExamples[0m

findPinPortNumber(21.15)                              findPinPortNumber(21.15)



[1mName findPinPortNumber [22m- Determines suitable ports available for a bump
[1mSyntax  findPinPortNumber  [22m[-help]  [-area <x1 y1 x2 y2>] [-bumps <bump_list>]
       [-geometry_height {<min> [<max>]}]  [-geometry_width  {<min>  [<max>]}]
       [-layer   <string>]  [-selected]  [-cellName  <cell_name>  |  -instName
       <instance_name> ] {-pinName <pin_name> | -netName <net_name> }
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that  includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each  findPinPortNumber  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  findPinPortNumber [1m-area <x1 y1 x2 y2> [22mSpecifies the area in
       which the command will be used. findPInPortNumber returns port  numbers
       overlapping  with the specified area. [1m-bumps <bump_list> [22mFinds suitable
       ports for the specified bumps based  on  the  smallest  distance.  This
       option supports only 1:1 pairing between ports and bumps. Therefore, if
       the number of ports is different from the number of bumps,  pairing  is
       based  on  the  smaller number. findPinPortNumber allows empty bumps or
       bumps assigned to the same net as the pin. If the assigned net is  dif-
       ferent  from the net with which the pin is connected, findPinPortNumber
       issues an error message and quits. [1m-cellName <cell_name> [22mFinds the  pin
       port  number of the instance of the specified cell. Wild cards are sup-
       ported in <cell_name>. [1m-geometry_height {<min> [<max>]}  [22mSpecifies  the
       minimum  and  maximum values for the height of the target port's geome-
       try. If you specify only one value, the height is taken as equal to the
       specified  value.  Only ports that match the specified height criterion
       are returned  by  findPinPortNumber.  [1m-geometry_width  {<min>  [<max>]}[0m
       Specifies  the  minimum  and  maximum values of the width of the target
       port's geometry. If you specify only one value, the width is  taken  as
       equal to the specified value. Only ports that match the specified width
       criterion are returned by findPinPortNumber. [1m-instName  <instance_name>[0m
       Finds  pin  port  number of the specified instance. Wild cards are sup-
       ported in <instance_name>. [1m-layer  <string>  [22mFilters  target  ports  by
       layer. If you specify this parameter, only ports on the specified layer
       are returned. You can specify either layer name or layer  ID,  such  as
       M8.  [1m-pinName <pin_name> | -netName <net_name> [22mFinds the port number on
       the specified pin or  on  the  pin  connected  to  the  specified  net.
       [1m-selected [22mFinds suitable ports for the selected instance and bumps:
[1mExample[0m

finishFloorplan(21.15)                                  finishFloorplan(21.15)



[1mName  finishFloorplan  [22m-  Performs advanced placement-related refinements to a
       floorplan, to produce a more polished  floorplan.  The  finishFloorplan
       command,  can be used on any floorplan, including third-party generated
       floorplans
[1mSyntax finishFloorplan [22m[-help] { [-autoHalo | [-autoHaloBasedOnPitch  [-margin
       <value>]]  | -addHalo <width> | [-fillPlaceBlockage <blkgType> <maxGap>
       [-density <value>] [-excludeFlops] [-deadArea  <float>]  [-honor_place-
       ment_density]] | [-fillRouteBlockage <maxGap> [-layer <layerID>] [-cut-
       Layer <cutLayerID>] [-fills ] [-exceptpgnet ] [-spacing <spaceValue>  |
       -designRuleWidth <width>] [-deadArea <maxDeadArea>]] | -addCornerBlock-
       age  <string>  |  [-drcRegionLayer  <layer+>  [-edgeExtend   {<x   y>}]
       [-edgeShrink  {<x  y>}]]| -addBoundaryEOLBlockage | -addRowBasedRegion-
       Blockage| -undo ] [-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}] [-namePrefix <name>] }
[1mParameters -addBoundaryEOLBlockage [22mAdds end-of-line(EOL) routing blockage with
       COREEOLBLOCKAGE  property around active object boundary. This parameter
       can only work with rows as active objects. For each layer, EOL  routing
       blockage  is  perpendicular with prefer routing direction. Note: A Core
       EOL blockage rule is used to specify line-end blockages formed from the
       core  edges.  The  EOL  Blockage  is  defined in LEF as below: PROPERTY
       LEF58_COREEOLBLOCKAGE COREEOLBLOCKAGE <outwardSize inwardSize> [SIDEEX-
       TENSION  <sideExtension>]  ; ; COREEOLBLOCKAGE <outwardSize inwardSize>
       SIDEEXTENSION <sideExtension> Defines  the  line-end  blockages  formed
       from  the core edges in the orthogonal direction of the preferred rout-
       ing direction of the layer of a design. The blockage is formed by going
       outward from the core by outwardSize and inward by inwardSize. If SIDE-
       EXTENSION is defined, the blockage is extended by  sizeExtension  along
       the  direction  of the core edge on both sides. These blockages prevent
       any line-end of a wire end inside it. If a wire goes through the block-
       age  and  just  touches the far end edge, it is still a violation. If a
       wire just touches an edge without extending inside the blockage, it  is
       fine.
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022     finishFloorplan(21.15)

fixVia(21.15)                                                    fixVia(21.15)



[1mName  fixVia [22m- This command fixes the following types of violations in special
       net vias: short, mincut, and minstep
[1mSyntax fixVia [22m[-help] {-short | -minCut | -minStep} [-area]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information for each fixVia parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all its parameters, use the  man  command:  man
       fixVia  [1m-area  {<x>1  <y>1  <x>2  <y>2} [22mSpecifies the rectangular area.
       Thus, the command applies to the violations within the area  only.  The
       area option should be compatible with all existing options and supports
       all violations that the command can support at the  moment.  Specifying
       the area improves the run-time for large design with significant number
       of violations. x1, y1 are the coordinates for lower left corner of  the
       area.  x2,  y2  are  the  coordinates for the upper right corner of the
       area. By default, this option is off and with no default value for  any
       of  its argument. [1m-short [22mFixes vias which have a short violation. [1m-min-[0m
       [1mCut [22mReplaces power vias flagged by a violation marker due to  a  viola-
       tion  of  the  LEF MINIMUMCUT rule. The via is replaced with a via that
       contains the minimum number of cuts based on the LEF rule, and the vio-
       lation  marker  is  removed.  [1m-minStep [22mReplaces power vias flagged by a
       violation marker due to a violation of the LEF  MINIMUMSTEP  rule.  The
       via  is  replaced  with a via that contains the minimum number of steps
       based on the LEF rule, and the violation marker is removed.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022              fixVia(21.15)

generateCapTbl(21.15)                                    generateCapTbl(21.15)



[1mName  generateCapTbl [22m- Reads in the interconnect technology (ICT) process file
       and generates a Capacitance table file
[1mSyntax  generateCapTbl  [22m[-help]  [-cap  <totalCapFactor>]  [-encrypt]  -output
       <fileName>   [-res  <resistanceFactor>]  [-xcap  <crossCouplingFactor>]
       [-lef <fileName> [-shrinkFactor <value>]] {-ict <fileName>  |  -incapt-
       able <fileName>}
[1mParameters  -help        [22mOutputs  a  brief  description that includes type and
       default information for each generateCaptbl parameter. For  a  detailed
       description  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man com-
       mand: man generateCaptbl. [1m-cap <totalCapFactor> [22mSpecifies  the  capaci-
       tance  scale  factor. Use this parameter with the -incaptable parameter
       to generate a capacitance table with capacitance values scaled  by  the
       specified scale factor. [1m-encrypt [22mEncrypts the generated capacitance ta-
       ble to protect the process information in the capacitance table header.
       When  you  use  the  create_rc_corner  -cap_table  command  to read the
       encrypted capacitance table, the software  writes  the  version  number
       that  was used to generate the file, and the name of the process to the
       log file. [1m-ict <fileName> [22mSpecifies  the  name  and  path  to  the  ICT
       (interconnect  technology)  process  file.  To support multiple process
       corners, a capacitance table should be created for each corner from the
       matching  corner ICT file. [1m-incaptable <fileName> [22mSpecifies the name of
       an existing capacitance table in ASCII format. You use  this  parameter
       along  with the -encrypt parameter to create an encrypted version of an
       existing capacitance file. Note: The -ict  and  -incaptable  parameters
       are  mutualy  exclusive.  One  of the two parameters must be specified.
       [1m-lef <fileName> [22mSpecifies the name and the full path to the process LEF
       file  for optimal accuracy. With the LEF file, this parameter generates
       a capacitance table by using the actual wire widths as specified in the
       non-default  rules  defined  in  the LEF. Without the LEF, the software
       uses generic widths and spacings, which might  increase  the  need  for
       interpolation  during extraction. [1m-output <fileName> [22mSpecifies the out-
       put filename that contains the capacitance table. This  is  a  required
       parameter.  [1m-res <resistanceFactor> [22mSpecifies the resistance scale fac-
       tor. Use this parameter with the -incaptable parameter  to  generate  a
       capacitance  table with resistance values scaled by the specified scale
       factor. [1m-shrinkFactor <value> [22mSpecifies the value by which the measure-
       ments  in  the  optional  LEF file have to be shrunk for the technology
       used with this design. Use this parameter only with the -lef  parameter
       and when the LEF technology does not match the target technology in the
       ICT file. Innovus scales the dimensions when reading the LEF file using
       the  shrinkFactor  specified.  The  ICT file should always refer to the
       target technology (min width and min spacing). Note: When working on  a
       design  that  needs to be scaled down in Innovus, you must also set the
       shrinkfactor in Design Import. This tells the extractor to  scale  down
       all  geometries  before  processing.  When the ICT file contains a lay-
       out_scale in the process declaration part, you do not need  to  specify
       the  shrink  factor. In this case, the embedded shrink factor will also
       be written in the captable header. Also, there is then no need  to  set
       the  shrink factor in the Design Import form. The embedded layout_scale
       is used to support half nodes such as  40nm  technology.  Default:  1.0
       [1m-xcap  <crossCouplingFactor>  [22mSpecifies  the cross-coupling capacitance
       scale factor. Use this parameter with the -incaptable parameter to gen-
       erate a capacitance table with cross-coupling capacitance values scaled
       by the specified scale factor.
[1mExample[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022      generateCapTbl(21.15)

generateRCFactor(21.15)                                generateRCFactor(21.15)



[1mName generateRCFactor [22m- Generates the resistance and capacitance scale factors
       for optimal RC correlation by comparing the  SPEF  files  generated  by
       native  extraction  either with the user-specified reference RC data or
       with the automatic running of extraction in the higher accuracy mode
[1mSyntax generateRCFactor [22m[-help] [-outputFile <file_name>] [-preroute { true  |
       false}]  [-postroute { low | medium }] [-reference {low | medium | high
       |    signoff    |     externalSpef}]     [-spefMapFile     <file_name>]
       [-use_ostrich_filters <file_name>]
[1mParameters  -help   [22mOutputs a brief description that includes type and default
       information for the generateRCFactor parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       generateRCFactor. [1m-outputFile <file_name> [22mSpecifies  the  name  of  the
       file  in which the command will save the new RC factor setting. You can
       use this file to set the actual scale factors. [1m-preroute {true | false}[0m
       Generates  the  scale factor for preroute extraction. When set to true,
       generates optimal scale factors for both signal nets and clock nets for
       preroute  extraction. Default: true [1m-postroute {low | medium} [22mSpecifies
       whether scale factors are to be generated for postRoute extraction.  It
       also  specifies  whether  scale  factors are to be generated for engine
       with effortLevel low only, or for both engines with effortLevel low and
       medium. If the -postroute parameter is not specified, scale factors are
       not generated for postRoute extraction. When you use the -postroute low
       parameter,  the  software  generates different scale factors for signal
       nets and clock nets. [1m-reference {low | medium | high | signoff | exter-[0m
       [1mnalSpef}  [22mSpecifies the postRoute engine or external SPEF that you want
       to use as reference for comparison. Default:  signoff  If  you  specify
       externalSpef,  you should use the -spefMapFile parameter to specify the
       third party SPEF  file(s)  to  be  used  for  comparison.  [1m-spefMapFile[0m
       [1m<file_name>  [22mSpecifies the SPEF map file to be used for comparison when
       using MMMC designs. When you use this parameter,  the  design  must  be
       placed  and  fully routed, and the referenced SPEF file must be the one
       generated from the same routed design. The map file has a  list  of  RC
       corners and the corresponding SPEF file for each RC corner, as shown in
       the following example: rcmin design_rcmin.spef rcmax  design_rcmax.spef
       [1m-use_ostrich_filters  file_name [22mSpecifies the filename containing user-
       specified ostrich filter values for Tcap, res, and  Xcap.  These  user-
       specified  values  are  applied  during  the  Ostrich run. In case this
       parameter is not specified by the user, default ostrich  filter  values
       will  be  used. The format of the file to be specified by the users for
       ostrich  filters  is:  -tcap  {-min_data  <value>   -max_data   <value>
       -min_fanout  <value>  -max_fanout  <value>  -max_perc_dev <value>} -res
       {-min_data <value> -max_data <value>  -min_fanout  <value>  -max_fanout
       <value>  -max_perc_dev  <value>}  -xcap  {-min_data  <value>  -max_data
       <value> -min_fanout <value> -max_fanout <value> -max_perc_dev <value>}
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

generate_esd_rlrp_report(21.15)                generate_esd_rlrp_report(21.15)



[1mName  generate_esd_rlrp_report  [22m- Reports the least-resistance path (RLRP) for
       the bump-to-clamp rule type in the ESD flow
[1mSyntax   generate_esd_rlrp_report   [22m[-help]   -net   <netname>[-number_threads
       <value>]   [-instance_pair_list   {{inst1   inst2   [pin1   pin2]}+}  |
       -instance_pair_list_file <filename>] -state_directory <directory>
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs the command usage and a brief description  about  the
       command  parameters. [1m-net <netname> [22mSpecifies the name of the net to be
       analyzed. [1m-number_threads  <value>  [22mSpecifies  the  maximum  number  of
       threads  to use when reporting the least-resistance path (RLRP) for the
       bump-to-clamp rule type in the ESD flow. Generally, using more  threads
       decreases  the  run  time.  There is no absolute limit to the number of
       threads you can use, however, it is recommended that you do not specify
       more threads than the number of CPUs available. The default value is 1,
       and the maximum value that can be specified  is  the  total  number  of
       available CPUs. [1m-instance_pair_list {{inst1 inst2 [pin1 pin2]}+} [22mSpeci-
       fies the instance pair list to enable effective resistance  calculation
       between  two  instances  in the design. pin is an optional argument. By
       default, the tool will use the instance pin  associated  with  the  net
       being  analyzed. The pin argument can be used in special cases when two
       different pins of an instance are connected to the same net.  <pin1>and
       <pin2>are pins of <inst2> respectively. If a pin name is not given, all
       pins   associated    to    the    specified    instance    are    used.
       [1m-instance_pair_list_file  <filename> [22mSpecifies the name of the instance
       pair list file. This file contains the instance pair list in  the  same
       format  as  mentioned  for  the -instance_pair_list parameter. The file
       allows  you  to   specify   a   large   number   of   instance   pairs.
       -instance_pair_list_file  and  -instance_pair_list  are mutually exclu-
       sive. [1m-state_directory <directory> [22mSpecifies  the  name  of  the  state
       directory in which the ESD analysis results are saved.
[1mExamples[0m

generate_tech_pg_lib(21.15)                        generate_tech_pg_lib(21.15)



[1mName generate_tech_pg_lib [22m- Generates the technology power-grid library on the
       fly
[1mSyntax     generate_tech_pg_lib     [22m[-help]     [-decap_cells     <cell_list>]
       [-default_power_voltage      <value>]      [-esd_cells     <cell_list>]
       [-filler_cells  <cell_list>]  [-keep  {true  |  false}]  [-lef_layermap
       <filename>]   [-output_dir  <dir_name>]  [-power_gate_file  <filename>]
       -tech_file filename [-tech_only {true | false}]
[1mParameters -help  [22mOutputs the command usage. [1m-decap_cells  <cell_list>  [22mSpeci-
       fies  the  names of cells that have explicit decoupling capacitance for
       use in  decap  optimization.  These  cells  are  nearly  equivalent  to
       feedthrough  cells,  except  that  there  is typically an active device
       between the power and ground nets to provide extra  decoupling  capaci-
       tance.  Power-grid  view  library generation uses this list of cells to
       ensure that a capacitance value is associated with  each  cell.  If  no
       capacitance  is  associated  with  a  cell,  a  warning message will be
       issued. [1m-default_power_voltage <value> [22mSpecifies voltage for the  power
       pins  which  are  present  in LEF. The default value is 1.2. [1m-esd_cells[0m
       [1m<cell_list> [22mSpecifies a list of Electrostatic  Discharge  (ESD)  cells.
       You  can  use  this  parameter to characterize ESD cells. [1m-filler_cells[0m
       [1m<cell_list> [22mList the names of the filler or feedthrough cells that have
       no  GDS  data.  These  cells can be swapped out for decaps during decap
       optimization. [1m-keep {true | false} [22mSpecifies that the generated library
       should  be  retained  after the session completes. The default value is
       false. [1m-lef_layermap <filename> [22mSpecifies a file that provides the map-
       ping  of  layers between the LEF and technology file. This parameter is
       optional. Library Generation automatically generates the layermap  file
       using the technology LEF (containing all layer and via definitions) and
       Quantus Tech (extraction library) files, therefore, a LEF layermap file
       is  not a mandatory input. The automatically generated layermap file is
       located in the PGV temp directory. The following is the format and sam-
       ple  content  of  the  auto-generated  file  (lefdefLayerMap_AutoGener-
       ated.txt): Layer Type tech_layername lefdef lefdef_layername via  VIA_9
       lefdef  VIA9 metal METAL_1 lefdef METAL1 You can specify this parameter
       if you want to provide your own layermap file.  [1m-output_dir  <dir_name>[0m
       Specifies  the  name  of the output directory in which tech-only power-
       grid library is created. The default is the current working  directory.
       [1m-power_gate_file  <filename> [22mSpecifies a file with the information that
       technology library generation needs to characterize a  powergate  cell.
       Specifies  the  cell name, unswitched power pin, switched power pin, on
       resistance in ohms, saturation current in milliamps, and  leakage  cur-
       rent  in  milliamps.  The  format  of  the  file  is:  <cell>  <supply>
       <switched> <Ron> <Idsat> <Ileak> The following is an example of  multi-
       ple footer powergate: FOOTBUFVHSV16 VSSG VSS 63 3.167 0.000128252 FOOT-
       BUFVHSV32 VSSG VSS 63 3.167 0.000128252 FOOTBUFVHSV64 VSSG VSS 63 3.167
       0.000128252  FOOTBUFVHSV8  VSSG  VSS  63  3.167  0.000128252 [1m-tech_file[0m
       [1m<filename> [22mMandatory parameter. Specifies the name  of  the  technology
       file that will be used for extraction. [1m-tech_only {true | false} [22mSpeci-
       fies to generate the technology PGV  without  any  cells.  The  default
       value is false.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

       [-break_at]         [-color_balance]        [-continue_on_no_selection]

getDistributeHost(21.15)                              getDistributeHost(21.15)



[1mName getDistributeHost [22m- Displays settings for the setDistributeHost command
[1mSyntax getDistributeHost [22m{-mode | -hosts | -queue | -resource | -custom_script
       | -env_script | -args | -single_cpu_lsf_args | -timeout | -shellTimeout
       | -reportLsfInfo <file> | -waitForLsfInfo <value>} [-help]
[1mParameters  -args  [22mDisplays the additional arguments when the software is run-
       ning in the Sun Grid Engine (SGE) or Load Sharing Facility (LSF)  mode.
       [1m-custom_script [22mDisplays the name of the custom script when the software
       is running in custom  mode.  [1m-env_script    [22mDisplays  the  user-defined
       shell  environment  script  that  is  run  for each of the slave hosts.
       [1m-hosts [22mDisplays the list of host names when the software is running  in
       rsh mode. [1m-help [22mOutputs the command usage and a brief description about
       the command parameters. [1m-mode [22mDisplays the distributed processing mode.
       The  possible  values  are  local,  sge,  rsh  ,  ssh , lsf and custom.
       Default: local [1m-queue [22mDisplays the queue name when the software is run-
       ning in sge or lsf mode. [1m-reportLsfInfo <file> [22mSpecifies to restore the
       LSF information to the specified file. This parameter can only be  used
       when  setDistributeHost -reportLsfInfo is specified in the current ses-
       sion. You must specify the getDistributeHost -reportLsfInfo only  after
       the  LSF  tasks  exit  to obtain the task CPU time. If you specify this
       command before the task exits, the command  gives  a  warning  message.
       [1m-resource  [22mDisplays the resource string when the software is running in
       sge or lsf mode. [1m-shellTimeout [22mDisplays the number of seconds the  host
       machine waits for rsh/ssh machines to become available for multiple-CPU
       processing. [1m-single_cpu_lsf_args [22mDisplays the lsf  arguments  when  the
       software  is running in lsf mode for a single CPU application. [1m-timeout[0m
       Displays the default timeout for a submitted job that will never start.
       [1m-waitForLsfInfo  <value>  [22mSpecifies the timeout period required to wait
       for task exit and generate the LSF information.
