       <y>}] }
[1mParameters  -auto_voltage_source_creation  {true|false} [22mSpecifies to automati-
       cally create voltage sources either for all nets (-net ALL)  or  for  a
       specific  net  (-net  net_name). The voltage sources are created on the
       top metal of all via cuts located  either  on  the  user-specified  via
       layer   or   the  design  top  via  layer  (default).  Default:  false.
       [1m-def_shape_only {true | false} [22mSpecifies to  generate  voltage  sources
       only  on the DEF routing shapes. This parameter controls the generation
       of voltage sources on the cell instance shapes. When this parameter  is
       set  to  false,  voltage  sources  are created for both the DEF routing
       shapes and shapes inside cell instances. This  parameter  is  specified
       with   the   -auto_voltage_source_creation   parameter.  Default:  true
       [1m-die_instance_name <dieinstname> [22mSpecifies the die  instance  name  for
       multi-die analysis. This option is only available in multi-die analysis
       (set_rail_analysis_mode    -die_mode    multi-die).     [1m-enable_switch-[0m
       [1mnet_ploc_generation  {true  |  false}  [22mSpecifies  to  generate  voltage
       sources on all switched nets. This  parameter  is  specified  with  the
       -auto_voltage_source_creation  parameter.  Default:  false [1m-file <file>[0m
       Specifies the name of the file containing the voltage  source  informa-
       tion. Not required for -format defpin option. [1m-format {defpin | padcell[0m
       [1m| xy | boundary | xyiv} [22mSpecifies how the voltage source is determined.
       Required  for xy, padcell, or boundary. defpin - Specifies that voltage
       sources will be determined by power  pins.  padcell  -  Specifies  that
       voltage  sources  will  be determined by pad cells. xy - Specifies that
       voltage sources will be specified by x y coordinates. boundary - Speci-
       fies  that  voltage  source locations will be used for instances in the
       design. xyiv - [1m-layer <vialayername> [22mSpecifies the via layer  on  which
       the voltage sources are to be generated. If this parameter is not spec-
       ified, the voltage sources will be generated on the top  via  layer  of
       the   design.   This   parameter  is  specified  with  the  -auto_volt-
       age_source_creation parameter. [1m-net <net_name> [22mSpecifies  the  name  of
       the  power  net. [1m-number_of_voltage_source <value> [22mSpecifies the number
       of voltage sources to be generated. You  can  adjust  either  -tile  or
       -number_of_voltage_source  to reduce the number of voltage sources cre-
       ated. This parameter is specified  with  the  -auto_voltage_source_cre-
       ation parameter. Default: 1 million. [1m-region {<x1> <y1> <x2> <y2>} [22mGen-
       erates the voltage sources in the specified region. If  this  parameter
       is  not  specified,  the software uses the entire design/layout size as
       the  region.  This  parameter  is  specified   with   the   -auto_volt-
       age_source_creation   parameter.   [1m-reset    [22mResets  all  the  previous
       set_power_pads commands [1m-short_pin_nodes {true |  false}  [22mSpecifies  to
       short all interface nodes on a pad cell pin to a single node and create
       voltage source for that node. Default:  false  Example:  set_power_pads
       -net <standard input>:37: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
 vdd  -format  padcell  -short_pin_nodes -file pad_cell.file [1m-tile[0m
       [1m{<x> <y>} [22mDefines the number of tiles in the  X  and  Y  direction  for
       automatic  creation  of  voltage  sources. When -tile is specified, the
       area (-region or default design area) will be tiled vertically and hor-
       izontally  per  the  given  tile size (x*y). For each tile, one voltage
       source will be created on the top metal of the biggest  via  array.  If
       -tile is not specified, the software creates voltage sources on the top
       metal of all via cuts located either on the user-specified via layer or
       the  top  via layer of the design. You can adjust either -tile or -num-
       ber_of_voltage_source to reduce the number of voltage sources  created.
       The -tile parameter is specified with the -auto_voltage_source_creation
       parameter.

       [1m<value2>[0m
[1mPlot Types Plot Type [22mDescription  [1mac  [22mAvailable/feasible  capacitance  (Farad)
       Displays  the  feasible decoupling capacitance that can be added in the
       area. The feasible capacitance in the area is calculated based  on  the
       filler  cells  placement.  The  program matches the placed filler cells
       with the decap cells available in the power-grid library  and  computes
       the  feasible  capacitance. The capacitance of the decap cell is stored
       in the power-grid library. [1mcap  [22mGgrid  capacitance  (Farad)  Plots  the
       capacitance of the extracted power-grid network. [1m<cvi1> [22mCustomized File
       1 Plots the user-specified instance voltage file. [1mdd [22mDecoupling capaci-
       tance  (decap) density (Farad/um 2 ) Plots decap density of the design.
       The decap density is the cell internal decoupling  capacitance  in  the
       unit area (m 2 ). [1mdr [22mDecoupling capacitance required Reports the decou-
       pling capacitance required to  fix  dynamic  IR-drop  violations.  This
       option suggests how much decap needs to be added in a given area to fix
       the IR-drop violations. The voltage threshold used to determine the IR-
       drop  violations  for  this  analysis  is  the  value  specified by the
       -threshold option of the set_pg_nets command. [1meffr [22mEffective resistance
       (ohm) - instance based Display the effective resistance results for all
       instances. [1mnode_reff [22mEffective resistance (ohm) -  node  based  Display
       the  effective resistance results for all nodes. [1mipc [22mInstance Peak Cur-
       rent Display the peak current of each instance. [1mivdn  [22mInstance  Voltage
       Drop  (Volts)  -  net-based  Plots the net-based instance voltage drop.
       [1mivdd [22mInstance Voltage Drop (Volts) -  domain-based  Plots  the  domain-
       based  instance  voltage drop. For domain based, at least one power and
       one ground net must be selected. [1mfd [22mFiller cell density (1/m 2  )  Dis-
       plays  the  filler  cell  density per unit area (m 2 ). The plot can be
       used to analyze the feasibility of adding decap cells by replacing  the
       filler  cells  and  not changing the placement of the logic cells. [1mfreq[0m
       Frequency domain (Hz) Displays the associated clock  frequency  of  all
       instances  in  the design. The instances associated with multiple clock
       domains are displayed using the fastest clock frequency. This plot  can
       be  used  to analyze and debug the power distribution in the design. [1mip[0m
       Instance total power (mW) The total power consumed by each instance  is
       displayed.  The  total  power is the sum of the internal, switching and
       leakage power of the instance. The power data is read  from  the  power
       database  and  can  be  specified  using  the -power_db option or it is
       queried directly from memory, if power calculation is  run  during  the
       session. [1mip_i [22mInstance internal power (mW) The power consumed by charg-
       ing and discharging of the internal  interconnect  and  device  capaci-
       tances of the instance. [1mip_l [22mInstance leakage power (mW) The power con-
       sumed by devices when not switching. [1mip_s [22mInstance switching power (mW)
       The  power  consumed by charging and discharging of the interconnect or
       output load. [1mipd_i [22mSpecifies internal power density in mW/um 2

       [1m-instance_voltage_window {1 | 0} [22mControls the EIV plot. EIV is obtained

[1mName  set_quiet_attacker [22m- Specifies one or more coupled nets as non-attackers
       (silent) for the delay and glitch analysis of a given victim net
[1mSyntax set_quiet_attacker [22m[-help] [-analysis_type {early |  late}]  [-attacker
       <string>]   [-transition  {rise  |  fall}]  [-victim  <string>]  [-view
       <string>]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints out the command usage. [1m-analysis_type {early  |  late}[0m
       Specifies  the  analysis  type  for which the attackers will be assumed
       quiet. If no  value  is  specified,  attackers  are  skipped  for  both
       early/late  analysis.  [1m-attacker <string> [22mSpecifies the attackers which
       should be made quiet for given victim net(s). If no attacker is  speci-
       fied,  all  the aggressors of given victim(s) will be ignored. Note: If
       no victim is specified, the specified attackers are made quiet for  all
       victim nets in the design. [1m-transition {rise | fall} [22mSpecifies the vic-
       tim transition for which attackers will be assumed quiet. If  no  value
       is  specified, attackers are skipped for both rise and fall transitions
       of the victim net. [1m-victim <string> [22mSpecifies a list of victim nets for
       which attackers should be made quiet. Specific attackers can be skipped
       using the -attacker option of this command. If the -attacker option  is
       not  specified, all the attackers of the given nets are made silent and
       SI analysis will not be performed on these nets. Note: If  this  option
       is  not  specified, the attackers specified in the -attacker option are
       made quiet for all the nets in the design. [1m-view <string> [22mSpecifies the
       view for which attackers should be made quiet. If no view is specified,
       attackers are assumed quiet in all views

[1mName set_rail_analysis_domain [22m- Specifies a rail analysis power domain
[1mSyntax   set_rail_analysis_domain   [22m[-help]   -name   <domain_name>   -pwrnets
       <power_net>_list -gndnets <ground_net_list> [-threshold <value>]
[1mParameters -gndnets <ground_net_list> [22mSpecifies a list of ground nets that are
       in  the  domain.  [1m-help   [22mOutputs a brief description that includes the
       type and default information for each set_rail_analysis_domain  parame-
       ter.  For  a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
       ters,   use   the    man    command    man    set_rail_analysis_domain.
       [1m-name<domain_name>  [22mSpecifies  the  name  of  the  power  domain. [1m-pwr-[0m
       [1mnets<power_net_list> [22mSpecifies a list of power nets  that  are  in  the
       domain. [1m-threshold <value> [22mSpecifies the minimum allowed voltage on the
       power net or the maximum rise on the ground net, depending on the  set-
       ting  of the-voltage parameter. The -thresholdparameter is used to ver-
       ify that the power grid passes the limit check and to set  the  filters
       for an IR plot. Note: This parameter does not support domains with MSMV
       power nets. If you have specified both net (set_pg_nets -threshold) and
       domain-based (set_rail_analysis_domain -threshold) thresholds, the net-
       based threshold will be honored.  The  valid  value  for  threshold  is
       between 0 and 0.5 (50%). For example, set_rail_analysis_domain -thresh-
       old 0.1 indicates that 0.1 is 10% IRdrop. If a power net in the  domain
       has  nominal voltage of 1v, 10% of threshold will translate to 100mV of
       maximum effective IRdrop between the power and ground net.

[1mName set_switching_activity [22m- Specifies activity for nets, pins, and ports
[1mSyntax  set_switching_activity [22m[-reset] [-activity <factor> | -density transi-
       tion_density   ]   [-clock   clock_name]   [-duty    <value>]    [-inst
       <instance_name>]  [-net <net_name>| -port <port_name>| -pin <pin_name>|
       -input_port    <port_name>|-output_port    <port_name>|     -bidir_port
       <port_name>]   [-period   <value>]   [-unclocked]   [-icg_ratio  <num>]
       [-comb_clockgate_ratio <num>] [-hier  <hierarchy_name>]  [-scale_factor
       <value>] [-cell <cell_name>] [-force] [-quiet]
[1mParameters  -activity  <factor> [22mSpecifies the activity for a net, pin, or top-
       level port. The <activity_factor> specifies the  number  of  times  the
       net, pin, or port switches in a clock cycle. Enter any positive number.
       If if the activity is set to 0.5, the activity happens once  for  every
       two  clock  cycles. If the activity is set to 2.0, the activity happens
       two times per clock cycle.  There  is  no  default  value.  [1m-bidir_port[0m
       [1m<port_name>  [22mSpecifies  the  name  of  the bidirectional port. The port
       names are in the following format: bidirectional-<port>. This parameter
       supports  wildcards (*) [1m-cell <cell_name> [22mSpecifies the activity on all
       output  pins  for  all  instances  of  the   specified   cell.   [1m-clock[0m
       [1m<clock_name>  [22mAssigns  global  activity factor to all nets in domain of
       <clock_name> if and only if <clock_name> is the fastest  clock  in  the
       domain set. To use this option, -clock and -activity must be used with-
       out any other options. [1m-comb_clockgate_ratio <num> [22mSpecifies to set the
       propagation ratio for combinational clock gate cell outputs. When spec-
       ified, this parameter sets the output activity of any instance that  is
       identified  as  a  combinational  clock  gating cell to <num> times the
       fastest transition density arriving on the instance's clock inputs. You
       can  specify this ratio for a net, pin, port, or clock. [1m-density <tran-[0m
       [1msition_density> [22mSpecifies the transition density for  a  specific  net,
       pin,  or  top-level  port.  Transition  density specifies the number of
       transitions per second. it can be any  positive  number.  There  is  no
       default  value. Note: If you specify the -density parameter in conjunc-
       tion with the -period parameter, the software issues a warning and  the
       -period  parameter  is ignored. [1m-duty <value> [22mSpecifies the duty cycle,
       which is the probability that the signal is a logical  1.  The  -period
       parameter  must  be  specified  to  add  a  duty. If not specified, the
       set_switcing_activity command picks this value from the external TWF or
       SDC  through  the  Common  Timing  Engine (CTE). Default: Uses the duty
       specified by the set_default_switching_activity command  if  the  -duty
       parameter  is  not  specified.  [1m-force  [22mSpecifies to apply user-defined
       activities for specific nets, pins, and ports, without having to load a
       verilog netlist using the set_top_module command. When the set_top_mod-
       ule command is not specified, the set_switching_activity  command  does
       not  support  the  -cell parameter, and the net/pin/port list using the
       get_pins/get_ports/get_nets commands. [1m-hier <hierarchy_name> [22mA  hierar-
       chical  name  that  an  activity is being assigned to. [1m-icg_ratio <num>[0m
       Specifies to set the propagation ratio for integrated clock gate  (ICG)
       cell outputs. When specified, this parameter sets the output pin of all
       identified ICG instances to <num> times the fastest transition  density
       arriving  on  clock  inputs of the instance. You can specify this ratio
       for a net, pin, port, or clock. [<standard input>:14: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')

       <input>-<port>.   This   parameter   supports   wildcards   (*)   [1m-inst[0m
       [1m<instance_name>  [22mSpecifies  the  activity  on a specific instance. [1m-net[0m
       [1m<net_name> [22mSpecifies the name of the net. This parameter supports wild-

       quency  is  used.  If  a negative number is specified, the static power
       calculation engine reverts back to the default frequency. Units in sec-

       picoseconds (ps). Note: If you specify the -period  parameter  in  con-

[1mName  set_table_style  [22m-  Disables printing of specific columns and allows for
       specifying the minimum and maximum size of each column in a report
[1mSyntax  set_table_style  [22m-help  -name  <string>  [-reverse_rows]  [-major_sort
       <integer>] [-minor_sort <integer>] [-max_widths <integer>] [-min_widths
       <integer>] [-indent <integer>] -frame | -no_frame_fix_width [-nosplit]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information for each set_table_style parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       set_table_style.  [1m-frame  [22mSpecifies that the table columns have a fixed
       frame or border, based on the minimum and maximum width  settings.  Any
       data  that  is  longer than the maximum width for its column is wrapped
       within the same column. This is the default format for tables.  [1m-indent[0m
       [1m<integer>  [22mSpecifies the number of spaces to leave on the left for that
       particular table. [1m-major_sort <integer> [22mSpecifies the column to be used
       in  the  major  sort. If the column number is negative, it reverses the
       sort. [1m-max_widths <integer> [22mSpecifies the maximum width for each  table
       column in the report specified by the -name parameter. Note: You cannot
       specify -max_widths parameter without  -name.  You  can  separate  each
       specified  width  value  with a comma (,). For example, if you specify:
       -max_widths {10,20,30} The first column will have a  maximum  width  of
       10,  the  second  column will have a maximum width of 20, and the third
       column will have a maximum width of 30. The fourth  and  fifth  columns
       will  remain  the  default  width spacing. Commas are also specified as
       column placeholders , when you want to change the spacing of  a  column
       without  changing  the spacing of the preceding column. For example, if
       you specify: -max_widths {,,20,30} The third column will have a maximum
       width of 20, the fourth column will have a maximum width of 30, and the
       first, second, and fifth columns will remain the default width spacing.
       If you specify: -max_widths {20,,30} The first column will have a maxi-
       mum width of 20, the third column will have a maximum width of 30,  and
       the  second,  fourth  and  fifth  columns will remain the default width
       spacing. Each column resizes itself to be between the range of the max-
       imum and minimum widths specified for that column, based on the data in
       that column. Overruns are wrapped within the same column, unless other-
       wise  specified. Default: {50,50,50,50,50} [1m-min_widths <integer> [22mSpeci-
       fies the minimum width for each table column in the report specified by
       the  -name  parameter.  Note:  You cannot specify -min_widths parameter
       without -name. You can separate each specified width value with a comma
       (,).  For example, if you specify: -min_widths {7,10,15} The first col-
       umn will have a minimum width of 7, the second column will have a mini-
       mum  width of 10, and the third column will have a minimum width of 15.
       The fourth and fifth columns will remain  the  default  width  spacing.
       Commas  are  also  specified  as column placeholders , when you want to
       change the spacing of a column without changing the spacing of the pre-
       ceding  column.  For  example, if you specify: -min_width {,,10,15} The
       third column will have a minimum width of 10, the  fourth  column  will
       have  a  minimum  width of 15, and the first, second, and fifth columns
       will remain the default  width  spacing.  If  you  specify:  -min_width
       {7,,10} The first column will have a minimum width of 7, the third col-
       umn will have a width of 10, and the second, fourth and  fifth<standard input>:14: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:16: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:20: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:22: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:27: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
  columns
       will remain the default width spacing. Each column resizes itself to be
       between the range of the maximum and minimum widths specified for  that
       column,  based  on the data in that column. Overruns are wrapped within
       the same  column,  unless  otherwise  specified.  Default:  {5,5,5,5,5}
       [1m-minor_sort  <integer>  [22mSpecifies  the  column  to be used in the minor
       sort. It applies  to  all  rows  that  have  the  same  values  in  the
       major_sort  column.  If  the  column  number  is negative, the software
       reverses the sort. [1m-name <string> [22mChanges the formatting for the speci-
       fied  table.  See tableTable for a list of table names you can use, and
       the commands with which they work. [1m-no_frame_fix_width  [22mSpecifies  that
       the table columns have a fixed minimum width, but no maximum width (the
       data does not wrap). Column data that fits within the column's  minimum
       width will left-justify and pad its location to fill the specified col-
       umn space. Column data that is longer than the column's  minimum  width
       will  take  as  much space in the table as needed. If a column is over-
       written by the data from the preceding column, its data will begin on a
       new line at the correct column location. Default: -frame [1m-nosplit [22mSpec-
       ifies that each column follows the preceding column  without  splitting
       to  a new line, if the data in one column overruns the next column. The
       wrapping behavior for data is controlled by the  size  of  the  display
       window. This format is useful for machine parsing the report. Note: You
       must specify  -no_frame_fix_width  in  order  to  use  this  parameter.
       [1m-reverse_rows  [22mReverses  the data rows. This is useful, for example, if
       you want to trace back from an end point and the default report  traces
       forward from the end point.

set_timing_derate(21.15)                              set_timing_derate(21.15)



[1mName  set_timing_derate [22m- Sets delay scaling or derating factors for early and
       late paths in the current design
[1mSyntax   set_timing_derate   [22m[-help]   <derate_value>[<object_list>]    [-add]
       [-cell_check]  [-cell_delay]  [-clock]  [-clock_period_check] [-corner]
       [-data] [-dynamic]  [-early]  [-fall]  [-increment]  [-input_switching]
       [-late]   [-mean]  [-multiply]  [-net_delay]  [-power_domain  <string>]
       [-pulse_width_check] [-retain_delay] [-rise] [-sigma] [-static]  [-sta-
       tistical] [-transition] [-min | -max | -delay_corner delayCornerName]
[1mParameters  -add  [22mIncrementally  adds or subtracts derates. You can also apply
       derates on specific leaf instances. [1m-cell_check  [22mSpecifies  scaling  on
       timing  checks.  Use  the  -cell_check option with the -early option to
       specify scaling on hold arcs and use with the -late option  to  specify
       scaling  on  setup arcs. When you specify this parameter, derating fac-
       tors are also applied to user  constraints  such  as  set_output_delay,
       set_data_check,  and  set_clock_gating_check. The -cell_check parameter
       by default does not apply check derate to output external delay  (e.g.,
       set_output_delay).  To  enable  this  feature,  you  can  set  the tim-
       ing_apply_check_derate_to_external_output_delay timing global  variable
       to  true.  When set to true, this global applies cell derate to the top
       boundary port. [1m-cell_delay [22mSpecifies scaling on cell delays. If neither
       the  -cell_delay  nor the -net_delay option is specified, the specified
       scaling factor applies to both types of  delays.  [1m-clock   [22mApplies  the
       derating  factors  to  clock  paths only. [1m-clock_period_check [22mSpecifies
       derate values for clock period  checks.  [1m-corner  [22mApplies  derating  on
       cells  or  nets that are modeled as corner data elements. The specified
       derating factor is applied to both the mean and  sensitivities  of  the
       delays  (corner objects can have propagated sensitivities). A cell with
       no timing arc data in a library that has  any  sensitivity  information
       with  respect to any parameter defined in SPDF are considered as a cor-
       ner object. All cells that do not qualify are considered to be  statis-
       tical objects. A net with parasitic data that has no sensitivity infor-
       mation with respect to any parameter defined in SPDF is considered as a
       corner  object.  All nets that do not qualify are considered to be sta-
       tistical objects. [1m-data  [22mApplies the derating  factors  to  data  paths
       only.  [1m-delay_corner  <delayCornerName>  [22mApplies the derating factor to
       the specified delay calculation corner or  a  list  of  delay  corners.
       Note:  The  timing  derate  can  be  applied to corners associated with
       active views only. [1m<derate_value> [22mSpecifies the derating  value  to  be
       used.  [1m-dynamic [22mApplies the specified derating factor to the delta por-
       tion of net delays only. You  can  specify  -net_delay  or  -cell_delay
       parameter with the -dynamic parameter. You cannot specify -dynamic with
       -mean or -sigma parameters. [1m-early  [22mSpecifies that the derating  factor
       applies  to  early  paths.  Early paths are launching clock during hold
       analysis, receiving clock during setup  analysis  and  datapath  during
       hold  analysis.  For  definition  of  early  and late paths, see Early-
       LatePaths in Innovus User Guide. Note: To use this parameter, you  must
       specify  -delay_corner.  [1m-fall  [22mApplies  the derating factor to falling
       delay and check arcs based on the transition  direction  at  the  arc's
       sink  pin.  This parameter can be used to selectively apply timing der-
       ates for the fall arcs (cell, net, or check arcs). <standard input>:15: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:17: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:18: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:22: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:25: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:28: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:30: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:32: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:34: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:36: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:38: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:41: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:42: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:43: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
<standard input>:46: warning: numeric expression expected (got `)')
[1m-increment [22mIncremen-
       tally  adds the derate value to the total derate value in all the modes
       - OCV, AOCV, and SOCV mode. [1m-input_switching [22mConsiders the given derate
       as  simultaneous  switching  input  (SSI)  derate that is applicable to
       early paths only. [1m-late  [22mSpecifies that the derating factor applies  to
       late  paths.  Late  paths  are  receiving  clock  during hold analysis,
       launching clock during setup analysis and datapath during setup  analy-
       sis.  Note:  To  use this parameter, you must specify the -delay_corner
       parameter. [1m-max [22mApplies the derating factor to  the  maximum  operating
       condition  during  best-case  worst-case  analysis.  This  parameter is
       ignored during on-chip variation analysis. Note:  You  cannot  use  the
       -max  parameter  when the software is in multi-mode multi-corner (MMMC)
       mode. You must use the -delay_corner parameter  instead.  [1m-min  [22mApplies
       the derating factor to the minimum operating condition during best-case
       worst-case analysis. This parameter is ignored during on-chip variation
       analysis.  Note: You cannot use the -min parameter when the software is
       in multi-mode multi-corner (MMMC) mode. You must use the  -delay_corner
       parameter instead. [1m-mean [22mControls nominal derating. You can apply sepa-
       rate derating the the mean components of the delay. [1m-multiply [22mIncremen-
       tally  multiplies  derates. You can also apply derates on specific leaf
       instances. [1m-net_delay [22mSpecifies scaling on  net  delays.  [1m<object_list>[0m
       Specifies  the  list  of instances, library cells, or nets to which the
       derating will be applied. [1m-power_domain <string> [22mAllows you to  specify
       a  specific  power  domain for the timing derate factors to be applied.
       [1m-pulse_width_check [22mSpecifies derate  values  for  pulse  width  checks.
       Note:  The  -pulse_width_check  and  -clock_period_check parameters are
       mutually exclusive. To apply check derating to pulse width checks,  set
       the  timing_enable_derating_for_pulsewidth_checks  global  variable  to
       true. By default, the global is set to false. [1m-retain_delay   [22mSpecifies
       scaling  on  retain  constructs.  If you specify both -retain_delay and
       -cell_delay parameters, the software uses the  retain_delay  value  for
       retain  construct  scaling.  If  you  do  not specify the -retain_delay
       parameter, retain constructs are scaled in  the  same  manner  as  cell
       delays.  [1m-rise  [22mApplies  the  derating factor to rising delay and check
       arcs based on the transition direction at  the  arc's  sink  pin.  This
       parameter  can be used to selectively apply timing derates for the rise
       arcs (cell, net, or check arcs). [1m-sigma [22mControls derating on the varia-
       tion component. You can apply separate derating to the sigma components
       of the delay. [1m-static [22mApplies the specified derating factor to the non-
       delta  portion  of  net  delays  only.  You  can  specify -net_delay or
       -cell_delay parameter with the -static parameter.  You  cannot  specify
       -static  with -mean or -sigma parameters. [1m-statistical [22mApplies derating
       on cells or nets that are modeled as  statistical  data  elements.  The
       specified  derating  factor  is  applied  to both the mean and sigma of
       delays. If both set_timing_derate -corner and -statistical options  are
       not  specified,  the derating factor is applied on variation and corner
       objects equally. This is equivalent to issuing to two separate set_tim-
       ing_derate  commands,  one  with -statistical option and the other with
       -corner option. [1m-transition  [22mSpecifies  scaling  on  transitions.  When
       specified, the software allows derate transition and stretch waveforms.

[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

[1mName  set_trace_obj_connectivity_mode  [22m-  Controls  certain aspects of how the

[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default

       detailed  description of the command and all of its parameters, use the

[1mSyntax  set_twf_attribute  [22m[-help]  [-clock <clock_name>] [-clock_edge {rise |

       gle_value}>] [-net <net_name>] [-pin <pin_name>] [-reset]  [-rise_delay
       <{min:max>or<single_value}>]  [-rise_slack <{min:max>or<single_value}>]
       [-rise_slew  <{min:max>or<single_value}>]  [-type   {data   |   clock}]
       [-shift_arrival_time <time>] [-clear_twf_attr]
[1mParameters  -clear_twf_attr  [22mSpecifies to reset the TWF file values for a spe-
       cific pin or net. The use model of this parameter is: set_twf_attribute
       -clear_twf_attr  -pin/-net  <<name>>  [1m-clock <clock_name> [22mSpecifies the
       clock name. This indicates that the nets and pins that are timing  con-
       strained  have  arrival  times  (timing  windows) caused by this clock.
       [1m-clock_edge {rise | fall} [22mSpecifies the capturing clock edge direction:
       rise  or  fall.  [1m-clock_freq <value> [22mSpecifies the clock frequency. You
       must specify the -clock parameter along with the -clock_freq  parameter
       to  assign  the  clock  for  which  the  frequency needs to be updated.
       [1m-fall_delay <{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the  fall  delay  for
       the  pin.  This parameter is not supported in the static power analysis
       flow. [1m-fall_slack <{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the fall  slack
       for  the pin. [1m-fall_slew <{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the fall
       slew for the pin. [1m-net<net_name> [22mSpecifies the net name. The  -net  and
       -pin parameters are mutually exclusive. [1m<-pin> <pin_name> [22mSpecifies the
       pin name. The -net and -pin parameters are mutually  exclusive.  [1m-reset[0m
       Resets  all  specified  options  back  to  default  values. [1m-rise_delay[0m
       [1m<{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the rise delay for the pin.  This
       parameter   is  not  supported  in  the  static  power  analysis  flow.
       [1m-rise_slack <{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the  rise  slack  for
       the pin. [1m-rise_slew <{min:max>or<single_value}> [22mSpecifies the rise slew
       for the pin. [1m-shift_arrival_time   <time> [22mSpecifies to filter the  idle
       period of the current waveform in the dynamic power analysis flow. This
       parameter is useful in removing the idle period of the current waveform
       result  with  long idle period (small current) before the 1st high cur-
       rent peak because of TWF delay annotation. The parameter allows to off-
       set idle period from the TWF delay values.

set_via_pillars(21.15)                                  set_via_pillars(21.15)



[1mName  set_via_pillars [22m- This command sets a via pillar list for a cell term or
       a single via pillar for an instterm
[1mSyntax  set_via_pillars  [22m[-help]  {-term  <term>   |   -instterm   <instterm>}
       <stack_via_rule+> [-required {0 | 1}]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information for each set_via_pillars parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion  of  the  command and all its parameters, use the man command: man
       set_via_pillars [1m-instterm <instterm> [22mSpecifies  the  instterm  name  or
       pointer. Only one via pillar is allowed for instterm. [1m<stack_via_rule+>[0m
       Provides a list of via pillars for an cell term, or a single via pillar
       for  an instterm. This list further provides the candidates of instterm
       via pillar setting. On running: set_via_pillars -term BUFX1/Z -required
       1  {vp_rule1  vp_rule2}  set_via_pillars automatically sets the minimal
       cost via pillar rule for the corresponding instterm, which is vp_rule1.
       You  can also set the other via pillar rule to the instterm by running:
       set_via_pillars -instterm i1/i2/Y vp_rule2  An  empty  <stack_via_rule>
       will  remove  the  via  pillar from instterm: set_via_pillars -instterm
       i1/i2/Y -required 1 [1m-required {0 | 1} [22mOn setting as 1 for a term,  this
       parameter  enforces  the  via  pillars  on all the instterms, which are
       instantiated by the specified term. On setting as 1 for an instterm  or
       cell term, it enforces the via pillar only on the specified instterm or
       cell term. However, if the via pillar list is empty for an instterm, no
       via  pillar  will be used even when the required bit is 1. [1m-term <term>[0m
       Specifies the Term name (cell name/term base_name) or  pointer.  A  via
       pillar list is allowed for term.
[1mExamples[0m

signoffOptDesign(21.15)                                signoffOptDesign(21.15)



[1mName  signoffOptDesign  [22m- Runs timing, area, DRV, dynamic or leakage optimiza-
       tion on signoff timing
[1mSyntax signoffOptDesign  [22m[-help]  [-all]  [-area]  [-drv]  [-dynamic]  [-hold]
       [-leakage]  [-noEcoRoute]  [-outDir  <dir_name>] [-reportFullClockPath]
       [-power] [-prefix <prefix_name>] [-setup]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information   for  each  signoffOptDesign  parameter.  For  a  detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  signoffOptDesign  [1m-all [22mPerforms DRV, Setup, Hold, and Power
       optimization in the path-based analysis (PBA) mode.  It  also  includes
       embedded  calls  to  ecoRoute,  parasitic extraction and signoff timing
       analysis. Note:The all-in-one mode  does  not  replace  all  customized
       fine-tuned  flows.  It provides the Innovus users easy access to Tempus
       ECO technology. The existing Tempus ECO flow using individual optimiza-
       tion  steps within Innovus is still supported and can sometimes be more
       efficient than the all-in-one mode. [1m-area [22mReclaims area on the  netlist
       without  causing  any  DRV/Setup/Hold  degradation.  [1m-drv [22mOptimizes DRV
       (maximum capacitance and maximum transition) violations. DRV  optimiza-
       tion supports buffer addition and resizing. [1m-dynamic [22mPrints initial and
       final power numbers. It optimizes the dynamic power to reduce the total
       power  consumption. Dynamic power optimization supports buffer deletion
       ,resizing, and swapping. [1m-hold [22mTriggers hold fixing in  signoff  timing
       mode.  [1m-leakage  [22mOptimizes leakage power. Leakage optimization supports
       VT swapping. [1m-noEcoRoute [22mAllows signoffOptDesign command  to  skip  ECO
       routing  and final signoff STA. [1m-outDir <dir_name> [22mSpecifies the direc-
       tory in which the reports will be saved. Note: In case signoffOptDesign
       is reusing ECO timing DB generated earlier by signoffTimeDesign or when
       the -noEcoRoute parameter is applied,  no  timing  reports  are  saved.
       [1m-power  [22mOptimizes  total  power in the design. During total power opti-
       mization, the software performs swapping and sizing on both the  combi-
       national  and  the  sequential  cells,  and  also removes buffers. This
       reduces leakage, internal, and switching power in the  design.  [1m-prefix[0m
       [1m<prefix_name>  [22mSpecifies  the  prefix for the timing report file names.
       [1m-reportFullClockPath [22mWhen this parameter  is  specified,  the  detailed
       timing  report  that  is generated contains the full clock path. [1m-setup[0m
       Optimizes setup timing violations. Setup optimization  supports  buffer
       addition, VT swapping and resizing.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022    signoffOptDesign(21.15)

specifyBlackBox(21.15)                                  specifyBlackBox(21.15)



[1mName specifyBlackBox [22m- Converts a hard macro into a blackbox
[1mSyntax specifyBlackBox [22m[-help] [-coreSpacing {<left right top bottom>}] [-min-
       PitchLeft <integer>] [-minPitchRight  <integer>]  [-minPitchTop  <inte-
       ger>]  [-minPitchBottom  <integer>]  [-pinLayerLeft {<list_of_layers>}]
       [-pinLayerRight {l<ist_of_layers>}]  [-pinLayerTop  {<list_of_layers>}]
       [-pinLayerBottom   {<list_of_layers>}]  [-reservedLayer  {<list_of_lay-
       ers>}]  [-placementHalo  {<left  right  top   bottom>}]   [-routingHalo
       <float>]   [-routingHaloTopLayer   <integer>]  [-routingHaloBottomLayer
       <integer>] [-noRebuildTiming] [ -cell <string>|  -masterInst  <string>]
       {-size  {<x  y>}  |  -area  <float>  | -gateCount <string> | {-gateArea
       <float>[-cellUtil <float>] [  -includeMacroArea  {0  |  1}  {-macroArea
       <float>| -macroList {<macroName> [<count>]}}]}} [{-area <float>| -gate-
       Count <string>} [-minWidth <float> | -minHeight <float>  |  -fixedWidth
       <float>  |  -fixedHeight  <float>  ]]  [-minWidth  <float> | -minHeight
       <float> | -fixedWidth <float> | -fixedHeight <float> |-aspectRatioRange
       {<min max>}] [-aspectRatio <float>|-aspectRatioRange {<min max>}]
[1mParameters  -area <float>   [22mSpecifies the total area in square micrometers. If
       you specify the block size area, the  default  for  the  created  block
       aspect  ratio  is  1.  Data_type:  float, optional [1m-aspectRatio <float>[0m
       Specifies the aspect ratio value. This value  combined  with  the  area
       information determines the width and height. Data_type: float, optional
       [1m-aspectRatioRange {<min max>} [22mSets the minimum and maximum  values  for
       the  aspect ratio range. This value combined with the specified related
       area information enables the blackbox to be reshaped while  maintaining
       the current area. Data_type: point, optional [1m-cell <string>   [22mSpecifies
       the name of the cell. Data_type:  string,  optional  [1m-cellUtil  <float>[0m
       Specifies  the  cell utilization. This value is used to derive the area
       of the blackbox, which is calculated using the following formula:Black-
       box  area  =  (standard  cell  area  /  cell  utilization) + macro area
       Default: The default value of cell utilization is 1 (100%).  Data_type:
       float,  optional  [1m-coreSpacing  {<left right top bottom>} [22mSpecifies the
       space, in micrometers, between the module boundary and core design area
       of  the  module on the left, right, top, and bottom sides respectively.
       The partition pins will be located at the partition  instance  boundary
       and  the  core  area.  Data_type: string, optional [1m-fixedHeight <float>[0m
       Specifies the fixed height of the module.  Data_type:  float,  optional
       [1m-fixedWidth   <float>    [22mSpecifies  the  fixed  width  of  the  module.
       Data_type: float, optional [1m-gateArea <float> [22mSpecifies the  gate  area.
       If  the value of the -includeMacroArea parameter is 0, the gate area is
       equal to the standard cell area. If the value of the  -includeMacroArea
       parameter  is 1, the gate area also includes the macro area. Data_type:
       float, optional [1m-gateCount <string>   [22mSpecifies a gate count value. The

[1mName  specifyCellEdgeType  [22m- Specifies edge type for cell edges as EDGETYPE in
       macro LEF
[1mSyntax specifyCellEdgeType [22m[-help] {-left <edgeType>  |  -right  <edgeType>  |
       -top  <edgeType>  |  -bottom <edgeType> | -reset } [{-left <edgeType> |
       -right <edgeType>} [-cellRow <rowNumber>]] [{-left <edgeType> |  -right
       <edgeType>}  [-half  {top  |  bottom}]]  [{-top  <edgeType>  |  -bottom
       <edgeType>} [-range {x y}]] [{-cell <cellName>} [-reset]]
[1mParameters -bottom <edgeType> [22mSpecifies an edge type on the bottom side. [1m-cell[0m
       [1m<cellName>   [22mSpecifies  cell  to which to add edge constraint. [1m-cellRow[0m
       [1m<rowNumber> [22mSpecifies the row number for horizontal edge type. You  can
       define different edge types for each row of multiple height cells using
       -cellRow. For example, there is triple height cell CKBUF.  (<Image>  To
       view  the  image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference - Release
       21.1 manual.) The following commands define different  edge  types  for
       different  rows  of  the  CKBUF  cell.  specifyCellEdgeType -cell CKBUF
       -right grp1 -cellRow 1  specifyCellEdgeType  -cell  CKBUF  -right  grp2
       -cellRow 2 In the above example, grp1 is applied to the first row (bot-
       tom row) of the right edge, grp2 is applied to the second row of  right
       edge,  and  no specific edge type is defined for the third row of right
       edge and is of DEFAULT type. The legal value of -cellRow is from  1  to
       n, where n is the number of cell height of the cell. [1m-half {top bottom}[0m
       Defines the edge types corresponding to the top or bottom half  of  the
       cell.  The  following  example associates the edge type 'grp1' with the
       bottom row, top half of the  multi-height  cell  SDFF8:  specifyCellEd-
       geType  -cell  SDFF8  -right  grp1 -cellRow 1 -half top [1m-help [22mOutputs a
       brief description that includes type and default information  for  each
       specifyCellEdgeType  parameter.  For a detailed description of the com-
       mand and all of its parameters, use the man command: man specifyCellEd-
       geType [1m-left <edgeType> [22mDefines the edge types corresponding to the top
       or bottom half of the cell. The following example associates  the  edge
       type  'grp1'  with  the  bottom  row, top half of the multi-height cell
       SDFF8. specifyCellEdgeType -cell SDFF8 -right grp1 -cellRow 1 -half top
       [1m-range  {<x>  <y>}  [22mSpecifies the range for the vertical edge type. The
       range for the vertical edge type can also be  negative.  The  following
       example  defines  a  partial  range  of an edge that the type should be
       labeled.This could only be defined on TOP  or  BOTTOM  edges.  specify-
       CellEdgeType -cell A -top GROUP1 -range 0 0.1 specifyCellEdgeType -cell
       A -bottom GROUP1 -range 0 0.1 specifyCellEdgeType -cell A  -top  GROUP2
       -range 0.2 0.3 specifyCellEdgeType -cell A -top GROUP3 -range 0.15 0.25
       (<Image> To view the image, refer to the Innovus Text Command Reference
       - Release 21.1 manual.) [1m-reset  [22mResets the specified cell constraint to
       the LEF status. [1m-right <edgeType> [22mSpecifies an edge type on  the  right
       side. [1m-top <edgeType> [22mSpecifies an edge type on the top side.

       this command after importing the design
[1mSyntax specifyNetWeight [22m[-help] netName
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default information for each specifyNetWeight parameter. For a detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  specifyNetWeight  [1m<netName..>  [22mSpecifies  the name(s) of an
       individual net.  You  can  use  wildcards  (*?)  with  this  parameter.
       Data_type:  string,  required  [1m<netWeightValue> [22mSpecifies the weighting
       priority of the net name, with values 512 (highest) through 1 (lowest),
       or  0  (don't care). Default: If you do not specify this parameter, the
       weight for nets is 2. The placer will try to shorten nets  with  higher
       weight,  and  give  less  priority to lower weights (ignoring nets with
       weight 0). The placer has a limit of 10 for  the  highest  weight,  and
       will  treat  any  value  above  10  as 10. The router will route higher
       weighted nets before lower weighted nets. Data_type: string, required

spefIn(21.15)                                                    spefIn(21.15)



[1mName  spefIn  [22m-  Loads  resistors and capacitors for the interconnects in SPEF
       into the Innovus database to calculate delays or build a timing graph
[1mSyntax spefIn [22m[-help] <fileNameList> [-extended] [-idx] [-scaleNets  <netFile-
       Name>] [-scaleRC] [-starN | -noStarN] [{-rc_corner <list_of_rc_corners>
       [-spef_field {1 2 3
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each  spefIn parameter. For a detailed description of
       the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man spefIn.
       [1m-extended   [22mEnables   the   reading   of   $llx=<value1>  $lly=<value2>
       $urx=<value3> $ury=<value4> $LAYER=<number> to set the layer number for
       nodes of a resistance from Quantus extended SPEF file. It also reads in
       extended *LAYER_MAP section, if it is present. This parameter can  also
       read in $l=<length> $w=<width> $si_w=<swidth> $lvl=<number > to set the
       width, silicon width, or layer for nodes of a  resistance  from  StarRC
       extended  SPEF file. [1m-idx [22mEnables Inter-Die Extraction (IDX) SPEF read-
       ing. IDX SPEF models the Inter-Die capacitive impact  in  the  form  of
       coupling  and ground capacitances. Individual die and IDX SPEFs need to
       be extracted by Quantus and in the extended SPEF  (xSPEF)  format.  The
       -extended  parameter is also required to be specified to read the xSPEF
       format. The software also supports multiple IDX SPEF reading. Flat die-
       level  SPEFs  need  to be specified along with IDX SPEFs. With the -idx
       parameter, die-level and IDX SPEFs  can  be  specified  in  any  order.
       [1m<fileNameList> [22mSpecifies a SPEF file or list of SPEF files as input for
       flat chip or  hierarchical  SPEF  stitching,  respectively.  [1m-rc_corner[0m
       [1m<list_of_rc_corners> [22mAnnotates the parasitics to the predefined RC cor-
       ners for multi-corner analysis. You can specify a list of RC corners to
       be  annotated.  If  you  want  to use SPEF information when calculating
       delays in multi-mode multi-corner analysis (MMMC) mode, you must  anno-
       tate  the  parasitics  for all RC corners in the design. A few examples
       are provided below to explain different scenarios of specifying rc cor-
       ners are their corresponding corner indices and SPEF files.
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

[1mName  staggerBondPad [22m- Generates a staggered wirebond pad pattern on top of an
       existing I/O ring
[1mSyntax staggerBondPad  [22m[-help]  {-startIoInstName  <instName>  [-endIoInstName
       <instName>] | -ring <number> | -side {e | w | n | s} [-ring <number>] |
       -all} {-pattern <pattern_string> | -startStaggerPosition {i | m  |  o}}
       [-pad <position> <padName position padName...>] [-pinName <pinName>]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mOutputs  a brief description that includes type and default
       information for each staggerBondPad parameter. For a detailed  descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       staggerBondPad [1m-all [22mSpecifies that bond pads will be placed on all  I/O
       instances. [1m-endIoInstName <instName> [22mSpecifies the name of the last I/O
       instance of where bond pads will be placed. You can use this  parameter
       in conjunction with the -startIoInstName parameter. Note: Bond pads are
       placed in a clock-wise pattern from the starting I/O  instance  (-star-
       tIoInstName)  to  the  last  I/O instance (-endIoInstName). [1m-pad <posi-[0m
       [1mtion><padName><position><padName>... [22mSpecifies which bond pad and posi-
       tion to use when multiple bond pads are specified in the LEF file for a
       given inner (i), middle (m), or outer (o)  position.  For  example,  If
       there  are three outer bond pads specified in the LEF file, you can use
       this parameter to choose which bond pad to use as the outer  bond  pad.
       Default:  The software uses the first bond pad in the list of bond pads
       for a given position. [1m-pattern <pattern_string> [22mSpecifies  the  stagger
       pattern  of the bond pads on the I/O instances. <pattern_string> speci-
       fies any combination of i (inner), m (middle), and o (outer).  [1m-pinName[0m
       [1m<pinName>  [22mSpecifies  the  name  of the pin inside the instance. If the
       instance specified by the -startIoInstName parameter contains  multiple
       pins,  you use this parameter to specify which pin to start with. [1m-ring[0m
       [1m<number> [22mSpecifies which ring to operate on with ring 1 being the outer
       most  ring.  The ring number is incremented by one as you get closer to
       the core. For a three-ring design, the inner most ring is ring 3. [1m-side[0m
       [1m{e  |  w  |  n | s} [22mSpecifies the geographical side of the die. You can
       specify the East (e), West (w), North (n), or South  (s)  side  of  the
       die.  [1m-startIoInstName  <instName>  [22mSpecifies the name of the first I/O
       instance of where bond pads will be placed. You can use this  parameter
       in  conjunction  with  the  -endIoInstName  parameter. If multiple pins
       exist in the instance, you can use the -pinName  parameter  to  specify
       which  pin  to  start  with. Note: Bond pads are placed in a clock-wise
       pattern from the starting I/O instance (-startIoInstName) to  the  last
       I/O instance (-endIoInstName) if applicable. [1m-startStaggerPosition {i |[0m
       [1mm | o} [22mSpecifies the starting stagger position of  the  specified  bond
       pad  (-pad)  on  the specified I/O instance (-startIoInstName). You can
       start the stagger position of the bond pad using the inner (i),  middle
       (m),  or  outer  (o) position. The default stagger position sequence is
       inner (i), middle (m), and outer (o). If you start with a stagger posi-
       tion of middle (m), the next bond pad is placed in an outer (o) stagger
       position followed by a bond pad placed in an inner  (i)  stagger  posi-
       tion.
[1mExample[0m

       in the sections on the main HTML report  page  include  links  to  more

       link under the General Library Information section of the HTML  report,
       the  software  displays  a  detailed  HTML  report on the layers in the
       design. Note: If you  specify  -noText,  you  cannot  specify  -noHtml.
       Default:  The  report  is  generated  in  both  HTML  and  text format.
       Data_type: bool, optional [1m-outdir <directoryName> [22mSpecifies the  direc-
       tory in which the HTML and text reports are saved. If -noText is speci-
       fied, saves only the HTML version of the report to the specified direc-
       tory.  The -outdir parameter cannot be used with -noHtml. Default: sum-
       maryReport Data_type: string, optional [1m-outfile <fileName>  [22mWrites  the
       text version of the report to the specified file. Note: You can specify
       this option only if  you  specify  -noHtml.  Default:  If  you  specify
       -noHtml  and do not specify -outFile, the software writes the text ver-
       sion of the report to a file named <design_name>.main.htm.ascii in  the
       summaryReport folder. Data_type: string, optional
[1mExamples[0m

swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell(21.15)  swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell(21.15)



[1mName  swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell [22m- Identifies the regular buffer/inverter
       and swaps it with always-on buffer/inverter
[1mSyntax  swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell  [22m[-help]   [-cellMapFile   <filename>]
       [-defaultAlwaysOnCell  <AoCellNames>]  [-nets  <LPErrorNetList>] [-ver-
       bose]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information  for  each swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell parameter. For a
       detailed description of the command and all its parameters, use the man
       command:  man  swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOnCell  [1m-cellMapFile <filename>[0m
       Specifies the map file name. The map file provides the equivalent driv-
       ing   strength   between   the  regular  buffer/inverter  and  AO  buf-
       fer/inverter. This means that the timing  will  not  be  degraded  with
       using  this  parameter,  when  the mapped always-on cell is swapped in.
       Following is the  map  file  format:  regularBufCellName  AoBufCellName
       [1m-defaultAlwaysOnCell <AoCellNames> [22mSpecifies the default always-on buf-
       fer/inverter to be used to replace the  regular  buffer/inverter.  When
       using  default  always-on buffer/inverter, this parameter just corrects
       the LP error. Additionally, this parameter may degrade the timing,  and
       you  need to run optimization in flow. [1m-nets <LPErrorNetList> [22mSpecifies
       the list of LP-error nets. By default, the swapRegularCellWithAlwaysOn-
       Cell  command works on all the buffer/inverter trees. When this parame-
       ter is used, the command works on  the  buffer/inverter  tree  for  the
       specified  nets.  [1m-verbose  [22mDisplays the detailed trace information for
       the specified nets.
[1mExamples[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:s0w2a:p1R5eg2u0l2a2rCellWithAlwaysOnCell(21.15)

[1mName swapSignal [22m- Swaps signal between selected instances (I/O pads or bumps).

[1mSyntax swapSignal [22m[-help]  [[-from  {<nameList>}  -to  {<nameList>}]  |  -cir-
       cle_offset <value>]
[1mParameters  -help  [22mPrints a brief description of the swapSignal command. For a
       detailed description of the command, use the man command: man  swapSig-
       nal  [1m-circle_offset <value> [22mSpecifies the offset value to swap bumps in
       circle. The value should be be positive and less than the number of the
       selected  bumps.  For  example,  if  you select the bumps bump1, bump2,
       bump3, bump4 and bump5 in the GUI and specify -circle_offset as 2,  the
       result  of  signal  swapping  will  be  as follows: bump1(S1) bump2(S2)
       bump3(S3)  bump4(S4)  bump5  (S5)  ->  bump1(S4)  bump2(S5)   bump3(S1)
       bump4(S2) bump5 (S3) [1m-from <nameList> [22mSpecifies the names of bumps from
       which signal is to be swapped. [1m-to <nameList> [22mSpecifies  the  names  of
       bumps to which signal is to be swapped.

       of  the  clock  tree. Instead, the amendments, which are in the form of
       Tcl commands, are written to the file specified using  this  parameter.
       [1m-use_estimated_routes  [22mSpecifies  that  NanoRoute should not be called.
       So, the routing estimates are left in the netlist.

[1mName trimMetalFillNearNet [22m- Trims any metal fill around critical nets
[1mSyntax  trimMetalFillNearNet  [22m[-help] [-area {x1 y1 x2 y2}] [-clock] [-create-
       FillBlockage <blockage_name>] [-layer <layer_name_list>]  [-minTrimDen-
       sity    {<percent1>    <layer_list1>   [{<percent2>   <layer_list2>}]}]
       [-minTrimUnionDensityToAboveLayer {<percent1  layer_list1>  [{<percent2
       layer_list2>}]..}] [-net {<net_name_list> | <net_object_pointer_list>}]
       [-recomputeDensity] [-remove] [-slackThreshold <slack_in_ns>] [-spacing
       <dist_in_um>] [-spacingAbove <dist_in_um>] [-spacingBelow <dist_in_um>]

[1mParameters -help  [22mPrints a  brief  description  that  includes  the  type  and
       default  information  for  each  trimMetalFillNearNet  parameter. For a
       detailed description of the command and all  its  parameters,  use  man
       trimMetalFillNearNet.  [1m-area  {x1  y1 x2 y2} [22mSpecifies a set of coordi-
       nates within which to trim metal fill. If this parameter is not  speci-
       fied,  metal  fill is trimmed around critical nets in the entire design

       clock.  [1m-createFillBlockage  <blockage_name> [22mCreates a fill blockage so
       that any subsequent fill steps do not refill the trimmed area.  If  you
       specify  a  name, the tool uses that name as the fill blockage name. If
       you do not specify a name, the tool uses the default name <netName_lay-
       erName_*>  for  the fill blockage. [1m-layer <layer_name_list> [22mTrims metal
       fill only on the specified layers. If this parameter is not  specified,
       metal   fill   is  trimmed  on  all  layers.  [1m-net  {<net_name_list>  |[0m
       [1m<net_object_pointer_list>} [22mSpecifies a list of critical  net  names  or
       pointers  which  are  surrounded  by metal fill. [1m-minTrimDensity {<per-[0m
       [1mcent1><layer_list1> [{<percent2><layer_list2>}]} [22mTrims metal fill  only
       until the specified window density percentage is reached to avoid caus-
       ing any metal density violations. The window sizes  are  controlled  by
       setMetalFill.  verifyMetalDensity  is used to compute the metal-density
       using the same setMetalFill settings. You can specify different  window
       density  percentages  for  different layers. For example, {{20 1 2} {30
       3}} would set the min-density for metal1, metal2 windows  to  20%,  and
       for   metal3   to   30%.   [1m-minTrimUnionDensityToAboveLayer  {<percent1[0m
       [1mlayer_list1> [{<percent2 layer_list2>}]..} [22mTrims metal fill  only  till
       meeting the specified percent window density. Default: 0 [1m-recomputeDen-[0m
       [1msity [22mBy default, if metal density values are required for  -minTrimDen-
       sity,  and  they  are available in the database from a previous call to
       verifyMetalDensity, the existing database values are used. This  option
       forces  a  call  to  verifyMetalDensity  to  recompute window densities
       instead of using the stored values. [1m-remove [22mSpecifies  that  the  metal
       fill  shapes  overlapping  the critical-net halo area should be removed
       entirely instead of being trimmed to the halo edge created with differ-
       ent  -spacing*  options.  This  avoids the possibility of smaller metal
       fill shapes that might be left  over  after  trimming.  [1m-slackThreshold[0m
       [1m<slack_in_ns>  [22mTrims  metal  fill  around nets with slack less than the
       specified value. The value specified should be in nanoseconds. [1m-spacing[0m
       [1m<dist_in_um>  [22mTrims fill on the same layer by specified distance around
       critical net routes. The distance specified should  be  in  micrometers
       (um).   The  default  is  0  so  no  trimming  is  done.  [1m-spacingAbove[0m
       [1m<dist_in_um> [22mTrims fill on the layer above the current layer by  speci-
       fied distance around critical net routes. The distance specified should
       be in micrometers (um). The default is 0 so no trimming is done. [1m-spac-[0m
       [1mingBelow  <dist_in_um>  [22mTrims fill on the layer below the current layer
       by specified distance around critical net routes. The  distance  speci-
       fied  should be in micrometers (um). The default is 0 so no trimming is
       done.

trim_pg(21.15)                                                  trim_pg(21.15)



[1mName  trim_pg  [22m-  This command offers a semi-automated mechanism that helps in
       trimming the redundant PG stripes and vias using an existing power grid
       pattern based on IR drop analysis reports
[1mSyntax   trim_pg   [22m[-help]   [-area  {<x1,  y1,  x2,  y2>}  |  -candidate_file
       <file_name>] <-net net_name> {{-layer  {<layer_name1>  [<layer_name2>]}
       -pattern {<str1> [<str2>
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information for each trim_pg parameter. For a detailed  description  of
       the  command  and  all its parameters, use the man command: man trim_pg
       [1m-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>} [22mDefines the area in which stripes and vias are to
       be  trimmed.  The  stripes overlapped with the box defined by -area are
       trimmed. Default: entire core area [1m-candidate_file  <file_name>  [22mSpeci-
       fies  the  candidate  filename. [1m-exclude {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2 ly2[0m
       [1mux2 uy2>}...} [22mExcludes the box areas for the stripes and vias in  which
       the  part  of  stripes  need  not to be trimmed. This parameter is used
       along with the -area parameter to specify the  exclusion  areas.  If  a
       stripe partially overlaps with the exclusion area, the overlapping seg-
       ment of the stripe is not trimmed.  The  exclusion  box  can  partially
       overlap  the  -area box. [1m-exclude_local_grid {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2[0m
       [1mly2 ux2 uy2>}...} [22mExcludes the areas in which  the  whole  stripes  are
       skipped  for  trimming.  If  a  stripe  is completely inside one of the
       -exclude_local_grid box (can touch the boundary), it is  excluded  from
       the  trim candidates and is not counted when applying the trim pattern.
       It is useful when trimming is done on a large area but there are  local
       stripes  in  this area, which could affect the global trim pattern. The
       exclusion box can partially overlap the -area  box.  [1m-keep_dangling_via[0m
       Keeps  the  dangling  vias while trimming stripes. By default, dangling
       vias are removed. [1m-layer {<layer_name1> [<layer_name2>]} [22mSpecifies  the
       metal layer names for stripe and via trimming. While trimming a stripe,
       specify <layer_name1> on which the stripes are  to  be  trimmed.  While
       trimming  via, specify <layer_name2>between which the stack vias are to
       be trimmed. The first layer is used as the reference while applying the
       via trim pattern. [1m-net<net_name> [22mSpecifies the power or ground net name
       to be trimmed. [1m-pattern {<str1> [<str2>[0m
[1mExamples[0m
[1mRelated Information[0m

[1mName uiGet [22m- Retrieves the current value of the specified property of the ele-
       ment that is being queried
[1mSyntax uiGet [22m[-help] <name> [<property>] [-quiet]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that  includes  type  and  default
       information for each uiGet parameter. For a detailed description of the
       command and all of its parameters,  use  the  man  command:  man  uiGet
       [1m<name> [22mSpecifies as a string the name of the interface element you want
       to query. If multiple widgets are found with the same <name>, the first
       matched widget is queried. Returns an error if there is no element with
       the specified name. [1m<property> [22mSpecifies the property whose value is to
       be  retrieved.  You  can  specify  the  following properties: -before |
       -checked | -children | -command | -disabled | -dockwin |  -enablevar  |
       -foreground  |  -geometry  |  -icon | -in | -label | -menu | -message |
       -newline | -shortcut | -statusbar | -title  |  -toolbar  |  -tooltip  |
       -type  |  -underline  |  -value  |  -variable  | -visible | -visiblevar
       [1m-before <name> [22mWhen specified, returns the element that  occurs  before
       the  element identified by <name>. [1m-checked [22mReturns the on/off state of
       the specified check box or radio button. If the check box or radio but-
       ton  is  selected,  returns  true.  If it is deselected, returns false.
       [1m-children [22mReturns child elements of specified interface element.  Note:
       You  can  use  this  parameter with elements of type menu, submenu, and
       toolbar. [1m-command [22mReturns the Tcl command to be executed when the spec-

       parameter only with elements of type command, check, radio or  toolbut-
       ton.  [1m-disabled [22mWhen specified, returns whether the specified interface

       [1m-enablevar [22mRepresents the Tcl global variable for Enable status. [1m-fore-[0m
       [1mground [22mReturns the foreground color of the icon for the specified tool-
       button. Note: You can use the -foreground parameter only with  elements
       of  type  toolbutton.  [1m-geometry [22mReturns the width, height, and coordi-
       nates of the main window. Note: The -geometry parameter  is  applicable
       only  for  the  main window, which is type main. [1m-icon [22mReturns the file
       name of the specified toolbutton. Note: The -icon parameter is applica-
       ble  only  for elements of type toolbutton. [1m-in [22mReturns the name of the
       parent element. [1m-label [22mReturns the  label  of  the  specified  element.
       Note:  This parameter is NOT applicable for elements of type separator.
       [1m-menu [22mReturns the names of the menus in the  main  window.  Note:  This
       parameter  is  applicable only for the main window, which is type main.
       [1m-message [22mReturns the message on the status bar. Note: This parameter is
       applicable only for the status bar. [1m-newline [22mReturns whether or not the
       specified toolbar starts in a new row. Note: The -newline parameter  is
       applicable  only  for  elements  of type toolbar. [1m-shortcut [22mReturns the
       shortcut key for a command, check box,  radio  button,  or  toolbutton.
       Note:  You  can  use the -shortuct parameter only with elements of type
       command, check, radio, or toolbutton. [1m-statusbar [22mReturns  the  name  of
       the  main  window's status bar. Note: This parameter is applicable only
       for the main window (main). [1m-title [22mReturns the text on  the  main  win-
       dow's  title  bar. Note: This parameter is applicable only for the main
       window (main). [1m-toolbar [22mReturns the toolbars in  the  window.  [1m-tooltip[0m
       Returns the tooltip text for the specified toolbar or toolbutton. Note:
       The -tooltip parameter is applicable only for elements of type  toolbar
       and  toolbutton.  [1m-type  [22mReturns  the  type  of  the specified element.
       [1m-underline [22mReturns the integer index of the underlined character in the
       element  label.  Note:  The  -underline parameter is NOT applicable for
       elements of type toolbar, separator, and toolbutton. [1m-value [22mReturns the
       value  stored in the associated variable of the specified radio button.

       cal_instance_name>[-preserve_routes]

       default information for each undo_uniquify_partition parameter.  For  a

       [1mcal_instance_name>  [22mSpecifies name of the hierarchical instance that is
       used to bring back the recursion of cells in a netlist and restore  the
       master  and  clone  association.  Based  of  the  selected hierarchical
       instance, its cell (module) is identified. All other occurrences of the
       identified  cell  with  the same naming format ( cellname_<number>) are
       then renamed to the identified cell name. That means all instances will
       have  the  same  cell  name and definition again, thereby restoring the
       master and clone relationship. Note:

uniquify(21.15)                                                uniquify(21.15)



[1mName uniquify [22m- Supports regrouping of master-clone partitions inside the non-
       unique modules. This command uniquifies or regroups  the  master/clones
       (one master module used by two or more hinst clones) by creating unique
       modules for each hinst clone, as needed
[1mSyntax  uniquify  [22m[-help]  {[<design>  |  <module>]  |  -new_master  <hinsts>}
       [-exclude <modules>] [-verbose]
[1mParameters -help [22mPrints a brief description that includes the type and default
       information for each uniquify parameter. For a detailed description  of
       the  command  and all its parameters, use the man command: man uniquify
       [1m<design> | <module>   [22mRegroups the master/clones within the <design> or
       <module>  and  recursively  below  it. This assures that all the hinsts
       inside those would have their own unique module, except for the modules
       specified  using  the  -exclude  parameter. In case multiple hinsts are
       referenced to the specified module, those will remain as clones.  Type:
       Mandatory [1m-new_master <hinsts> [22mSplits the hinst clones of a master mod-
       ule into the clones of a new master. The new master is also  regrouped,
       except  for  the modules specified using the -exclude parameter. It may
       also happen that one of such hinst clones is forced to have a new  mas-
       ter  (refer to the Examples section). In case a hinst is not a clone of
       the same  module,  an  error  message  is  displayed.  Type:  Mandatory
       [1m-exclude <modules>   [22mExcludes the specified modules from unification or
       regrouping. Use this parameter if a specific sub-module is a partition,
       which  will  be implemented and shared only once. Type: Optional [1m[-ver-[0m
       [1mbose]   [22mReports the hinst clones (if any), which are  regrouped.  Type:
       Optional
[1mExamples[0m
                           Tue Aug 23 02:02:15 2022            uniquify(21.15)

[1mName  update_glitch  [22m-  Allows  you  to run glitch analysis without running SI
       delay analysis
[1mSyntax update_glitch [22m[-help] [-effort {medium | high}]
[1mParameters -help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes  type  and  default
       information  for  each update_glitch parameter. For a detailed descrip-
       tion of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man
       update_glitch.  [1m-effort  {medium | high} [22mSpecifies the effort level for
       update glitch. When set to high, glitch  analysis  uses  more  accurate
       modeling  of  glitch  for  small attackers, thereby reducing pessimism.
       Note: The run time in high mode may be slightly higher, and is  largely
       dependent on the distribution of coupling. Default: medium

update_module_model(21.15)                          update_module_model(21.15)



[1mName  update_module_model  [22m-  Invokes an independent session in interactive or
       batch mode at top-level design
[1mSyntax update_module_model [22m[-help] [-cpu  <number_of_cpus>]  [-distribute_job]
       [-eco_report]    [-log_dir    <dir_name>]    [-return_tag   <tag_name>]
       [-return_type {lef flexIlm  ilm  pnr}]  [-tag  <tag_name>]  {[-distrib-
       ute_run | -cell <cell_name>] [-interactive | -plugin_tcl <tcl_commands>
       | -gen_eco_only ]}
[1mParameters -cell <cell_name> [22mSpecifies which  cell  the  command  will  update
       changes.  Data_type:  string,  optional [1m-cpu <number_of_cpus> [22mSpecifies
       the number of CPUs that will be used for the  independent  session.  By
       default  it  uses  the same of number of CPUs as its parent. Data_type:
       int, optional [1m-distribute_job [22mEnables distributed processing where more
       than one block design can be run in parallel. Data_type: bool, optional
       [1m-distribute_run [22mEnables you to execute all  the  specified  update_mod-
       ule_model  distributed jobs using a Makefile. Data_type: bool, optional
       [1m-eco_report   [22mSpecifies the output report file that  contains  the  ECO
       change  information.  Data_type: bool, optional [1m-gen_eco_only [22mGenerates
       an eco file that contains general netlist ECO  and  placement  changes.
       This mode allows you to explicitly review the ECO before applying it to
       the block DB. (<Image> To view the image, refer  to  the  Innovus  Text
       Command  Reference  -  Release  21.1 manual.) Data_type: bool, optional
       [1m-help [22mOutputs a brief description that includes the  type  and  default
       information  for  each  update_module_model  parameter.  For a detailed
       description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man  com-
       mand:  man  update_module_model [1m-interactive   [22mInvokes independent ses-
       sion in interactive mode. Data_type: bool, optional [1m-log_dir <dir_name>[0m
       Specifies  the  log  file  directory  name. Data_type: string, optional
       [1m-plugin_tcl <tcl_commands>   [22mSpecifies the TCL commands to be run in  a
       batch  independent  session.  Data_type:  string,  optional [1m-return_tag[0m
       [1m<tag_name> [22mSpecifies the tag name that will be used to update the spec-
       ified  cell  model at the top-level design. Default: The default return
       tag is the tag name of the  current  loaded  block  design.  Data_type:
       string, optional [1m-return_type {flexIlm ilm lef pnr} [22mSpecifies the model
       type to be brought back to top-level design. The  return  type  can  be
       lef,  flexIlm, ilm, or pnr. Default: lef Data_type: enum, optional [1m-tag[0m
       [1m<tag_name> [22mAllows you to explicitly specify the tag name  of  the  cell
       pnr  model  that  will  be  loaded.  If  a  tag  is  not specified, the
       update_module_model command loads the pnr model of the  same  tag  with
       the currently loaded design (restore_module_model). For example, if the
       currently loaded design has tag init, then the update_module_model com-
       mand  will  load  the  pnr model of tag init for the specified cell. It
       will display an error if the tag is not available.  Data_type:  string,
       optional
[1mExample[0m
